<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont rallies Tories on VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government secured a majority of 25 in the Commons last night for its
controversial proposal to extend value added tax to domestic fuel from April
of next year. The government's majority of seats over all other parties is
20.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, won congratulations from cabinet
colleagues and Tory backbenchers when he wound up the four-day Budget debate
with a hard-hitting speech which appeared to have strengthened his hold on
the chancellorship.
Earlier Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, alleged that the government had
deliberately massaged downwards its pre-election forecasts of public
borrowing.
Drawing on a report first published in the Financial Times last autumn Mr
Brown demanded publication of internal Treasury documents showing that the
chancellor had rejected as too high his officials' first forecast of the
public-sector borrowing requirement. In a rowdy end to the debate Mr Lamont
refused to be intimidated by persistent Labour barracking in support of
demands that all retirement pensioners should be compensated in full for the
increase in fuel charges resulting from the VAT levy.
He ruled out such across-the-board payments, reaffirming that relief planned
by the government through increased income support would be targeted on
those most in need. To government cheers he insisted: 'This party has an
excellent record in helping the worst-off'.
Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister, was among several Tory
backbenchers who pressed for more generous compensation covering categories
marginally above entitlement to income support.
He stressed that those 'just above' the qualifying level for income support
would also be hard hit by the new impost.
The VAT resolution was carried by 303 votes to 278, with the numbers passing
through the government lobby three short of the total (306) which enabled it
to secure a majority of 27 to beat off an opposition challenge to the entire
Budget package.
Mr Nicholas Winterton (C Macclesfield) and Mr William Powell (C Corby)
abstained in the VAT vote, when the government's majority fell to 25. Mr
Michael Alison (C Selby) did not vote.
The chancellor vigorously rebutted charges that the tax increases imposed in
the Budget amounted to a betrayal of election promises by insisting that its
commitment to 'sound finances and low direct taxation' took priority.
</TEXT>
