<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems cool over Labour
Maastricht plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECTS of as many as six more government defeats on the Maastricht
bill appeared to be receding last night as senior Liberal Democrats
indicated they were unlikely to support a string of non-wrecking Labour
amendments.
But government whips were still left facing a stormy passage when the bill
returns for detailed Commons consideration tomorrow.
At least two further Labour amendments - including its attempt to remove the
protocol containing Britain's social chapter opt-out - were expected to
secure Liberal Democrat support, making government defeats likely.
Meanwhile, government hopes of speeding up the passage of the bill by
carrying procedural motions extending debate into the small hours were also
looking forlorn. By what are thought to be the Tory whips' own calculations,
the government could still be some 20 short of the votes necessary to do
this, even when the Liberal Democrats agree to side with them.
Two weeks ago, the government suffered its first Commons defeat on any issue
for about three years when MPs supported a minor Labour amendment to the
Maastricht bill by a margin of 22 votes. And it suffered a fresh humiliation
when the bill was last debated on March 12, deciding against calling a vote
to extend the sitting after 10pm, despite hinting heavily that it planned to
do so.
The non-wrecking Labour amendments - which mainly focus on increasing the
accountability to parliament of various European institutions and the Bank
of England - could conceivably secure enough support to be carried even
without the Lib Dems.
But not all the 50 Tory rebels who government whips expect to vote against
or abstain on procedural motions would be likely to rebel over these
amendments. Hard-core rebels are expected to meet today to discuss tactics.
The Liberal Democrats are not expected to decide on strategy until tomorrow.
The party is believed to be leaning towards the view that Labour's accent on
accountability risks distracting attention from the issue of how best to
make European institutions more democratic.
</TEXT>
