<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Inflation distortions under attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES WILL be required to eliminate distortions in their accounts caused
by foreign currency transactions in high-inflation countries under draft
regulations from the Accounting Standards Board.
A proposed consensus from the board's urgent-issues task force recommends
that companies operating in hyper-inflationary economies should remove
distortions before incorporating the figures into consolidated accounts.
They may either adjust the local currency financial statements to reflect
current price levels or use a relatively stable currency to measure the
foreign operations.
The proposed regulations are out for consultation and are likely to be
approved after the next meeting of the task force on May 12. If so they
would become mandatory soon after.
In an information sheet circulated to preparers of accounts the task force
also said it was seeking legal advice on requiring companies to mark their
current investment assets to market.
The proposals would require companies to show at market value their highly
liquid and readily marketable investments held as current assets, in the way
already adopted by marketmakers and other investment dealers.
Insurance companies will be temporarily exempt from some of the requirements
of FRS 3, the new profit-and-loss accounting standard, under draft
guidelines issued by the Accounting Standards Board yesterday.
Following pressure from the insurance industry the board has said that the
sector will not have to calculate gains and losses on disposals of
investments by reference to the amount at which they are carried in the
balance sheet.
The proposals, contained in Fred 5, a financial reporting exposure draft,
are out for consultation until the end of April. They have been inspired by
new European Community legislation.
</TEXT>
