<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Violent search for a settlement at Timex: The confrontation
which has followed the sacking of 320 workers in Dundee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VIOLENT scenes yesterday outside the Timex circuit-board plant in Dundee
are indicative of the mounting anger among the 320 strikers who were
dismissed by the US-owned company last month, and who are determined to win
their jobs back.
But they also demonstrate how the workers' cause has been taken up by
far-left political groups such as Militant Tendency and the Socialist
Workers Party. Their presence is an embarrassment to the AEEU engineering
union, which represents the workers.
Mr John Kydd, senior shop steward at Timex, said: 'The company will either
have to take us all back or close the plant down for good.' Mr Jimmy Airlie,
the union's Scottish executive officer said: 'We cannot allow any company to
behave in the way that Timex has done and get away with it.'
Just over four weeks ago Timex sacked all the workers at the plant -
although those who had been in dispute for 21 days had agreed to go back to
work under protest.
What was even more surprising to some was Timex's decision to sack employees
who had worked through the original strike.
Mr Peter Hall, Timex's UK president, said this was necessary to prevent
legal action by individual workers over imposed changes in their employment
contracts. But the move did little to calm the labour force.
The ferocity of the strike has taken the normally conciliatory union by
surprise. Union officials emphasise their moderate tradition by pointing out
that it was the AEEU which wanted a single-union deal with Ford when the
company considered building a plant in Dundee five years ago.
Union officials said that from the start they had tried to negotiate a
compromise but Timex had shown no interest.
The Timex president said: 'The dispute is over as far as the company is
concerned.'
Timex has sought to use the courts to end the dispute. Initially it secured
an interdict - equivalent to an injunction - to limit the number of pickets
outside its gates to six.
But the company's subsequent attempts to tighten the legal restrictions on
the strikers have proved less successful. It failed to prevent the 320
former employees from taking part in picketing, and last week the Court of
Session in Edinburgh rejected a submission that the union was causing a
disturbance by holding marches and demonstrations outside the plant.
Some of the strike leaders still face an attempt by the company to have them
jailed for alleged breaches of the original interdict. The union says it has
withdrawn its legal representation of the leaders for fear of opening its
funds to civil damages.
With unemployment in Dundee above 10 per cent, the company says it is not
encountering difficulties in hiring a new workforce.
It insists that its competitive position required drastic action and says
falling demand meant it needed to cut costs and reduce production.
Timex negotiated with the union for two months. Senior executives from its
Connecticut headquarters flew to Britain in mid-February to seek a deal.
The workforce was asked to accept a 12-month pay freeze, a 10 per cent cut
in benefits including pension rights and a lay-off rota for six months with
access to independent arbitration in case of problems.
Timex told the union that it intended to extend production in the second
half of the year and recruit a further 300 workers. But when the workers
refused to accept the package, the company lost patience.
The violent scenes yesterday outside the Dundee plant are certainly not
wanted by the AEEU, which would like nothing better than a quick and
amicable end to what it sees as an unnecessary conflict. Its wish does not
seem likely to be granted.
</TEXT>
