<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Private cash urged for council homes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE-SECTOR capital could be used to modernise local-authority housing
stock if councils transferred ownership of their estates to arms-length
housing companies, says a report published yesterday by the Joseph Rowntree
Foundation, the social research organisation.
The report says that transferring council estates to local housing companies
would allow funds to be raised on the capital markets without increasing the
public sector borrowing requirement. The move could produce savings in
public expenditure of Pounds 16bn for the Treasury, releasing funds for
building affordable rented accommodation.
Sir George Young, the housing minister, welcomed the report and promised the
environment department would examine it 'with great care'. He warned,
however, that any new approach would have to be attractive to tenants and
investors, as well as local authorities and the government. The Rowntree
report investigates ways in which local authorities could borrow against the
security of their housing stock to modernise and repair council homes.
At present such borrowing counts towards the public sector borrowing
requirement and is therefore controlled by the Treasury.
Nineteen councils have arranged to transfer their estates to housing
associations which can borrow outside the PSBR. Many, however - especially
in inner cities - cannot do this because the current value of their housing
stock is less than the debt outstanding on it.
Councils would retain a non-controlling interest, with tenants'
representatives on the boards.
Local Housing Companies. Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End, York YO3
6LP. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
