<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Trade deficit with non-EC countries widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S TRADE deficit with countries outside the European Community
widened sharply last month, raising fears about structural problems in the
economy as it emerges from the recession.
The visible trade deficit deteriorated by Pounds 274m in February to Pounds
1.3bn, the second-biggest monthly deficit on record. The value of imports
and exports reached record highs.
The seasonally adjusted figures from the Central Statistical Office showed
that import prices rose 2.25 per cent in February against a 0.5 per cent
rise in export prices.
The most widely used measure of underlying trends showed that while import
and export volumes reached record highs, imports continued to grow faster
than exports on a three-monthly basis.
The trade deficit was expected to rise for a while after devaluation because
of the higher cost of imports. But yesterday's figures showed that import
volumes excluding oil and erratic items such as aircraft and precious stones
have also risen. They rose 6 per cent in the past three months compared with
the three months to November. Exports rose 4.5 per cent in the same period.
Although the fall in the pound has made foreign goods more expensive the
trend continued last month. Underlying import volumes rose 3.2 per cent from
the previous month compared with a 1 per cent increase in underlying
exports.
The higher import volumes may reflect a rise in economic activity as
manufacturers increase orders for foreign components and raw materials.
The poor performance of non-EC trade comes in spite of the improving
economic outlook in north America. The value of exports to the US and Canada
rose 8.5 per cent in the latest three months compared with the three months
to November, but imports in the same period rose 22 per cent. The balance of
trade with north America was nonetheless healthier than a year ago.
The deficit with Western Europe excluding the EC also widened. Import values
rose 13 per cent in the latest three months compared with export growth of 5
per cent.
Mr Robert Lind, an economist at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said: 'Strengthening
economic recovery in North America compares with dismal recessionary forces
in the major EC economies. We might have expected the UK's trade performance
with countries outside the EC to have reflected this.'
The figures show that export growth has been concentrated in basic materials
in recent months, although the CSO pointed out that this mainly reflected a
large consignment of industrial diamonds that left the country in February.
Export volumes of manufactured goods rose 3 per cent in the three months to
the end of February compared with the previous three months.
The deficit in oil narrowed to Pounds 110m in February compared with Pounds
135m in January.
The erratics deficit deteriorated to Pounds 320m from Pounds 128m and as a
result the underlying visible trade deficit, which excludes both oil and
erratics, also widened to Pounds 904m from Pounds 797m in January.
