<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Ministers 'missed chance' on NHS pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ERIC CAINES, the personnel director of the National Health Service, said
yesterday government ministers and managers of new National Health Service
trusts had failed to grasp a unique opportunity to abolish central pay
mechanisms and improve performance in the service.
Mr Caines, who leaves the NHS next week, took a keen interest in the
abolition of central mechanisms for pay and terms of employment and the
introduction of local trust-based bargaining.
Only a handful of NHS trusts have moved in this direction and the government
has not abolished central machinery, including pay review bodies and the
Whitley council.
Trusts give several reasons for staying within their remit, including the
need to concentrate on more immediate practical problems.
Mr Caines, in a final salvo against NHS managers and ministers, said in an
interview in Personnel Today that one of the most important areas needing
attention when the first NHS trusts were set up was to devise trust-based
reward systems balancing fair pay and the need for flexibility in work
practices.
He said: 'Unfortunately - and it grieves me to say this - the NHS has almost
certainly passed up the best, indeed the only opportunity it has ever had to
make fundamental changes in these areas.'
Managers, he said, had failed to see the billions of pounds spent on pay as
a key management tool.
Unions representing hospital workers said yesterday they had rejected
suggestions by two trusts, Hillingdon in Middlesex and Redbridge in Essex,
to forego the 1.5 per cent pay increase this year.
</TEXT>
