<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Setbacks to spending curb on legal aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S proposals for curbing the rise in legal-aid spending
suffered two setbacks yesterday.
The Law Society won leave in the High Court to challenge the proposal of
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, to replace hourly-based fees with standard
fees for criminal legal-aid work in magistrates' courts.
The Commons home affairs committee said the Lord Chancellor's plans to cut
legal aid eligibility would deprive people access to justice. The MPs called
for a full day's debate in the Commons on Lord Mackay's proposals.
The High Court was told that Lord Mackay's decision to introduce standard
fees went against the principle in the 1988 Legal Aid Act that a solicitor
would receive 'fair remuneration' for a case.
Mr Michael Beloff, QC for the society, said Lord Mackay's 'desire for
economy' had overridden the need to act both lawfully and rationally.
The regulations relating to standard fees are due for implementation on June
1. Granting the society leave for an urgent hearing, Mr Justice Macpherson
said: 'I firmly believe there is a case which should be argued. It is most
unfortunate that there should be litigation between the largest of the two
branches of the law and the head of the judiciary.'
The Commons home affairs committee report said the proposed cuts in legal
aid eligibility, designed to save Pounds 43m in the legal aid budget in
1993-94, Pounds 110m in 1994-95 and Pounds 175m in 1995-96, should have been
preceded by a cost-benefit analysis of their effect across the range of
public spending.
MPs say it is important to determine why legal-aid costs are rising so
rapidly. This must be complemented by an inquiry into the scope for savings
and efficiency gains in the way legal services are delivered and courts run.
They call for a government commitment to restore the eligibility cuts in
real terms once other savings are found.
They also recommend that the plan to abolish free legal advice under the
green form scheme for those with a disposable income of more than Pounds 61
a week should be changed to allow those with disposable income just above
that figure to continue to receive advice with a contribution.
The government has already taken a decision to retain the contributory green
form scheme in Scotland and MPs say they see no justification for treating
people in England and Wales differently.
</TEXT>
