<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / George Walker switches tack in bankruptcy fight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GEORGE WALKER, the former chairman and chief executive of Brent Walker,
the property and leisure group, is back fighting moves by his creditors to
have him declared bankrupt.
Only two weeks ago Mr Walker, who faces claims from his creditors for up to
Pounds 180m, made his own application to be made bankrupt. The move was to
enable him to qualify for legal aid in his defence against theft charges
involving Pounds 12.5m brought by the Serious Fraud Office.
Having overcome the problem which prevented him getting legal aid for his
trial, he yesterday dropped his bankruptcy application - but found himself
facing a fresh petition from his creditors.
The creditors say Mr Walker has breached the individual voluntary
arrangement (IVA) he reached with them last September to repay his debt
without being declared bankrupt. The IVA had been agreed after a narrow vote
in the face of opposition from the banks, who continued to argue for Mr
Walker's bankruptcy.
At a High Court hearing yesterday the supervisors of the IVA said the
agreement had been breached because Mr Walker's wife, Jean, was not now
intending to pay for civil litigation against Brent Walker. These actions
might have increased the amount of money available to be repaid to
creditors.
Lawyers for the supervisors claimed that Mr Walker's solicitor had told them
that Mrs Walker now intended to spend her money supporting her husband's
defence for his criminal trial. Mr Walker's solicitor, Mr Michael Coleman,
denies such a conversation took place.
The bankruptcy petition was supported by two of Mr Walker's largest
creditors - a group of banks led by the TSB, and the Inland Revenue, to whom
Mr Walker owes Pounds 40m.
Mr Martin Pascoe, for the banks, said Mr Walker was now seeking to escape
from the conditions imposed by the IVA. Mr Robin Hollington, for Mr Walker,
opposed the bankruptcy petition, saying it was a 'draconian' measure. The
hearing was adjourned until April 2.
Mr Walker had originally been refused legal aid for his trial because the
Legal Aid Board ruled that his assets, although pledged to creditors through
the IVA, were still technically his. A magistrate overruled this decision
last week.
If the bankruptcy order against Mr Walker was granted, he would become
Britain's second-biggest bankrupt after Mr Kevin Maxwell, against whom
claims exceeding Pounds 400m have been made.
</TEXT>
