<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Consumer optimism rising, says poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE ABOUT the general economic situation has risen slightly this
month, but pessimists continue to outweigh optimists, the latest Gallup
survey of consumer confidence showed yesterday, Emma Tucker writes.
The survey, conducted in the first two weeks of the month, found that 40 per
cent of the 2,025 adults sampled believed the economic situation would
worsen over the next 12 months against 27 per cent who believed it would
improve. The difference between the two figures was one of the lowest since
July last year.
Twenty-six per cent expected their household's financial position to worsen
this year while 20 per cent expected it to improve.
The results of the survey point to a fragile improvement in consumer
confidence, but it is too early to judge the impact of the Budget on
sentiment.
Fear of unemployment continues to damp optimism, however, with 76 per cent
of the survey's respondents expecting unemployment to rise in the 12 months
ahead.
</TEXT>
