<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Scots schools 'fail in basic skills'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SCOTTISH education system, although widely recognised as good, is
failing too many children by not teaching them basic skills, Mr Ian Lang,
Scottish secretary, said yesterday.
Large numbers of young Scots were leaving school unable to read or write, or
add up, he said in a speech to Conservatives in Aberdeen.
'They don't even have the tools to do the jobs of yesterday, never mind
tomorrow.'
He said calls for a period of calm to digest recent changes were
understandable but they could not be allowed to stand in the way of the need
for change to achieve higher standards.
Teaching had to return to the backbones of education of the past -
'spelling, punctuation, grammar, arithmetic'.
Assessment by regular testing was essential, in spite of the 'overblown
rhetoric' of its critics, he said.
Mr Lang said the policy outlined last year and broadly accepted by the
teaching profession, provided for pupils aged between five and 14 to be
tested five times in reading, writing and mathematics when the teacher
judged them to be ready to 'negotiate the test successfully'.
He highlighted the problem of truancy and said that each school's truancy
performance would be recorded for 1993-94 and included in the school's
handbook from the following year.
He reminded education authorities that they had the power to prosecute
parents who did not ensure that their children went to school.
Mr Lang said that school boards - the equivalent of boards of governors in
England - which were introduced in the late 1980s by Mr Michael Forsyth,
then Scottish education minister, were 'frankly, of varying quality'.
Many still lacked self-confidence or were less interested than they might
be.
</TEXT>
