<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Mexico City calls for a mayor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A LARGE majority of voters support moves towards greater democracy,
according to a plebiscite carried out in Mexico City.
In an attempt to put pressure on the Mexican government to accept an elected
mayor of Mexico City, more than 300,000 city residents voted on Sunday in a
plebiscite on the capital's political future.
Preliminary figures showed that among the 10 per cent of those eligible who
voted, 85 per cent favour the election of a mayor of Mexico City, 84 per
cent supported a local Congress with legislative power, and 66 per cent
approved of turning Mexico City into the country's 32nd state.
The poll was organised by a disparate group of democratic activists from all
the main political parties and civic organisations. It was intended to
highlight discontent with the lack of democracy in Mexico's business,
cultural and political capital - and indirectly in all Mexico. Those in
favour of plebiscite hoped to counter an argument, supported by many in the
Mexican government, that there was limited public interest in democratic
reform.
The organisational success of the plebiscite, and the overwhelming support
for the propositions, lends some credence to the argument of the democratic
activists. However, a turnout of 10 per cent was lower than the organisers
had hoped for.
For the most part the initiative had been frowned upon by Mexico's ruling
Institutional Revolutionary party, and received only lukewarm support from
the current, unelected mayor, Mr Manuel Camacho.
The Mayor of Mexico City is now picked by the president, while the local
assembly has no power to write legislation.
</TEXT>
