<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Mexico ponders price it must pay for Nafta
 -Side accords demanded by the US raise some thorny issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN President Carlos Salinas is asked about the side agreements on labour,
the environment and import surges which it is proposed to attach to the
North American Free Trade Agreement, he has a stock answer. They must not,
he says, be in conflict with the text of the basic accord; violate the
sovereignty of the negotiating countries; nor be protectionist.
Unfortunately for Mr Salinas (and Canada, which shares most Mexican
concerns), many of the proposals raised by the Clinton administration and,
above all, by US congressmen look to break all three conditions.
The side agreement on import surges would have to conflict with Nafta as the
latter already contains safeguards for industries affected by such surges.
The proposal to impose trade sanctions on companies that fail to comply with
environment and labour laws could expose thousands of Mexican companies to
endless complaints, and turn Nafta into a protectionist's charter.
The US proposal for trilateral commissions on labour and the environment
would, if they had any power, reek of interventionism.
However, given the Mexican government's desire to have Nafta passed as
quickly as possible by all three legislatures, it is sure to make
significant concessions. The question is which conditions are flexible, and
which are matters of principle.
The government has already accepted, albeit reluctantly, the principle of
negotiations on import surges. Indeed, the real aim of insisting side
agreements be consistent with the Nafta text was probably to avoid the US
administration opening up specific sectoral agreements - such as on sugar or
glass, or other areas where US businesses feel hard done by. Such a
reopening of Nafta would have delayed ratification, and could have caused
the whole treaty to unravel.
The question of sovereignty is the most tricky, for non-intervention in
other countries' affairs has been the cardinal principal of Mexican foreign
policy for 50 years, and a form of intellectual self-defence against US
interference.
But it is undeniable that Mexico has already sacrificed considerable
sovereignty in agreeing to many of the provisions in Nafta. Indeed the
attraction of Nafta for many government officials was precisely that it
would tie the hands of the current and future governments with respect to
tariffs, investment laws, and other parts of economic policy, and thus
restrict sovereignty in an area where Mexican governments had been none too
successful.
Under Nafta, for example, Mexico agrees to abide by the resolutions of
trilateral panels in trade disputes - a clear infringement of sovereignty as
traditionally defined in Mexico. It agrees not to ease environmental
regulations to attract investment; to harmonise norms and standards with the
US and Canada; set, in effect, an external sugar tariff equal to that of the
US, and so on.
As such, common rules on the environment and labour, and trilateral
commissions, would not by themselves violate any new principles of
sovereignty. Mr Jorge Castaneda, a visiting professor at Princeton
University and vocal critic of the Mexican government, says: 'I see no
reason why Mexico should abdicate sovereignty on intellectual property
rights and investment and not on labour and the environment.'
However, there is, as Mr Castaneda himself admits, one important difference:
abdicating sovereignty on investment and property rights will attract
capital and stimulate growth; abdicating sovereignty on labour and the
environment is likely to do the opposite. The government will, in the words
of one official, oppose measures that 'do not make economic sense': that is,
social regulations so onerous they could limit growth.
Direct enforcement of Mexican labour and environmental laws by the US is
unlikely to be the main stumbling block. As Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, has pointed out, the US could not tolerate Mexico helping
enforce US laws, so it could hardly create environment and labour
commissions that let Americans enforce Mexican laws.
Instead, the three countries will look for mechanisms to force each to
comply with labour and environmental conditions in Nafta, according to Mr
Luis Miguel Diaz, legal director in Mexico's foreign relations ministry, and
a side agreement negotiator.
Talks on labour and environment, says Mr Diaz, will follow the same logic as
those on the economic text of Nafta - that they will be co-operative
agreements which in effect compel each country to adapt domestic laws. 'The
limit of the negotiations is that national authorities remain national
authorities, but there will be a system to make countries respond to the
regulations laid out in Nafta.'
The concern for Mexico and Canada is that this 'system' could become
protectionist. The US has proposed giving the trilateral panels power to
impose trade sanctions against a company that fails to comply with its
national environmental and labour laws - sanctions, as it were, that would
punish social dumping.
This could turn into an excuse for US companies to defend themselves against
cheap Mexican exports by claiming the exporting companies did not fully
comply with Mexico's labour and environment laws. Such proposals could
restrict access to the US market, and undo some of the economic benefits of
Nafta for Mexico.
US brewer in Mexican deal, Page 23
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    MXZ  Mexico.
</CN>
