<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / World Trade News: EC envoys move quickly after US trade
offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO TOP EC trade negotiators will today try to capitalise on the temporary
ceasefire with the US and make fresh progress on the Gatt Uruguay Round
talks.
Mr Hugo Paemen, the EC's chief trade negotiator, and Mr Thinh Van Tran, EC
ambassador to the Gatt talks in Geneva, will meet their US counterparts in
Washington - three days after the Clinton administration agreed to suspend
sanctions in an escalating dispute over public procurement contracts.
A senior Brussels official said the administration had also offered
encouraging signals by stating for the first time in public that it wants to
make a 'substantial' market access package on goods and services a priority
in the renewed negotiations on a Gatt agreement. 'The statement was exactly
what we had been looking for,' said the official.
The new products in goods and services, suggested by both the US and the EC,
have been added to the this week's US-EC market access negotiations, in the
hopes that agreement will help 'jumpstart' the Gatt negotiations in time to
wrap up the round by the end of the year.
Indications that the market access talks would be broadened came on Friday,
when President Clinton told EC Commission President Jacques Delors that he
would delay sanctions set to go into effect yesterday in the dispute over
government procurement. In a joint US-EC statement, the EC promised 'to
address constructively US concerns'.
Mr Harry Freeman, a Washington trade lobbyist, said the stress on market
access reverses the emphasis in the Gatt negotiations from 'the new issues'
 -such as services and intellectual property rights - to tariff cutting in a
move designed to broaden domestic political support for the Uruguay Round.
The sanctions delay put Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, on
the defensive. He had suggested to Congress that, unlike his predecessors,
he would not back away from threats of retaliation.
Questioned about the administration's change of heart on weekend television,
he said: 'President Delors came to us and asked that we delay it. . .
because he had some constructive suggestions in order to try to meet our
concerns.'
The encouraging signals came after Mr Jacques Delors, met President Bill
Clinton for 50 minutes at the White House and warned him that US sanctions
would provoke a very negative response in Europe. After the warning, the
Commission president was invited to hold talks with Mr Kantor.
In Brussels yesterday, officials were still assessing the motives behind the
suspension of trade sanctions which were due to go into effect yesterday. A
spokesman for Mr Delors said the moves did not necessarily signal a less
aggressive US trade policy. 'We are dealing with signals rather than
certainties.'
The visit of Mr Paemen and Mr Van Tran aims to lay the groundwork for next
week's talks in Brussels between Mr Kantor and Sir Leon Brittan, EC
commissioner responsible for external trade relations.
These talks have become a critical test not only of EC/US intentions to
narrow differences on Gatt but also whether they can resolve a series of
nagging bilateral disputes including aviation subsidies, steel trade and
government procurement.
EC officials said yesterday that they hoped the US will consider favourably
the proposal for a joint study of the US and EC disagreements over access to
their res-pective government procurement markets.
</TEXT>
