<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Japanese caution on chip target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO and AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE INCREASE in foreign suppliers' share in the Japanese semiconductor
market to more than 20 per cent in the fourth quarter of last year has been
welcomed in Japan.
However, Mr Nobuo Kanoi, chairman of the Users Committee of Foreign
Semiconductors, cautioned against relying on short-term market share
figures. While the increased market share was a positive development, it was
important to focus on stable long-term business relationships, he said.
'In the future, as in the past, the global economic environment and
fluctuating exchange rates can influence short-term market share figures. It
is important not to become overly optimistic when the quarterly numbers rise
or overly pessimistic when they do not,' Mr Kanoi said.
Important progress has been made in industrial co-operation. Japan's 10
largest semiconductor users, for example, had prepared 'inquiry lists' as
tools for foreign suppliers to formulate order forecasts.
'No one can deny that the Japanese market is 100 per cent open, or that
tremendous progress has been made to date in improving business
opportunities. . . ,' Mr Kanoi said.
A senior official of Japan's Trade Ministry said yesterday that Japan did
not plan to set market-share targets for foreign goods in any sector beyond
semiconductors, AP-DJ reports from Tokyo.
Mr Yuji Tanahashi, vice-minister for administrative affairs at the Ministry
of International Trade and Industry, was speaking after Mr Mickey Kantor, US
trade representative, was quoted as saying the market-share goals might need
to be expanded to other sectors.
The bilateral semiconductor agreement is the only significant trade pact to
set specific targets for a share of the Japanese market. Officials have said
the agreement invited misunderstanding and should not be copied in other
sectors.
