<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Algerians protest at growing terrorism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ESTIMATED 80,000 Algerians marched through the centre of Algiers
yesterday to protest against the growing wave of terrorism sweeping the
country.
Similar marches were being held nationwide, called by politicians, trade
unionists, employers, doctors, women's groups and other associations.
'Neither Tehran nor Khartoum,' shouted the crowd, referring to two capitals
which Algerian leaders and the press have often accused over the past year
of sheltering and helping radical Islamic groups.
The government closed state companies and bussed in thousands of employees
to join the Algiers demonstration. But some in the crowd shouted
anti-government slogans.
The wave of repression and terrorism which followed the cancellation, 14
months ago, of elections that the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) was poised
to win, has claimed more than 1,000 victims among the security forces and
the fundamentalists.
The terrorism took a new turn last week when two senior civilians and a
surgeon were killed and a fourth just escaped with his life.
Until now, radical Moslem groups have not targeted civilians, even those
associated with the government.
Despite the mounting violence, the High State Council (HCE), Algeria's five
man collegiate presidency, has invited political parties to join in a
dialogue aimed at finding a common platform for discussions on a new
constitution.
The two moderate Islamic parties, Hamas and Nahda, and the former single
ruling party, the FLN, have indicated their readiness to talk. But the two
lay parties, the Front des Forces Socialistes and the Rassemblement pour la
Culture et la Democratie have declined.
</TEXT>
