<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / French Elections: Paris-Bonn axis faces pressure - A
conservative government will adopt a hard line in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CO-OPERATION between Paris and Bonn represents the traditional driving force
behind the development of the European Community. But the French
conservatives' crushing victory, underlining the unpopular effects of the
Socialist government's policy of linking the franc to the D-Mark, may pose
severe tests for Franco-German cohesion.
The likelihood that the new French government may toughen France's line on
the Gatt trade talks is injecting additional uncertainty into economic
policy questions.
There is also worry in Spain - which faces general elections in the autumn -
that the Socialists' rout may undermine the pro-European policies of Mr
Felipe Gonzalez, the Socialist prime minister.
Professor Michael Sturmer, director of the German foreign policy think-tank,
Stiftung Wissenschaft und Politik, said that France and Germany had no
option but to maintain strong ties: 'The French want to run European
policies, but they cannot do it on their own. And the Germans need someone
to lean on.' But the German Bundesbank could come under 'enormous pressure'
to head off the risk that the new French government might seek to sever the
franc/D-Mark parity.
Prof Sturmer said that he saw the need for 'plain speaking' by Bonn to the
prospective right-wing government, to emphasise the importance of a Gatt
trade deal.
There could be a 'trade-off' here affecting the Bundesbank's willingness to
cut interest rates to help the French economy, he suggested.
In Brussels, European Community officials said that the conservatives'
landslide might make France's European policies much less predictable. Most
senior European Commission officials believe the French opposition's pledge
to stick to the franc fort policy, but some Community officials worry that
strains caused by cohabitation between a weakened President Francois
Mitterrand and an assertive conservative government may reinforce the
present political drift in the EC.
'We may be in for a period of prolonged infighting,' said one senior
official in Brussels yesterday. There is anxiety in Brussels over the French
conservatives having pledged to re-open the EC-US farm trade deal, widely
viewed as the pre-requisite for a Gatt conclusion.
One view in Brussels is that Mr Jacques Chirac, the Gaullist RPR leader, may
provoke a Gatt crisis to strengthen his domestic position. This would be at
the expense of upsetting his EC partners, particularly Germany.
Speculation about the new French government's monetary policy difficulties
has coincided with fresh evidence of Bundesbank scepticism about the targets
agreed at Maastricht for economic and monetary union. Mr Helmut Schlesinger,
the Bundesbank president, yesterday emphasised Germany's own problems in
meeting the Emu fiscal objectives.
According to Mr Richard Reid, chief economist at Union Bank of Switzerland
in Frankfurt: 'The failure of the Socialists to win a single seat in the
first round does raise the question of whether there will be a reassessment
of the franc fort policy.'
Mr Matthys van der Want, chief economist at Pierson, Heldring, Pierson, the
Amsterdam merchant bank, said that he did not expect a 'weakening' of
Bonn-Paris links, especially since the Bundesbank is now in the midst of a
process of gradual interest rate cuts.
However, he added that France would run into problems unless the Bundesbank
cut its benchmark interest rates by at least a further two percentage points
by the fourth quarter. In view of the strong links between the French and
Spanish Socialist parties, the result sent a nervous ripple through the
Madrid government.
'The French result will affect the Spanish government in that it may force
it to change its strict fiscal and monetary policies,' said Mr Joaquin
Tamames, a leading Madrid business consultant.
Like many analysts, Mr Tamames believes the government is already softening
its economic policy position in the face of polls showing the Socialists
rapidly losing ground to their conservative opponents.
On the other hand, Professor Pedro Schwartz, one of Spain's leading liberal
economists, said he believed the French vote would not move Mr Gonzalez. 'I
don't think he can win any votes by walking away from his policies.'
He added that Mr Gonzalez would be most helped by a crisis in Russia or in
the EC . 'That would set Spaniards looking for a safe pair of hands rather
than for change,' he said.
Reports by Lionel Barber in Brussels, Peter Bruce in Madrid, David Marsh in
London, and Christopher Parkes in Frankfurt
</TEXT>
