<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / French Elections: Business looks for swift interest rate
cuts - This would aid the new government in implementing its privatisation
plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEADLINE emblazoned across yesterday's La Tribune Desfosses, the French
financial newspaper, was short and to the point: 'New government - the
business community expects swift, spectacular policies'.
The chief concern of French financiers and industrialists is how quickly the
conservatives, now set to return to power after a resounding victory in the
first round of the parliamentary elections, will be able to reduce interest
rates.
They are keen for the new government to implement the privatisation
programme outlined in its election manifesto. There is also feverish
speculation as to whether the right will continue the Gallic political
tradition of dismissing the Socialist chairmen of France's state-controlled
companies.
However, the immediate priority for the corporate sector is interest rates.
The Socialists refused to reduce rates for fear of imperilling the French
franc, preferring to wait for German rates to fall so that France could
follow suit without jeopardising the currency.
As a result, French companies face the parallel problems of high interest
rates depressing domestic demand and the strong franc impeding their export
efforts.
The conservatives claimed to be committed to continuing the franc fort
policy in their election manifesto. However, rogue voices in both parties -
Mr Charles Pasqua and Mr Philippe Seguin in the RPR and Mr Alain Madelin in
the UDF - have argued for devaluation.
'The markets are still waiting for a firm commitment that the new government
will adhere to the franc fort,' said Mr Jean-Francois Mercier, chief French
economist at Salomon Brothers. 'There is also concern that, if German rates
have not come down significantly by the summer, the calls for devaluation
from the conservatives will grow louder.'
A reduction in interest rates is also essential if the conservatives are to
implement their privatisation plans. High rates will make it more difficult
to encourage private investors to buy equities. The new administration also
faces the problem that the Paris stock market is now far less buoyant than
in 1986, when the right last took power.
The conservatives hope to stimulate equity investment by introducing tax
breaks, possibly for long-term investments of up to FFr50,000 (Pounds
6,273). James Capel in Paris calculates that this could bring FFr50bn of new
private investment into the stock market each year. The new government may
also consider abolishing the Bourse tax on equity investment.
'Although market conditions are less favourable than in 1986, there is no
reason that the first tranche of privatisations should not start in early
summer,' said Mr David Harrington, French market strategist at James Capel.
'It is partly a question of pragmatics. The conservatives need to raise
money to plug the budget deficit.'
The critical question is which companies will go first. Some candidates are
too sickly to be privatised at present, notably Credit Lyonnais, the bank
which last year produced its worst performance for two decades, and Bull,
the computer group that has for four years been in the red. Analysts suspect
that the new government will start with more robust businesses such as
Assurances Generales de France in insurance and Rhone-Poulenc in chemicals.
The conservatives may also adopt a different approach to the management of
the remaining state companies, by encouraging them to float off subsidiaries
and being more relaxed about job losses.
There is also speculation that they might renegotiate the recent acquisition
of Yves Saint-Laurent, the fashion house headed by Mr Pierre Berge, a close
friend of President Francois Mitterrand, by part of Elf-Aquitaine, the
public sector oil group. The deal, due to be completed in May, has been
fiercely criticised by the right.
One of the first tasks of the new administration will be to scrutinise the
heads of the state-controlled companies. Mr Loi Le Floch-Prigent of
Elf-Aquitaine, Mr Jean-Yves Haberer of Credit Lyonnais and Mr Gilles Menage
of Electricite de France are all seen as vulnerable.
They may yet be safe. Mr Edouard Balladur, favourite for prime minister, has
already said he does not relish the prospect of a corporate witch-hunt.
</TEXT>
