<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / French Elections: Right aims for Louis XVI presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
YOU would have to go back into early 19th century French history to find a
comparable conservative majority, if France's centre-right parties were to
achieve in next Sunday's run-off elections for the National Assembly the
maximum projected for them as a result of last Sunday's first ballot.
The top limit of the range of seats predicted for the neo-Gaullist
Republican Rally (RPR) and centre-right Union for French Democracy (UDF) is
480 seats out of the 577 total. That, said one commentator yesterday, would
leave President Francois Mitterrand with 'as much authority as Louis XVI'
after he was brought back to revolutionary Paris from Varennes.
But second rounds in French elections are a chance for second thoughts. This
is why most pollsters put the bottom range of the RPR/UDR eventual score in
seats at around 440, with the outside possibility that the Socialists -
having failed to gain a single seat in the first ballot - might pick up as
many as 80, admittedly far short of the 262 seats which they and their
allies held in the last parliament.
There are two reasons why the pendulum might swing back slightly from the
right. One is that more people might vote next Sunday than did last Sunday,
when 31.07 per cent of the electorate stayed away from the polling booths.
This abstention rate is high compared to the last cohabitation election in
1986 when the RPR/UDF first entered government under the Mitterrand
presidency. Socialist appeals for a common front against the right might
bring out more left-wing voters in six days' time. The second factor is
known as desistement, in which second-round candidates of the left desist in
favour of the one among them best placed to beat the right, with the same
tactics happening on the right. The way in which such desistement can affect
the outcome is well illustrated by Sunday's outcome in Gardanne, near
Marseilles, which Mr Bernard Tapie, the businessman, is trying to keep for
the Socialists. He scored 25.6 per cent, his RPR challenger 24.28 per cent,
the Communist 19.31 per cent, and the extreme-right National Front 18.97 per
cent. All four are in a run-off race of unusual symmetry between left and
right.
Adding to the Socialists' weakness is the fact that in this election the
party has no electoral pacts with others, though it has at least a history
of striking bargains with the Communists. There is no such track record of
co-operation with Les Verts and Generation Ecologie. Indeed, the Socialists
have really messed up their relations with this green alliance.
They waited until last week, when the greens were beginning to slump in the
polls, to suggest a tactical voting pact. Had they proposed this when the
environmentalists were riding high in the polls (at one point ahead of the
Socialists, at 20 per cent), the Socialists could have given the greens, and
in the end themselves, a real fillip. Now that the ecologists have crashed
to a total 7.6 per cent vote in the first round, they are not much good to
the Socialists. With Mr Brice Lalonde, the GE leader, and Mr Antoine
Waechter, the leader of Les Verts, knocked out in the first round, most
greens feel too sore with Socialist opportunism to want to co-operate now.
By contrast, the RPR and UDF are solid, at least on paper. In more than 500
constituencies they fielded a single candidate in the first round, and 78 of
them gained an outright victory (42 for the RPR, 36 for the UDF). In 52 of
the 70 seats where the RPR and UDF ran a kind of US-style primary election
against each other, the RPR candidate did better than the UDF one. Where,
therefore, both candidates did well enough to appear in the run-off, it
would seem to be up to the UDF in most cases to give way. That is indeed
what opposition leaders decided in their 'code of good conduct'.
But the centrist, particularly the Christian Democrat, wing of the UDF
thinks otherwise. With some reason, they argue that they are naturally
better placed than hardline Gaullists to pick loose votes in the centre. And
they got backing from Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing. The UDF president said
that, while he 'would take no risk' of letting a Socialist get back in,
'when the choice is just between opposition candidates, it will be the
electors who will decide.'
The reason for this jostling between the partners in France's future
coalition government is that each wants to provide the prime minister
nominated by President Mitterrand next week. If, as now seems likely, the
RPR wins most seats, that job will go to one of its men, probably Mr Edouard
Balladur. But desperately keen to shake its image of being the RPR's little
brother, the UDF is conceding nothing until the polling booths close, again,
at 8 pm next Sunday.
