<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Demirel prospers as Kurdish rebels fall out: A look at the
alternatives for Ankara as the threat from guerrillas weakens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Suleyman Demirel, the Turkish prime minister, was careful not to reject
it out of hand, but many Turks privately dismiss last week's ceasefire
declaration by Apo Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the rebel Kurdish Workers
party (PKK), as yet another ploy to gain time.
There is, however, an important difference from earlier ceasefire offers,
beyond the fact that Mr Ocalan wore a suit and tie for the first time anyone
can remember. Unlike other occasions, Turkey has a chance to offer reforms
for its 10m-strong Kurdish minority without being accused of caving in to
extremism.
Both on the military front and to some extent with western opinion, the
perception from Ankara is that the tide is fast turning in Turkey's favour
at the expense of the PKK.
The generals will no doubt be counselling the prime minister to press home
the military advantage. The alternative course is to push on with
far-reaching legal and cultural reforms, which western diplomats believe is
the only way to win over moderate Kurdish opinion and resolve the problem.
Mr Demirel appears in no mood to enter negotiations with the PKK or even the
Kurdish deputies in the Turkish parliament. It will be particularly
difficult to convince his hardline colleagues of the need for magnanimity.
Nonetheless, there is clear relief that this weekend's Kurdish new year
celebrations passed off relatively peacefully, unlike last year, when more
than 90 people died after government forces used tanks and armoured
personnel carriers to reassert control in a string of towns on Turkey's
borders with Iraq and Syria.
Since that crisis, the Turks have fast improved their counter-insurgency
tactics against a weakly armed and inexperienced guerrilla force. The
purchase of US Black Hawk helicopters has provided a new, fast reaction
capability.
Turkey's army, while mostly made up of conscripts, has officers with a
wealth of experience, many of them having spent all their professional lives
fighting the PKK. The security forces have played on divisions in the
Kurdish community already strained by the revival of an earlier wave of
bloody rivalry between hardline Kurdish Islamic groups. All of this has
served further to weaken the PKK's support among the people.
Diplomatically, the Turks have made important gains. For all his wife's
campaigning for the Kurdish cause, French President Francois Mitterrand has
openly declared his opposition to the PKK's methods and aspirations for a
separate state. Mr Douglas Hurd, the UK foreign secretary, made much the
same pronouncement.
Even some of Germany's politicians, despite the attractions of the Kurdish
cause as a domestic issue, have moved to condemn the PKK as a terrorist
force.
The PKK's ability to sustain the conflict has long depended on being able to
to infiltrate trained fighters across Turkey's borders. Today the PKK's
Syrian backers, increasingly isolated since the end of the cold war and the
withdrawal of Soviet patronage, are keen to improve ties with Ankara. Iran
too seems less inclined to foment the crisis.
The real test came in tacit co-operation with Iraq's Kurdish peshmerga
rebels, whose increasingly close ties with Ankara reflect an anxiety not to
alienate the Turks, who control the vital aid lifeline and provide air bases
for the allied air umbrella.
The PKK was forced from its bases in northern Iraq; even now the peshmerga
leadership is still reluctant to elaborate on its role in this.
In the wake of the Gulf war, Turkey's western allies were rarely comfortable
explaining to their public why they condoned Ankara's heavy-handed
repression of its own Kurdish minority while the west offered support to the
Kurds in Iraq. Diplomats now say that, more than any other issue, the sight
of Kurds fighting Kurds has served to change the way that western public
opinion views the Kurdish cause.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TRZ  Turkey, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
