<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Amato prepares to replace minister: Italian premier moves to
repair damage caused by further resignation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Amato government yesterday sought to shake off the image of a lame-duck
administration in the wake of the weekend resignation of Mr Gianni Fontana,
minister of agriculture, who had become swept up in Italy's continuing
corruption scandals.
Instead of marking time until the next main event in the political calendar
 -the referendums set for April 18 - without replacing him, Mr Giuliano
Amato, the prime minister, yes terday said that he intended to appoint a new
minister as soon as possible.
It had been previously suggested that Mr Amato would make no new appointment
at least until the referendums. One of the 10 referendums concerns the
abolition of the Ministry of Agriculture and the devolution of decisions in
agricultural matters to the regions.
However, the agricultural minister has to watch over at least three key and
controversial areas - the future of the Gatt talks and the impact of any
agreement on Italian farmers, especially of oilseeds; the bitter dispute
between Italy and the EC over milk quotas; and this month's outbreak of foot
and mouth disease in Italy, caused by cattle imported from Croatia, which
has led to a tough ban on meat exports.
These considerations, combined with the obvious signals of weakness in any
decision not to replace Mr Fontana, appear to have persuaded the prime
minister.
The portfolio was held by the Christian Democrats and replacement would have
to come either from the same party or from the ranks of technocrats.
Mr Fontana, 48, is under investigation by magistrates in his home base of
Verona for alleged illicit financing of political parties. He is the fourth
minister to resign in just over a month.
Mr Giovanni Goria, who resigned as finance minister because of his alleged
involvement in irregularities in a savings bank scandal, has since been
cleared by magistrates.
Meanwhile, Mr Carlo Ripa de Meana the former EC commissioner, who resigned
as Italy's environment minister last month and left the Socialist party in
protest at Mr Amato's attempts to find a political solution to the judicial
problems presented by the corruption scandals, was elected the leader of the
Green party over the weekend.
A total of six ministers have resigned since the Amato government was first
formed at the end of June last year.
The prime minister now faces an uphill task in convincing both the members
of his own four-party coalition and the rest of parliament that he has the
will to keep governing.
The leaders of most of the political parties have begun discussions to
consider whether a new, broader-based government should be formed after the
referendums to carry out essential constitutional reforms.
But the parties' positions remain riven by internal rivalries and
suspicions.
</TEXT>
