<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / EC pact on monitoring emissions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC ENVIRONMENT ministers last night agreed standardised mechanisms to
monitor the Twelve's commitments to cut carbon dioxide emissions.
Policing this main greenhouse gas will highlight whether measures planned so
far can meet the EC's undertaking to stabilise CO output at 1990 levels by
2000.
It could thus underline the need for the European Commission's controversial
carbon/energy tax if conventional energy efficiency measures, designed to
cut emissions and combat global warming, prove insufficient.
Agreement was held up by British insistence that a clear difference be
established between monitoring and implementation, and that responsibility
for measuring emissions should lie squarely with each member state.
But wider differences among the Twelve over the EC strategy to fight global
warming while protecting competitive advantage in the middle of a recession
were also on display. How to share out the cuts has not been resolved.
EC environment commissioner Ioannis Paleokrassas said that national
programmes to cut CO output would still see emissions at 3 per cent over
1990 levels in 2000, underlining the need for the tax Brussels wanted. The
tax would put Dollars 3 (Pounds 2.10) on each barrel of oil equivalent,
rising to Dollars 10 by 2000, with half on the fuel content of all
non-renewable fuel and half on its carbon content.
Industry is hostile to the tax because of its implications for competition,
despite the US administration's recent proposal to tax fuel.
But northern countries such as Germany, Holland and Denmark strongly back
the tax. They have set themselves higher emission reduction targets - and
some countries fear these more difficult goals could creep into any form of
monitoring which bordered on policing. The UK is reticent, and more so after
its recent decision to levy its own fuel taxes.
Spain is strongly opposed to the tax, arguing that richer countries that
emit more CO should be set higher cuts.
</TEXT>
