<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Hopes dim for Bosnia peace accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS for peace in Bosnia receded further yesterday. 'The feeling is
that time is running out on these (New York peace) talks,' said Mr Fred
Eckhard, the conference spokesman, in an unusually pessimistic statement.
'There is a question as to how many more days they can keep a negotiating
process going that seems to be getting nowhere.'
At the same time, the United Nations Security Council put off adoption of a
resolution enforcing a ban on flights over Bosnia, if necessary by shooting
down offending aircraft. The council had been due to vote last night but
agreed to a delay at the request of the Russians.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, has intimated that he might
break off the peace talks if the ban is enforced.
An enforcement vote by the Security Council would be the first time that the
UN has authorised military intervention against one of the parties in the
Bosnian conflict, namely the Bosnian Serbs.
The Council was due to act after bombing raids last week by aircraft
believed to be Serbian on mainly Moslem villages in Bosnia. But the
resolution will not go into effect until the Council, the enforcing
countries and the UN peacekeeping forces agree on a date. A grace period of
two to three weeks may be given to the Serbs before the resolution is
implemented.
The Bosnian Serbs have largely respected the original ban, adopted last
November, at least as far as fixed wing combat aircraft are concerned.
However, they have continued to fly helicopters to transport personnel, the
wounded and war supplies. Last week's bombing is reported to have been
carried out by crop-sprayers.
In Sarajevo, UN officers said that General Philippe Morillon, the UN
military commander who last Friday led the first relief convoy into the
besieged town of Srebrenica since the Bosnian civil war began last April,
had struck a deal to evacuate Serbs from the Moslem-dominated town of Tuzla.
Mr Karadzic was quoted as having ordered his forces to open an air corridor
for UN helicopters.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
