<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Russia split on Yeltsin support: President gives guarantee
of media freedom - US pledges backing for reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA'S republics and regions were last night split more or less equally
over support for Mr Boris Yeltsin in his attempt to hold a popular vote on
his presidency and a new constitution.
The mixed reaction in the regions - that belied expectations of widespread
rejection of his action in outlying areas - filtered in to Moscow as the
Constitutional Court adjourned its crucial review of Mr Yeltsin's move
without an immediate decision.
Reflecting western support for Mr Yeltsin, Mr Warren Christopher, secretary
of state, said the US must help reform in Russia 'not as a matter of charity
but as a strategic concern of the highest order'.
He said Mr Yeltsin was committed to reform in its broadest sense, including
protection of civil liberties. But Mr Christopher stressed that US
assistance would not be 'cheap' and must be 'for the duration', vested in
reformers 'whether they are up or whether they are down'.
The response in Russia's outlying regions is vital for Mr Yeltsin as they
could interfere with his proposal to hold a popular vote on April 25 on
whether Russia should be ruled by the president or by the parliament that is
largely hostile to him and his pro-market reforms.
While the reaction was encouraging for him, it raised the danger of a deeply
divided nation, with rising tension between regions as the power struggle in
Moscow intensifies.
Mr Yeltsin moved to forestall expected attempts by parliament to declare
control over the media, by announcing he would guarantee the freedom of all
TV and radio stations and newspapers. Most national papers are already
sympathetic to him and the two main state channels are headed by his
appointees.
Mr Yeltsin got further strong support from Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, the prime
minister, who highlighted the desperate nature of the Russian economy as the
decisive factor in the president's decision to rule by decree until the
popular vote was held.
But Mr Yeltsin suffered a blow when Mr Nikolai Fyodorov, the justice
minister, resigned - the first minister to make clear his lack of support
for the president.
The Constitutional Court deliberated for hours but failed to rule on the
constitutionality of Mr Yeltsin's move. The court's chairman, Mr Valery
Zorkin, said deliberations would continue later this week.
Like parliament, the 13-member court is dominated by conservatives. But the
delay pointed to a troubled debate on a ruling that might lead to steps in
parliament to impeach Mr Yeltsin. Pointing to one of the court's problems,
Mr Zorkin said it had not received any documents requested from Mr Yeltsin.
Mr Vyacheslav Kostikov, Mr Yeltsin's press secretary, earlier dismissed the
court as biased because of Mr Zorkin's declaration on Sunday that the
president was in breach of the constit-ution.
In London, Mr John Major sent a message of support to Mr Yeltsin. 'Russia
needs effective democratic government respecting the rule of law. That is
what we support and what you are seeking to achieve,' the prime minister
said.
Mr Major added that over the past two weeks the Group of Seven leading
industrial countries 'has been working on ideas for further economic
support'.
Page 2
Debt deal likely to be at core of aid for Russia
Yeltsin receives greater regional backing
