<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / BAT plans to pay 33.9p scrip dividend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAT Industries, the UK-based tobacco and financial services group, plans to
pay a scrip dividend worth 50 per cent more than the 22.6p final cash
dividend announced recently.
The group does not intend to repeat the offer, worth 33.9p per share, for
future dividend payments. Shareholders who want cash can sell the new
ordinary shares through Barclays de Zoete Wedd Securities for 32.2p, free of
dealing costs - a 5 per cent discount to cover the joint broker's risk in
underwriting the deal.
BAT has taken this step partly because its large overseas earnings give it a
big problem with unrelieved Advance Corporation Tax. But the group denied
that this step was inspired by last week's Budget moves to deal with ACT.
Mr Amir Eilon, of BZW, said: 'We had been working on this for 18 months and
would have done it anyway if the Budget had not come along. The government
has in fact cut this short by promising to deal with unrelieved ACT.'
The scheme will need to be approved by a 75 per cent majority of
shareholders voting at BAT's annual meeting in May. City institutions do not
normally take scrip issues, but BZW said it was confident that most large
shareholders would approve the deal.
Other large companies might be tempted to follow BAT. To do so without
diluting earnings or net assets, they will need to have unrelieved ACT and
be confident that they can employ the money released at a sufficiently high
rate of return.
BAT could save up to Pounds 97m of ACT and up to Pounds 330m of dividends by
issuing the scrip, assuming full take-up. The group said its net asset value
could increase by as much as 6.2 per cent and earnings per share would be
enhanced. Gearing could fall from 54.6 per cent to as low as 41 per cent,
depending on take-up.
Sir Patrick Sheey, chairman, said: 'Shareholders will benefit from the
higher value and the group will benefit from being even better placed to
take advantage of the extensive opportunities for organic growth within our
existing businesses.'
BAT is investing heavily in cigarette factories at Southampton in the UK,
Georgia in the US, and in new technology for Farmers, the group's US
insurance subsidiary.
Details, Page 24
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
