<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Spring Ram
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Spring Ram Corporation's forced conversion to the kitchen sink school of
auditing must count as a triumph for the rigorous new accounting regime. It
was always improbable that a company manufacturing kitchens and bathrooms
could have maintained pre-tax profit margins at around 20 per cent
throughout the recession. Its aggressive accounting policies now emerge as
one of the main reasons.
Last year's cleaned-up results emerged some Pounds 13m below what the market
had expected. Spring Ram blithely suggested this provided a solid new base
from which to progress. Its irrepressibly optimistic fan club sensed a
buying opportunity following the company's share price collapse.
This shows remarkable forgiveness for a company which has developed a nasty
habit of disappointment. There must be grave doubts about the quality of
Spring Ram's previously stated earnings. Its in-bred culture and the delay
in appointing non-executive directors continue to give grounds for concern.
Should shareholders be burned again they have nothing to blame but their own
myopia.
</TEXT>
