<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Argos
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Market research is no substitute for a good idea - as Argos's foray into
furniture demonstrates all too clearly. Chesterman was only a four-store
pilot venture, yet it managed to cost Argos Pounds 21m in its brief passage
from cradle to grave. The company argues that there was too big a gap
between the research being done and the stores opened. It seems more likely
that the management's good use of research in the main Argos chain - a
business it knows well - blinded it to ambiguous answers about a business it
did not know at all. The high exit cost also indicates that the management
had not seriously considered that the project might fail.
More happily, Argos is blessed with a flourishing core business. Floor space
will grow by around 6 per cent this year, and total sales may be up over 10
per cent. Calls for more rapid development are sensibly being resisted, and
the format still has several years of expansion, so earnings growth seems
assured. That, however, is amply reflected in Argos's premium rating. And
Chesterman has delivered a nasty knock to the management's reputation. The
market's relief that Argos has decided against moving into Europe is
evidence enough of that.
</TEXT>
