<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / US puts increased pressure on Japan over economy plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US government has sharply increased pressure on Japan over the contents
and the scale of plans to boost its flagging economy with an emergency
public spending package to be announced within the next few weeks.
The US probing of the Japanese plans suggests the Clinton administration
will take an increasingly assertive stance, not just on trade but on
macro-economic policy.
Senior US officials led by Professor Larry Summers, who has been nominated
to oversee the US approach to international economic policies, have sent the
Japanese finance ministry a long stream of questions about the details of
the Y10,700bn (Pounds 62.5bn) emergency package introduced last year.
The questions are thought to reflect scepticism among some of President Bill
Clinton's senior economic advisers over the real extent of the stimulus
which the special package delivered.
While Japan presented the package as worth about 2.3 per cent of gross
national product, the US administration estimates it may be worth less than
1 per cent.
The US probing comes as Japan is in the delicate process of drawing up plans
for a further emergency package, which some politicians have suggested may
be worth as much as Y14,000bn.
Prof Summers' questioning is complicating the task of drawing up the
package, which Japanese leaders want to be ready for Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, the
prime minister, to present to Mr Clinton during talks in Washington on April
16.
The US has repeatedly called on Japan to stimulate its slowing economy to
raise demand for imports, in order to reduce its ballooning trade surplus
with the US and help sustain the role of exports in the US economic
recovery.
Until recently the US pressure was mainly confined to the size of the
Japanese fiscal programme. In the past few weeks more attention has focused
on its contents as well suggesting that the US administration may not take
it at face value.
Japanese officials say the US has expressed scepticism about the value of
increased spending through the Fiscal Investment and Loan Programme, Japan's
so-called second budget, which is largely funded by postal savings.
More than Y4,000bn of the Y10,700bn package was funded by drawing funds from
the programme. However, the US suggests much of this spending is simply
redirected rather than new money.
The US and Japan also differ over Japan's room for manoeuvre on fiscal
policy. The US believes Japan's public finances allow considerable room for
fiscal stimulus through cutting taxes, higher spending and increased
borrowing. The Japanese finance ministry insists much of its apparent
surplus is already committed to pensions for the country's rapidly ageing
population.
Tokyo grilled by US, Page 6
</TEXT>
