<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWAD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Observer: Thinker on the trigger
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'Workers of the world unite' has given way to putting thinkers of the world
on screen for 1960s student revolutionary Tariq Ali. His latest project is a
series of films about philosophers.
The first, on Wittgenstein, is for release this week. A second in the can is
on Spinoza. Another, on Locke, is scheduled for filming this autumn.
'I'm hoping Jonathan Miller will play him,' says Ali, adding that while
presenting his subjects' ideas, he isn't doing it classroom-style. 'The idea
is to explain their philosophies through the way they lived their lives.'
Hence, a good candidate for a fourth film would surely be Oxford's F H
Bradley who died in 1924. True, in Britain he was rarely seen outside Merton
College where he lived as a bachelor, but he often took health-restoring
trips abroad where he had some intriguing adventures.
One was to link up with a red-headed writer called Elinor Glyn who
scandalised Edwardian society with her novel Three Weeks about a steamy
affair in exotic settings. The result was a popular jingle:
Would you like to sin
with Elinor Glyn
on a tiger skin?
Or would you prefer
to err with her
on some other fur?
Whether she did any sinning with Bradley is uncertain. While the fact that
he was 65 when they met makes it less likely, his writings show he doubted
that he could have a Platonic relationship with a woman.
What he certainly had, however, was a fierce hatred of cats which, when
feasible, he shot at with a revolver. Nor evidently did he see them as his
only potential enemies, because he never went abroad without carrying one of
the three pistols that were found in his college room on his death, none of
them registered with the police.
All of which sheds odd light on Bradley's brand of philosophy. He was an
idealist.
</TEXT>
