<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Right man, wrong job: Germany needs Hans Tietmeyer in Bonn,
not at the Bundesbank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank vice-president, is favourite to take over
at the top of the German central bank when Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the
president, retires at the end of September.
There is a chance, however, he will find himself in the wrong job.
Mr Tietmeyer, 61, a former state secretary in the Bonn Finance Ministry, who
joined the Bundesbank in 1990, would make a good central bank president. He
is a formidable negotiator who combines wide knowledge of financial affairs
with great powers of persuasion in public and private.
The real gaps in the running of the German economy are, however, not in
Frankfurt, but in Bonn.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who will ultimately decide the Bundesbank
succession, should put Mr Tietmeyer in supreme charge of tackling the
economic consequences of German reunification - by making Mr Tietmeyer
Germany's next finance minister.
The suggestion is controversial. Removing Mr Theo Waigel, the present
finance minister, who heads Mr Kohl's Bavarian sister party, the Christian
Social Union, would cause a coalition crisis. Additionally, Mr Tietmeyer
would be loath to consider the idea because he started his Bonn career as an
economics ministry official as long ago as 1962. He knows, first-hand, the
strains and frustrations of government life - pressures which have been
greatly increased by the problems of unification.
The president of a universally respected, statutorily independent central
bank enjoys a much more comfortable and predictable existence than the
finance minister. The job is secure - it carries an eight-year mandate.
And the Bundesbank boss earns around DM700,000 a year, well over double Mr
Waigel's salary.
For all this, there are compelling reasons why Mr Tietmeyer's talents would
be put to better use in Bonn than in Frankfurt.
First, Mr Tietmeyer's lack of mainstream political experience would be an
asset, not a liability, in view of German voters' disenchantment with the
established political parties.
Mr Tietmeyer, a member of Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic Union since 1960,
certainly has the ear of the chancellor. He is not a member of the Bundestag
 -but then neither is Mr Klaus Kinkel, the current foreign minister, who
took over last year.
Second, Mr Tietmeyer's stamina and experience would give him crucial
advantages in negotiations on putting the financing of German unity on a
sounder footing. Mr Kohl's budget deal with the Social Democrats and the
Lander 10 days ago still leaves gaping holes in public-sector finances. This
means the search must go on for the right balance of spending cuts, tax
increases and new public financing methods, including privatisation. As a
technocrat of stature, Mr Tietmeyer would stand a good chance of remaining
in his post if - as seems possible - a grand coalition of Christian and
Social Democrats came to power during the next few years. Clearly, however,
an outright SPD victory in the December 1994 general elections would deprive
Mr Tietmeyer of a job. That is a risk he would have to take.
Third, Mr Tietmeyer has been called in before by Mr Kohl on sensitive
missions. In spring 1990, the chancellor made him head of the West German
delegation negotiating the introduction of the D-Mark into east Germany.
Mr Tietmeyer has since admitted that, reflecting the need for a quick deal,
Bonn made important errors in its accord with the east Germans. These
concerned above all the terms on which east Germany's assets and liabilities
were converted into D-Marks.
These mistakes have had important economic policy consequences. As finance
minister, Mr Tietmeyer would have a chance to correct some of them.
Fourth, on the international stage, Mr Tietmeyer would be a more convincing
performer than Mr Waigel. Mr Tietmeyer has a better grasp of the issues at
the heart of the debate over European economic and monetary union.
If he made more strenuous efforts to correct imbalances in German fiscal
policies, Mr Tietmeyer would carry more conviction in pleading for patience
over the effects of these policies on Germany's partners.
Commonsense, then, indicates that Mr Tietmeyer would be an optimal choice.
But practical realities suggest that he is likely to stay in Frankfurt. That
would be a pity.
The Bundesbank often appears strongest when the government is weak. That is
not good for Germany's image. An imaginative decision to recall Mr Tietmeyer
to Bonn would help redress the balance.
Summoning into the government a man of his reputation and intellect would
emphasise the scale of the country's challenges. And it would improve the
chance that, within a relatively short span of years, Germany will come to
terms with them.
</TEXT>
