<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Why Europe's hands are tied: The Commission is taking a back
seat at a time of political and economic crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Early in the new year, Mr Jacques Delors chaired the first meeting of the
European Commission. Turning to his new team, he asked whether they were
content to follow their member states' instructions and lie low until
ratification of the Maastricht treaty on European Union.
The answer was a resounding yes. Mr Delors concurred, reluctantly. One week
later, he again asked whether it was wise for the Commission to take a back
seat. Once again, a clear majority favoured a low profile.
With hindsight, Mr Delors believes he made a mistake. At the very moment of
political and economic crisis in the European Community, the Commission has
forfeited its authority as arbiter between the 12 member states. A power
vacuum has arisen in the EC.
'We have been put in a (Trappist) monastery,' says one EC official. Another
senior EC official is blunter. He argues that the EC has degenerated into a
standing inter-governmental conference, led by a weak Danish presidency
which cannot see beyond May 18, the date of a second referendum on
Maastricht.
Europe appears doomed to play a waiting game which - bar upsets - may end
with final ratification in the UK in early autumn. Mr Delors, meanwhile, has
taken to travel: a leisurely trip to Morocco, and a tour of Latin America,
ending in a 55-minute meeting with US President Bill Clinton in Washington.
Yet the impression of inactivity may be misleading. Whatever the outcome in
Denmark and the UK, EC leaders face choices which will determine whether the
Community moves forward, stagnates, or slips into genteel decline.
The first challenge is trade. Hard-pressed companies are pushing for
protection from cheap imports from eastern Europe and high-technology
competition in Asia. The call for special treatment covers steel,
semiconductors, cereals, fish and many other recession-hit industries.
Protectionist pressures may subside after the French parliamentary
elections, the first round of which ended Sunday; but Brussels diplomats
predict that the new right-wing government in Paris would adopt an even
tougher line on trade than its Socialist predecessor. Their fear is that
France will demand a renegotiation of last year's EC-US farm trade accord,
dashing hopes for the Gatt Uruguay Round.
This is a troubling prospect, particularly in Bonn. The German government is
uneasy about being forced to choose between France as its natural EC ally
and its wider national interest in seeing an early Gatt deal. Last month, Mr
Klaus Kinkel, German foreign minister, warned: 'We have reached the point
where our conception no longer coincides with that of France.'
Mr Kinkel's comments reflect a reassessment of EC trade policy in Bonn.
Germany remains furious that it lost the 'banana' war. Having fought to
preserve its supply of high-quality 'dollar' bananas from Latin America,
Germany was forced to accept an EC-wide quota which guaranteed supply from
Caribbean producers, many from former French and British colonies.
Diplomats detect a new German assertiveness in favour of open markets. Bonn
has resisted French-led efforts to strengthen trade weapons such as
anti-dumping duties. It has also ignored pressure to impose curbs on cheap
imports from China and North Korea. 'Trade policy is completely blocked in
the EC,' says a former EC commissioner.
The second challenge for the EC is how to stimulate economic growth. Last
week's  1/2 percentage point reduction in the Bundesbank's discount rate is
welcome; but the Commission argues that German rates must fall much further
and faster if the EC is to beat its already optimistic forecast of 0.8 per
cent growth in 1993. The target of 3 per cent growth looks even more remote.
Yet at least 2.5 per cent growth is necessary to prevent a further rise in
unemployment, according to a new European Parliament study. Low growth means
longer dole queues. The EC economy expanded by just over 1 per cent in 1992,
but unemployment rose by 2m. This year, the number of people out of work in
the EC could top 17m.
The response is an EC 'growth package'. The idea is that member states
co-ordinate capital spending projects on roads, housing and infrastructure
to kick-start their economies. But the real test is whether the 12 can put
on a convincing show of solidarity to coax the US and Japan to support
expansionary fiscal measures at the Tokyo economic summit in July.
Without economic growth, there is no prospect of the EC meeting its third
challenge: adequate 'convergence' in economic performance to proceed to a
European monetary union in 1997, leading eventually to a single European
currency.
The economic downturn, compounded by high German interest rates, has shown
that EC economies are more likely to diverge in the near term. This
divergence lay behind the crisis in the exchange rate mechanism which forced
sterling and the Italian lira to float; the Spanish peseta, the Portuguese
escudo and the Irish punt have suffered forced devaluations, while the
French franc is far from safe.
Many EC officials argue the way to beat the speculators and salvage Emu is a
Franco-German initiative launching a 'fast track' to monetary union,
possibly through a fixing of franc/D-Mark exchange rates. 'There is nothing
in the Maastricht treaty which prohibits such a move,' says one.
A putative 'strong currency club' led by France and Germany would probably
include the Benelux countries. Others would be invited to follow, at their
own pace. EC officials add that such an initiative could be timed to
'relaunch' the EC immediately after Maastricht ratification.
Yet such talk finds little resonance in Bonn; even less so in Frankfurt,
home of the Bundesbank. Senior German officials rule out moving ahead of
schedule on Emu; their great fear is that weaker members will try to fudge
the 'convergence criteria' on curbing inflation and budget deficits, just to
secure the political triumph of a monetary union by 1997.
A senior Bonn official predicts that a majority of countries will not be
ready to meet the Maastricht criteria in 1996. Without mentioning whether
deficit-ridden Germany will be strictly eligible to join Emu, he declares:
'It's going to be 1999.'
The length of time reflects the need to work out how to meet Maastricht's
twin objectives of deepening the EC through monetary and political union,
while preparing to accommodate new members. Enlargement goes beyond the
current batch of EC aspirants - Austria, Finland, Sweden and Norway - and
extends planning for a Community of up to 20 members.
Similar planning for institutional change is proceeding quietly in other
European capitals. Among the ideas are: more responsibilities to the
European Parliament, including voting on the membership of the Commission
and new, limited revenue-raising powers; stronger powers for the Commission
president, possibly by creating a troika of vice-presidents responsible for
the internal market, trade and political co-operation; and limits on the
number of languages used in the bureaucracy.
At present, some 10,000 EC meetings are interpreted in nine official
languages, requiring 72 combinations for interpreting purposes. The use of
16 languages would result in 240 combinations, requiring 54 interpreters for
one meeting of a single committee.
But no one wants to open the debate on institutional change. It might scare
voters in Denmark or enrage UK Euro-sceptics. It could also muddy the
picture in the Nordic countries, where popular support for Maastricht is
lukewarm.
A senior Belgian official says the present vacuum is surreal. 'The accession
negotiations are being conduced on the basis of a non-existent treaty, a
non-existent consensus among the applicants, by an EC presidency (Denmark)
whose country has not even ratified the treaty.'
Sooner or later all member states will have to make the tough choices on how
to pursue deepening integration while continuing to offer wider membership
of the club. On this fundamental question, the debate over the Maastricht
treaty has little or nothing to say.
</TEXT>
<XX>
