<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Leading Article: Storms ahead in France
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S conservative parties have won a spectacular victory in the first
ballot of the general election. If confirmed in the second ballot next
Sunday it will produce a national assembly reminiscent of the Chambre Bleu
Horizon of 1919, or even the Chambre Introuvable of 1815, both remembered as
high points of right-wing electoral backlash.
Yet the overwhelming parliamentary majority projected for the conservative
alliance reflects only a modest jump in their popular vote. The truly
spectacular event is the halving of the Socialist vote. This was
foreshadowed in local and regional elections a year ago, but then it could,
at a pinch, be interpreted as a mid-term protest vote. Certainly it was a
warning, to which President Francois Mitterrand responded by dismissing his
unpopular prime minister, Mrs Edith Cresson, replacing her with the
generally respected finance minister, Mr Pierre Beregovoy. That response has
cut no ice.
Mr Beregovoy is still respected - by the markets, but in elections they do
not have the deciding voice. With the public at large his reputation has
been tainted - not so much by the personal peccadillo of an interest-free
loan from a businessman as by the fact that his party has been involved in
scandal after scandal, while the president himself is seen as well past his
sell-by date. Crime and immigration prey on the minds of many ordinary
voters, in France as elsewhere in western Europe. But none of these things
would cause such fierce and widespread resentment were it not for the state
of the economy. Growth has come to a stop. Bankruptcies are rising steeply.
So, above all, is unemployment.
Model of responsibility
This sounds like a familiar pattern. Left-wing governments traditionally
come unstuck on economics, and disillusioned electorates then turn to
conservatives, with sounder and more rigorous policies, to sort things out.
But that is not what has happened in France. The Socialist party sowed its
wild oats way back in 1981-83, and since then has been a model of fiscal and
monetary responsibility. France has one of the lowest rates of inflation on
the continent, and is running a trade surplus. While it is certainly
plausible to blame the current recession on the government's obsession with
sound money, especially its determination to hold the franc-mark parity at
all costs, this is in fact the one issue on which the main opposition
leaders decline to criticise it. Even if the voters' howl of pain was
directed primarily at this policy, the effect will be a government pledged
to continue it.
Poisoned chalice
Inevitably the markets will question how credible, and for how long, such a
pledge can be. Already voices within the victorious parties are calling for
devaluation, and the very size of the new government's majority will make it
harder to silence them. No doubt steps will be taken to reinforce the
pledge's credibility, though it seems unlikely that a further rise in
interest rates would have that effect. The Bundesbank will reiterate its
commitment, but this too may fail to carry conviction unless accompanied by
cuts in interest rates much more decisive than we have seen yet.
If the franc fort is one poisoned chalice for the incoming government,
another is the agreement on agricultural subsidies reached between the EC
and US last November, which French conservatives denounced with even greater
venom than the Socialist government, and pledged themselves rather more
convincingly to reject. In attempting to honour that pledge they will find
themselves at odds with Germany.
The potential for a serious Franco-German split, with all that that implies
for the EC's future cohesion, is obvious. Some elements within the
coalition, especially on its Gaullist wing, may be tempted to make a virtue
of such a split. Others, including Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing, leader of
the non-Gaullist wing, would strenuously oppose it, and would be supported
by the President.
His support may not count for much, at least initially. After such a defeat,
and with only two years of his second mandate left to run, he appears the
lamest of lame ducks. But on past form he will be quick to exploit the many
fault lines in the new governing majority - not least the fact that its
leaders will be rivals in their aspiration to succeed him.
</TEXT>
<XX>
