<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / God is in the market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE ROGALY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Contemporary British political debate is a pawnbroker's auction. We are
offered second-hand lies, used slogans and recycled sound-bites. We are
bribed with money taken from our own pockets. This is hardly surprising.
Most of us, politicians and public alike, work in a moral and philosophical
vacuum. Marxist socialism has been exposed as rotten; any kind of socialism
as inefficient. So much for utopian creeds. Their infinitely more profound
erstwhile rival, Christianity, has become unfashionable, if not in the US
then at least on this side of the water. The ghost of Christian morality
lingers on, but the damage caused by the decline of religious observance is
already being felt. The moral foundations of public discourse have been
blown away.
Sporadic efforts are being made to find alternative lodestars. None of them
looks especially promising. This morning a new think tank opens for business
under the name of Demos. Organised by former proponents of Marxism, it is
supported by distinguished people with a wide range of views. Its
presentational literature reads like the wailing of a tribe of lost souls.
It proposes to find ' . . . new ways of giving shape to the democratic
ideal'. Politics, say the founders, 'needs to be enriched with the insights
of . . . anthropology, organisation theory, psychology, theology, biology,
geography, culture and communications theory'. Yes, theology is in there,
but religious practice, moral philosophy, Christian values, the human
spirit, are not evident.
I cannot say anything about the actual work of Demos. It has not yet
published any, beyond its 'statement of aims'. It may produce brilliant
papers; if so they will be welcomed. At the moment it is an empty box. To me
the wrapping is disappointing. The curse of the west in general and Britain
in particular is widespread anomie, a withering away of social and ethical
standards. The pragmatic Demos is a symptom of this late 20th-century
cultural deficiency. It does not have the appearance of a potential cure.
Against that it has to be acknowledged that the thinking business is not
what it was. There are more producers, but quality is hard to find. Some of
the brightest minds on the left are occupied, serving the Labour party's
commission for social justice. On the right, at least five organisations are
hopping about looking for audiences, acquiring one another's luminaries and,
I suspect, competing for funds. Schismatics have departed from the
grand-daddy of them all, the Institute of Economic Affairs. Yet the IEA's
rump is still churning out booklets, the latest being 'God and the
Marketplace', published yesterday1.
These have the merit of seeking to debate the morality of wealth creation.
During the past decade capitalism has been elevated to the role of the god
that succeeded. In one of the IEA essays a high priest of this endeavour,
Professor Michael Novak, puts his case once more, thus: 'What makes human
beings distinctive is creativity. The Pope has focused on this 'creative
subjectivity' of the person, seeing the endowment of a fundamental human
right to personal economic initiative.' True, but Centisimus Annus, John
Paul II's encyclical of 1991, also warns of the free market's limitations -
as one of the other contributing authors, Bishop John Jukes, reminds us.
The evidence is in the streets. Look at the beggars, or the lost faces in
the dole queues. In spite of Professor Novak's enthusiastic assertions,
capitalism exists side-by-side with growing unemployment, relative
deprivation and a level of absolute poverty that should not be accepted. The
numerical evidence can be found in 'Poverty the Facts', by Carey Oppenheim,
an up-to-date edition of which was published by the Child Poverty Action
Group yesterday2. As a pressure group, the CPAG piles on the agony, and
gives some of its statistics greater weight than they can carry, but at
least it does so with moral intent.
The same purpose informs Mr John Smith, Labour party leader, whenever he
speaks. In his Tawney memorial lecture at the weekend he came out
unashamedly as a Christian socialist. ' . . . Let me assert my profound
conviction that politics ought to be a moral activity,' he said. ' . . . We
should never feel inhibited in stressing the moral basis of what we
believe.' Mr Smith would be the first to agree that in so doing he is not
claiming a monopoly of ethical sentiment, either for himself or for Labour.
Other Labour front-benchers have contributed to a new book, 'Reclaiming the
Ground'3, the final chapter of which consists of Mr Smith's lecture. The
book reveals Labour's leading Christian socialists to be Mr Tony Blair, Mr
Paul Boateng and Mr Chris Smith.
A few devoted souls, not on the front bench, have trodden similar ground. Mr
Frank Field, a Labour MP who sparks off more bright ideas than all his
comrades put together, is a practising Christian. The name of R H Tawney,
who died in 1962, was taken in vain by the founders of the Social Democratic
Party in the 1980s. I am not sure how many of them were heathens. Among the
Tories there are Messrs John Patten, John Gummer and Peter Lilley. Beelzebub
records that Mr Lilley would rather take his instruction on church matters
from Mr Field than from Mr Gummer.
The central tenet of Christian socialism is no great mystery. As expressed
by Mr Blair, its principal element is 'the union between individual and
community, the belief that we are not stranded in helpless isolation, but
owe a duty both to others and to ourselves and are, in a profound sense,
dependent on each other to succeed'. This is in stark contrast to the cult
of the individual alone, which is what people mistakenly perceive to be the
wellspring of Thatcherism.
A morally-founded debate might reveal more similarities than differences
between Christians in different parties. In one of the IEA essays Simon
Robinson, Anglican chaplain at the University of Leeds, gamely tries to
reconcile Novak's thinking with Tawney's. Difficult. Yet in continental
western Europe the moral high ground sought by Mr Blair and Mr Smith is
familiar. It is occupied by Christian Democrats.
1IEA, 2 Lord North St. SW1 P 3LB. 2CPAG, 4th Floor 1-5 Bath St., EC1V 9PY.
3Hodder &amp; Stoughton. Pounds 5.99
</TEXT>
