<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Letter: Russia: effective assistance with safeguards and a
contradiction (2)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr KEN LIVINGSTONE MP.
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I was alarmed by your leader ('The choice over Russia', March 17)
advocating support for President Boris Yeltsin 'up to the point where the
president concentrates authority in his hands'. You suggest that the west
may have to choose 'an autocracy run by democrats'. This is a contradiction
in terms and decidedly not the choice in Russia.
The west told the Russian people that market reform and parliamentary
democracy were indivisible. Yet now, when the Russian parliament asserts its
prerogative to guide the reform process, they are told that some kind of
emergency, presidential rule and the suspension of parliament, are
preferable. If there are genuine concerns about democracy in Russia then
there is an evident and simple solution: immediate parliamentary and
presidential elections to determine whom the people wish to represent them.
That is far better than the imposition of emergency rule which might unleash
forces of disintegration that dwarf anything seen so far in eastern Europe.
Ken Livingstone,
House of Commons,
London SW1A 0AA
</TEXT>
