<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Letter: Russia: effective assistance with safeguards and a
contradiction (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Prof D MARIO NUTI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The current major constitutional crisis in Russia poses an awkward
dilemma for the Group of Seven: whether to provide large-scale assistance to
Russia with the risk of its being wasted by a new government slowing down or
reversing stabilisation and transition, or wait and see, thus contributing
to Boris Yeltsin's demise. But there appear to be two forms of financial
assistance which could be safely and effectively pledged immediately,
regardless of future political and constitutional developments. These are:
the provision by IBRD (World Bank), EBRD (European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development), and other financial institutions of investment funds for
energy, military conversion and agro-industry, which might be well utilised
in any case as long as they were not channelled through the Russian central
bank, which effectively sabotaged Gaidar's 1992 programme, but through more
direct and controllable channels;
the provision of funds to cover partially and up to a maximum ceiling, for a
half or whole year in the first instance, the cost of additional
unemployment in Russia. This form of assistance would be 'robust' with
respect to uncertain developments: if Yeltsin were ousted and stabilisation
and reform stopped or reversed there would be no significant increase in
unemployment and therefore the western commitment would be automatically
voided. An immediate announcement should strengthen popular support for
Yeltsin's likely initiatives, like a plebiscite or a presidential takeover.
The amounts involved in supporting additional unemployment may be
substantial. There has been a tendency to evaluate the effectiveness of
dollar grants at the purchasing power in Russia of their rouble equivalent
at a vastly undervalued exchange rate. However, aid would be used to finance
imports of consumption goods on which the unemployed would spend their
benefits, and therefore the dollar value of necessary real aid should be
calculated at international prices. Mario Nuti,
professor of comparative
economic systems,
Faculty of Economics
and Commerce,
University of Rome
'La Sapienza'
</TEXT>
