<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Letter: Demands on charities' funds not all the same
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ANDREW HIND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, There is a danger that Andrew Jack's interesting article of March 15 on
charities 'Fears grow for charities as cash crisis worsens' will have
created two misconceptions in the minds of your readers.
First, that the funds of Britain's top 50 charities are all available for
distribution. In the case of Barnardo's, the majority of assets on our
balance sheet are in fact buildings which house our many child-care projects
around the UK. Without investing in property which, to borrow an ugly US
phrase, is 'critical to our mission', Barnardo's would not be able to
provide services to children and young people to the standard we believe
should be expected from a leading child care charity.
When assessing a charity's overall level of resources it is usually more
helpful to concentrate on analysing unearmarked reserves rather than total
funds.
Second, the article suggests that it is always a bad thing for charities to
have expenditure growing faster than income. It is regrettably true that
many charities currently have severe funding problems, but we must not
overlook the fact that a small number of charities hold high levels of
reserves. We should applaud those which are reducing reserves in a
controlled and responsible way by accelerating new projects and incurring
charitable expenditure greater than levels of income.
The problem with this subject is, to paraphrase the 1988 SORP2 statement on
charity accounting practice, that charities are very different and the
balance sheet is not necessarily a sound measure of wealth. The only way
round this is for donors to encourage charities clearly to outline their
reserve policy in their accounts.
Andrew Hind,
director of finance and
corporate services,
Barnardo's,
Tanners Lane,
Barkingside,
Ilford, Essex IG6 1QG
</TEXT>
