<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Arts: Morbid modern message - William Packer questions the
artistic merit of 'installations'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It may seem a bore to bang on yet again with the great 'modern: is it or
isn't it art' debate, but while our institutions continue to show the stuff,
the questions will hardly go away. Is whatever is put into a room enough to
constitute a work of art? Does the putting together, however so elegantly
and scrupulously, of given elements, constitute a work of art? And where do
such practices leave the careful carving and modelling that was the norm
only a generation ago? Three current exhibitions of sculpture set out the
issues.
Robert Gober, who, we are told in his blurb material, is in the forefront of
America's new generation, has, for his first solo show in Britain, rehung
the Serpentine throughout with wallpapers of his own design. One paper
carries only two images, of a man asleep in bed and, next to it, a black man
hanged upon a tree. Another, given in two ways, light on dark and dark on
light, is a little more complex, setting graffito-like male and female
genitalia beside each other. The most complex pattern is of trees in an
autumn wood, the ground covered in golden leaves. Not merely repeated but
inverted, the paper transforms the room into a glade, at least to the extent
that a drop-cloth achieves the same effect in a pantomime -
Babes-in-the-Wood, perhaps.
It would be unfair to dwell too long on the qualities of these essays in
decoration. Mr Gober is no draughtsman, and to say that they are crude,
alike in conception as in execution, is enough. But I do concede that here
they serve a higher purpose. The glade, for example, is further elaborated
by a huge cigar lying in the centre of the room, and against the walls some
pairs of truncated legs, set as though the rest of the unfortunate bodies
were burrowing into the piles of leaves. One is in his underpants, with
plug-holes set into his bare legs: another supports candles in square holes
cut through his trousers.
In the middle of the darker of the genitalia-decorated rooms sits a paper
bag full of doughnuts: the lighter room has an arm-chair in one corner, a
sack-like wax torso, half male, half female, in another, and more plug-holes
set into the wall. The bedroom has a wedding dress as its centre-piece, and
hand-painted bags of cat-litter against the walls.
Such are what Mr Gober calls his 'natural history dioramas about
contemporary human beings'. His publicity apologists go further, saying that
they evoke 'scenes of intimacy and social repression' that may be 'construed
as a reaction to the escalating horror of living today . . . His sculpture
stands as a provocation and a defiant challenge: not only to good taste and
good sense, but to the accepted practice and consumption of art.'
But is any of that true? Far from being provocative, Mr Gober is merely the
academic and the conformist, to which his burgeoning international
reputation bears eloquent witness. And what he actually does, with such
perfunctory competence, is no more than the staple of the anonymous
window-dresser, or the scene-painter, whose whole duty is merely to hold for
the moment a passing interest, enough for the message to get across.
Ah] The message] the horror of living today, AIDS, eroticism, perversion,
morbidity, death. And has he never looked at Breughel, Callot or Grunewald,
Goya or Picasso, Bellmer or Kienholz? Perhaps he has.
Susana Solano, at the Whitechapel, is a different case, again an artist who
has come to international prominence with remarkable rapidity - she began
working only in the late 1970s - yet one whose orthodoxy is formal rather
than conceptual. Her work is abstract, often set on a large scale, and her
practice the conventional manipulation and disposition of industrial
elements in an industrial way - welded, bent and bolted.
Her formal ideas are remarkably consistent, limited virtually to the single
theme of enclosure, upon which she works endless elegant variations - the
box; the cage; the drawer; the cabinet; the shelf; the cell. It is all
immaculately presented, every element set against the next just so, every
surface particular in its quality and contrast. Yet is it not all just a
little soulless and impersonal? Heavy metal is impressive by its very
presence, and elegant simplicity inevitably portentous. It is a formula less
to respond to than to respect.
Dennis Mitchell is now 80 and gravely ill. He has only ever been shown on
his own in London in small gallery shows, which makes the substantial
retrospective of his post-war work, now filling Angela Flowers' gallery all,
the more welcome. He has worked in Cornwall all his life, a true veteran of
Saint Ives in its pre-war days, his work founded in the simple, symbolic
abstraction of Brancusi and confirmed in the example of Barbara Hepworth.
Seen in the light of the Gobers and Damien Hirsts of this world, he must now
seem sadly old-fashioned and irrelevant a figure, yet here, personified in
the quiet, consistent achievement of a lifetime, an unexpectedly powerful
creative integrity distinguishes him - old-fashioned indeed. Carved and
modelled polished and patinated, everything carries the mark of the artist's
hand, unprogrammed and intuitive. Each curve and bend, each cavity and
convexity, each surface, is unique in its modulation and adjustment, the
purpose not merely to serve or indulge some external Goberean angst, but
simply to get it right, to make it true. I knew the work and had expected to
respect it: I had not expected to be so moved by it.
Robert Gober: Serpentine Gallery, Kensington Gardens W2, until April 25,
then to the Tate Gallery, Liverpool; sponsored by Beck's Beer. Susana
Solano: Whitechapel Art Gallery, Whitechapel High Street E1 until May 2,
then to Malmo and Grenoble; supported by the Spanish Foreign Ministry and
Henry Moore Foundation. Dennis Mitchell: Angela Flowers, London Fields,
Richmond Road E8 until April 18
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8412 Museums and Art Galleries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
