<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's Assignment sounds like a vivid example of the hypocrisy involved in
negotiations aimed at achieving a more united Europe. Everybody believes in
co-operation until their own interests are directly affected. We are told
that Europe is currently divided over bananas: Germany wants a free market
with low prices, but Britain, supposedly the great champion of free markets,
is keen to protect its old colonial suppliers. Julian Pettifer reports from
the banana republics on the effects of the world's big economies (7.45
BBC2). In the era of the big battalions it is good to know that, in wildlife
programmes at least, some one-man bands still succeed. Secret Nature which
tonight investigates the creatures inhabiting the freshwater world of
Slapton Ley in Devon, is produced, photographed, and narrated by Andrew
Cooper (8.30 BBC2). Without Walls follows Kazuko Hohki and her Tottenham pop
cabaret group Frank Chickens back to Japan where Kazuko decides to get
married (9.00). Stay up till 12.30 and you can watch the opening race in
Nigel Mansell's Indy Car 93 season (ITV).
