<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Arts: Britten's War Requiem - Concerts in London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sunday's War Requiem, given in the Albert Hall (and broadcast live on BBC2),
brought to an end Mstislav Rostropovich's mainly Barbican-based 'Festival of
Britten'. In spite of passing vagaries of execution - some of them caused,
it must be admitted, by the conductor's warm-hearted, imprecise beat - it
has proved a resounding success: a series that seized the musical public's
attention because its arrival was timely, its programming apt and its
overall purpose possessed of missionary enthusiasm.
It was, therefore, a particular shame that a good third of this War Requiem
should have been counterpointed by the loud double-clicking sound emitted
every ten seconds from the Albert Hall cupola - an electronic gremlin that
was allowed to persist unchecked for an everlasting-seeming 25 minutes. The
performance had set off with rapt, steady gravity, giving ample evidence of
the immaculate preparation of all its forces (London Symphony Orchestra plus
chamber orchestra conducted by Richard Hickox, hugely enlarged LS chorus,
boy-choristers from St Paul's Cathedral). But it was lamed by the continual
interruption: even when that was finally halted, the exalted atmosphere
proved hard to restore.
In such a case, a whole review is surely out of place; a few critical points
only are permissible. This work was destined - in spirit, if not in fact -
for the Albert Hall: its finest features are there emphasised and its
patches of mechanical inspiration (in the Offertorium, especially)
dramatically ballasted; voices solo and choral carry across the spaces with
radiant, heart-lifting ease. The soloists were Makvala Kasrashvili (a
shining, passionate soprano in the Vishnevskaya mould), Anthony Rolfe
Johnson (who, curiously, ignored all p-markings in the 'Agnus dei') and Bryn
Terfel (heroic-toned, vigorous in manner, a degree lacking in reflective
eloquence).
In aid of the Vishnevskaya-Rostropovich Foundation
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
