<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Bank of Edinburgh calls off merger
discussions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Edinburgh, which was established in 1990 to take over small and
medium-sized building societies, yesterday disclosed that its first attempt
to do so by acquiring the Heart of England Building Society had failed.
The bank and the society announced that they had agreed not to proceed
further with merger discussions. One of the bank's shareholders said talks
had foundered on difficulties in gaining regulatory approval from the Bank
of England.
Mr Russell Frith, Bank of Edinburgh finance director, said the bank still
believed that it could acquire other societies. 'There is nothing we have
found that is wrong with the basic principle of what we wanted to achieve,'
he said.
The Heart of England, which is the 25th biggest society with assets of
Pounds 1.01bn, said it intended to continue to trade independently although
it did not rule out entering merger discussions with large building
societies. Mr Mike Travis, chief executive of the Heart of England, said the
society, which is due to report full-year results in April, would declare a
profit. 'It is business as usual, although we are disappointed that this
proposition did not go ahead,' he said.
The bank's largest shareholder is Scottish Amicable, which has a 39.2 per
cent stake. Mr Graham Knox, deputy managing director of Scottish Amicable,
said the negotiations had failed because of strict regulatory requirements.
Mr Knox said that the bank had not been able to satisfy a series of
requirements for it to retain a banking licence after taking over Heart of
England. He said it had learned a number of lessons that would be useful for
the future.
Mr Knox said that reports that Scottish Amicable wanted to take a majority
stake in the bank were incorrect.
</TEXT>
