<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: P-E Intl shares decline 12% after tumble to
Pounds 160,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES IN P-E International fell by 12 per cent yesterday, from 58p to 51p,
after the management and computer consultancy group revealed a sharp
contraction in profits before tax last year and omitted the final dividend.
Pre-tax profits fell to Pounds 160,000 from Pounds 1.62m in 1991 when the
outcome was depressed by a Pounds 541,000 exceptional item. The latest
results reflected the difficult market for management consultancy and the
cost of reshaping the business.
Turnover increased Pounds 71.1m (Pounds 68.8m) but operating profits fell to
Pounds 572,000 (Pounds 2.56m) reflecting higher selling and administration
expenses of Pounds 19.8m (Pounds 16.6m) including a Pounds 343,000 pension
charge and a Pounds 100,000 write-down of property which has since been
sold.
Losses per share were 0.22p (earnings 4.9p); the passed final leaves the
total at 1p (6.2p).
Since taking over as chairman in May, Mr George Cox has instituted a
wide-ranging business review and reorganisation of the group and its senior
management. Commenting on the results he acknowledged that the level of
profits were 'not what the company would like to have achieved,' but said
that the third quarter of last year represented 'probably the lowest point
of the recession as far as P-E is concerned' and was followed by a stronger
final quarter.
During the year several small businesses acquired or created in recent years
were sold or closed. Aside from recording operating losses of Pounds 427,000
on these businesses, a Pounds 524,000 extraordinary loss, reflecting
goodwill previously written off to reserves, was recorded on the disposal of
Applied Skills for Management which was sold back to its former owner.
While some new businesses have been successfully turned around, other areas
are still under review, including Westvries, the group's Netherlands
subsidiary, which incurred a pre-tax loss of Pounds 394,000 last year.
The group has been attempting to develop its overseas revenue as part of its
efforts to generate new long term contracts and longer-term revenue sources.
Last year, after above-the-line costs of about Pounds 750,000, Mr Cox said
'substantial progress' had been made towards this objective and the
proportion of group revenues coming from outside the UK increased from 19
per cent to 27 per cent at the year end.
Gearing rose from 22 per cent to 32 per cent and net borrowings increased
from Pounds 2.8m to Pounds 4m by the year-end. Subsequently borrowings have
increased substantially, mainly because of corporation tax payments and the
settlement of creditors.
</TEXT>
