<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Company News: AT&amp;T unveils video/PC system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Telephone &amp; Telegraph yesterday unveiled a new, inexpensive desktop
business video system which allows two personal computer operators to see
each other on their computer screens while simultaneously talking and
manipulating data.
The product is not the first of its kind, but AT&amp;T's marketing muscle could
help this multi-media technology become much more widely accepted as a
business tool.
AT&amp;T yesterday committed its business video products to be based on globally
accepted standards for calls over digital phone lines, allowing its products
to work with others equipped with the same standards.
The company also said the product was one of the first large fruits of
collaboration between AT&amp;T's business communications unit, its
micro-electronics operation and NCR, the computer company acquired by AT&amp;T
in a hostile and controversial 1991 takeover.
The system, the first to employ AT&amp;T Microelectronics' AVP 4000 chipset for
compressing video images, produces slow motion pictures of about 10 frames
per second and operates through special AT&amp;T business switches or a digital
telephone line.
The cost of a unit starts at Dollars 6,995.
Delivery will begin in the US in the autumn and international marketing may
follow next year.
