<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Company News: Hongkong Land rises to Dollars
305m despite rental fall - Hong Kong Results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONGKONG Land, the Jardine Matheson group's property investment arm which
dominates Hong Kong's central office market, yesterday announced a 2.3 per
cent increase in net profits to USDollars 305m in 1992, up from Dollars
298.1m the year before.
The company confirmed it would exercise its option to increase its
shareholding in Trafalgar House, the UK construction, engineering and
shipping group, to 27 per cent from 20.1 per cent.
However, Mr Alisdair Morrison, managing director, said this would represent
only 6.5 per cent of shareholders' funds, and the group would continue to
focus on its core Hong Kong portfolio.
Hongkong Land, chaired by Mr Simon Keswick, will pay a final dividend of 6.5
US cents per share, representing a total 1992 dividend of 9.5 cents,
compared with 9 cents in 1991.
The company experienced a marginal fall in rental income last year as a
result of tenancies being renegotiated at below the property market's 1989
peak.
This phase will continue in 1993, with little growth expected. However, the
directors emphasised the 18 per cent increase to Dollars 1.95 in the
company's net asset value per share, as a result of the turnaround in office
property prices in 1992.
Hongkong Land sold its Number Nine Queen's Road tower block for USDollars
491m last year, but Mr Morrison said no other of the group's properties were
on the market.
He was confident that, with limited new supply of office space in the
central district, asset values would continue to rise.
The increase in last year's profits was due to a Dollars 18.7m reduction in
finance charges, as a result of debt reduction through property sales.
In 1993, the group will gain a maiden contribution from its Trafalgar House
investment, which will be equity accounted from April.
