<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Company News: Intel ships Pentium chip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL, the US semiconductor group, yesterday began officially shipping its
newest and most powerful personal computer microprocessor, the Pentium,
which is designed to preserve its status as the world's leading chip-maker
through much of the 1990s, writes Martin Dickson in New York.
The company said it would ship hundreds of thousands of Pentium
microprocessors this year, with volume passing the 1m mark in 1994. Intel
microprocessors are the brains for over 70 per cent of the world's personal
computers. The Pentium will provide increased power for applications such as
complex financial analysis and computer-aided design.
The Pentium contains 3.1m transistors, compared to 1.2m on Intel's current
486 model. It performs 112m instructions per second, making it five times
faster than the original 486.
