<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Company News: How the scheme works
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A TARGETED stock scheme does not involve any formal spin off of any assets
or operations, unlike a conventional demerger, where a company divides its
business into different legal entities.
Instead, the company - with agreement from existing shareholders - makes a
tax-free distribution of new shares designed to reflect the performance of
one division. The existing shares are usually renamed, and reflect
performance of the remaining operations.
Both series of shares are quoted, and the company notionally divides its
assets and liabilities between these two divisions. This allows it to report
separate financial results for each.
However, from a legal standpoint, relatively little changes. The company
remains responsible for all liabilities and assets, and the rights of
bondholders and other creditors are maintained. The different series of
stock vote together on corporate matters, such as the election of directors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Share issues.
    MGMT  Management.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
