FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Britannic Assurance slips 4% to Pounds
23.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITANNIC Assurance, the life assurance group, yesterday announced a 4 per
cent fall in total net profits for 1992 to Pounds 23.7m, from Pounds 24.7m
in the preceding year.
The shares dipped 40p to Pounds 13.03.
If last year's except-ional transfer of Pounds 4.9m from the industrial
branch is excluded, profits on life business increased from Pounds 19.5m to
Pounds 21.8m, helped by an increase in new premium income from single
premium pensions from Pounds 43.1m to Pounds 73.3m.
In the general branch, the group incurred a reduced loss of Pounds 205,000
(Pounds 2.3m).
Mr Roman Cizdyn, life insurance analyst at Smith New Court, said that he
felt the share price had been driven down thanks to over-enthusiastic buying
of small stocks in the preceding weeks.
The results were broadly in line with expectations, Mr Cizdyn said.
Earnings per share fell from 39.59p to 37.91p, but the dividend for the year
is increased by 13.6 per cent, to 33.5p, via a final of 23.35p.
The group also proposed a 2-for-1 scrip issue. Mr Brian Shaw, general
manager and actuary, said the unwieldy share price of more than Pounds 13
might deter private investors, although it would have little effect on
institutions.
