<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Fall in autumn sales hits Tay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFITS BEFORE tax at Tay Homes, the Leeds-based housebuilder, fell 43 per
cent to Pounds 1.03m in the half year to December 31 1992 following a slump
in autumn sales.
A rise in unit sales from 357 to 409 early in the period pushed turnover up
7 per cent, from Pounds 25.4m to Pounds 27.2m.
However, Mr Trevor Spencer, chairman, said demand collapsed in the period
covering October to December to as low as an average of 10 unit sales a
week.
January sales picked up to average levels of 38 per week, before faltering
around the beginning of March. However, figures had again picked up in the
past week.
A brighter outlook for the rest of the year, fuelled by low interest rates
and stabilising house prices, was undermined by continued narrow margins as
housebuilders maintained discount schemes to entice buyers.
The company, which in January issued a profits warning for the full year to
June 30 1993, said it did not anticipate a significant improvement in
conditions until its 1993-94 trading year.
Analysts' original profits forecasts of up to Pounds 6m pre-tax in the
current year have since been downgraded to about Pounds 3.5m.
The company said it had 4,000 plots in hand at an overall cost per plot of
about 15 per cent of present selling prices.
It said this should allow it to increase volumes and margins whenever an
upturn came.
Earnings per share were down from 5.5p to 3.04p. The interim dividend is
held at 1.2p.
