<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Delay on E&amp;A scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SCHEME of arrangement between English &amp; American, the London market
insurance company, and its creditors could take at least a year to
negotiate, according to Mr Tony McMahon of KPMG Peat Marwick, the
provisional liquidators.
Mr McMahon said the company had been hit by a rise in 'attritional' claims
on its marine book. Underwriters said last year that a rise in marine cargo
claims had caused a downturn in the company's fortunes. More recently it has
been forced to build up reserves against future marine liability claims.
E&amp;A's other insurance businesses, which include a run-off and insurance
management company, are unaffected by the developments.
Meanwhile, provisional liquidators of Trinity Insurance, another UK company
seeking to negotiate a scheme of arrangement, announced yesterday that the
scheme had been sanctioned in the courts. Mr Richard Boys-Stones and Mr
Colin Bird of Price Waterhouse have been appointed as scheme administrators.
</TEXT>
