<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Aitken out of US with Dollars 54m disposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AITKEN HUME International, the financial services and banking group, is to
pull out of the US market with the sale of its fund management business for
a maximum consideration of Dollars 54m (Pounds 38m).
The group, which in 1989 sold all but three of its diverse businesses in an
effort to stem losses, is left with just its private banking operations in
London and Guernsey.
Mr Ziad Idilby, chairman, said the group had not yet decided how it would
use the proceeds from the sale of National Securities &amp; Research
Corporation.
However, a statement issued yesterday said the group did not intend to use
the proceeds for acquisitions or expansion of existing businesses.
The sale price represented a significant increase over the Dollars 30m-plus
paid for the fund management business by Aitken in the early 1980s, Mr
Idilby said. 'It was more or less an offer we could not refuse.' The
disposal was the result of several approaches, either for NSR alone or for
Aitken Hume as a whole, received in recent months.
Aitken finally agreed to sell NSR - which manages some Dollars 2.7bn in
assets - to Phoenix Home Life Mutual Insurance. Last year NSR contributed
pre-tax profits of Dollars 4m on total income of Dollars 17.8m.
The deal bars Aitken from competing against Phoenix in the US mutual funds
industry.
A total of Dollars 14.8m will be held in escrow pending settlement of
certain outstanding issues. Mr Idilby added that the net asset value of the
group would be 67p a share after the disposal.
