<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (19):
Challenge for company culture - Business re-engineering: the need for
'totally new thinking'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OVER a decade ago, in 'Information Technology Year,' Kenneth Baker toured
the UK exhorting businesses to automate and change the entire way they
operated to increase productivity and gain new market opportunities.
The story goes that after one such speech in 1982 he was approached by a
small businessman who said: 'I'm so fired up by what you said that I'm going
straight out to buy an electric typewriter]'
Eleven years later this story is all too familiar to proponents of business
process re-engineering or any of the 20 other names for this idea which were
discovered in a recent survey.
'Companies are spending millions of pounds on applying information
technology to business processes which are donkey's years old and are
irrelevant to today's needs,' says Mr John Bennett, an executive director at
computing company ICL.
'Advances in technology mean that companies are enjoying huge improvements
in cost-performance of computers. Businesses have extensive telecom networks
and easily accessible databases. Yet despite the advances and the massive
investment in technology, office productivity has barely increased in the
last dozen years and in many cases has actually decreased,' he says.
Mr Bennett believes no more than five per cent of ICL customers are
seriously working on business re-engineering.
Mr David Harvey, a director of research firm Business Intelligence, which
recently published a 300-page report on business re-engineering*, says
information technology itself is part of the problem.
MOST businesses claim they are 'geared to constant change,' he says. 'But
too often the change is the wrong kind: the kind that props up a creaking
management process or functional structure and keeps it going for a few more
years, rather than replacing it with a system which works and is suited to
current needs. The result is management systems of growing complexity and
overhead.'
Information technology has been part of the problem, he says - 'as
administrative systems have grown in complexity, IT has been used to help
manage that complexity.'
Today's quest for more competitive companies with fewer layers of management
and administration has made business re-engineering a hot topic in the
1990s. An annual survey of senior executives in Europe by the consultancy
CSC Index found that this issue entered 'the top 20' at 17 in 1989 and
jumped to number one in 1990, staying in the top three since then.
Business re-engineering, according to the Business Intelligence report, is
the transformation of a company from one based on functions, such as
accounting, marketing and manufacturing, to one based on processes, such as
order processing and fulfilling customer expectations.
The study highlights the restrictions of traditional structures. Each
department focuses on what it contributes, not on what is needed as a whole.
There is competition between functions, for example for budgets and staff.
Staff identify with their function, rather than with the company as a whole.
There are barriers to co-operation between functions, and sometimes even
conflict. And a structure based on functions generates its own bureaucracy,
which is needed to co-ordinate work and the flow of documents between the
functions.
'Re-engineering challenges the underlying values and culture of a company,'
the report says. 'All the components of a company could be affected, because
re-engineering takes a holistic approach. Everything that affects outcomes -
organisation, processes, people, technologies - must be considered for
change.'
Mr Christopher Bell, a business re-engineering specialist at Andersen
Consulting, goes further: 'Question everything: there are no sacred cows,'
he says. 'Set dramatic targets and think of dramatic ways of reaching them.'
All this is a considerable challenge and there can be no textbook approach.
Christopher Bell underlines the need for totally new thinking when looking
at re-engineering.
'Go wild with ideas,' he says. 'Look at brain-storming meetings, suggestion
boxes, workshops, industry 'best practice,' confession meetings,
consultants, focus groups: any technique to generate new ideas to do things
differently.'
Even so, it is worth identifying specific areas which are ripe for
re-engineering - and the resultant re-engineering need not be too
earth-shattering. Rank Xerox, for example, cut the time to bill special
contracts from more than three months to just one day, largely by
simplifying the flow of documents around the company. This was part of a
wider corporate re-engineering in the UK.
Christopher Bell at Andersen Consulting and David Harvey at Business
Intelligence emphasise activities which focus on customers and the quality
of products and services delivered to them.
Mr Harvey points to the typical arrangement where a customer enquiry at a
branch generates a request for information to a particular department, which
sends back the reply, which generates a further enquiry based on the
information, so that enquiry goes to another department and so on.
A variation on this theme is when too many staff in different departments
deal with the same customer or supplier.
THE Business Intelligence research highlights IT as key to business
re-engineering. Others agree. At the simplest level, IT enables departments
to share information through an on-line database, breaking down barriers and
jealously guarded departmental ownership of data.
Electronic data interchange, the exchange of orders, invoices and sales
forecasts between computers, is transforming relationships between trading
partners and eliminating paper-handling. And often such systems will just be
the starting point for business re-engineering.
'The IT function must no longer be seen as the unit which mulls over whether
the company should go for the Unix operating system,' says John Bennett at
ICL. 'The emphasis now must be on how the function can play its part in the
future of the enterprise.'
David Harvey at Business Intelligence agrees: 'The relationship between IT
and the rest of the company must be completely different from that of the
past. In the past it has been a stand-alone department, often detached from
business thinking. It must now be part of the team which helps shape the
business re-engineering programme.'
He adds: 'The IT director should be more pro-active. Senior executives are
unable to think of their business and processes in terms of anything more
than today's - and probably yesterday's - technologies, because they are not
told how new technologies can make possible what has previously been
impossible.
'Whose fault is this? If the buck does not stop with the IT director, it is
hard to think where it should stop.'
Business Re-engineering. Pounds 395. Business Intelligence, telephone
081-544 1830.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-2000</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWABXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (20):
Force for radical change - Software: object-oriented technology will lead to
upheavals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE abstract and esoteric world of computer software shares one thing in
common with the real world; it has the equivalent of an 'ecology.' And, like
the real world, the structure of this ecology is subject to changes and
shifts as a result of external pressures. Advances in hardware technology,
increased user-demand and straightforward improvements in software itself
have come together to create a force for radical change in the ecology of
the software world in the last few years. Experts talk of 'paradigm shifts'
and 'revolutions.'
At the heart of this upheaval is a new way of thinking about information
technology called object-oriented technology. It aims to define a new
approach to the design and construction of information systems and the
software which supports them.
The ecology of the software world defines the relationships between the
building blocks of modern computer systems. It includes everything from the
basic operating software, which controls the internal workings of the
system, to the graphics-based 'front end' interface which the user sees.
Traditionally, these components have been closely tied to each other,
overlapped in their functionality and been mainly concerned with internal
technology issues such as performance and system efficiency.
By contrast, the object-oriented approach aims to separate software into a
set of components according to their function and define ways in which they
can talk to each other.
Traditional engineering provides an analogy. Engineers see a motor vehicle,
a washing machine or, for that matter, a computer system, as a series of
components which are connected together to create the finished product. Each
of the components - a motor, an electronic controller, and so on - has a
pre-defined function and standard links to connect it to other components.
SYSTEMS designers and software engineers can use the object-oriented
approach in the same way to re-define the ecology of computer software.
Object-oriented also introduces several new ideas to thinking about computer
software. Objects can, for example, be 're-used' in other applications. New
objects can be created easily from existing objects. As a result, it
promises to improve programmer productivity and make long-term maintenance
easier.
Object-oriented technology is gaining ground - both among suppliers, which
see it as an opportunity to expand the scope of information technology
products, and among users who see it as a better way to solve their
information processing problems.
UK market research company Ovum forecasts staggering growth in the market
for object-oriented technology between now and 1997. Last year the combined
US/European market for object-oriented software - including development
tools, languages and databases - was worth Dollars 865m. This will rise to
over Dollars 4bn by 1997 and, although the annual growth rate will have
fallen back from its current high of 69 per cent, it will still stand at 27
per cent a year.
The rush to move into object-oriented technology is confirmed by other
sources. The Object Management Group (OMG), an organisation founded in 1989
to promote the cause, reports that the embryonic US market for
object-oriented databases grew from Dollars 18m in 1991 to Dollars 60m last
year.
Mr Christopher Stone, president of OMG, says: 'Compared with the early
growth rates for relational database technology about ten years ago - this
represents a high early acceptance of object-oriented systems.'
The level of interest is also reflected in the growth of the OMG itself. It
now has over 300 members, including all of the leading hardware and software
companies from IBM to Microsoft. Mr Stone also reports an upsurge of
interest from user organisations.
This year, there are three big conference/exhibitions taking place in the UK
alone - including the OMG-sponsored Objectworld. This level of interest is
reflected throughout Europe and the US.
There is good cause for this strong interest in object-oriented technology.
It promises to change the ecology of software for the better and correct
many mistakes of the past.
Mr Steven Cook, managing director of the UK object-oriented software
specialist Object Designers, sees the level of interest moving from the
exploratory to the pragmatic: 'We founded our company to help large users
make strategic long-term decisions about object-oriented technology. Their
position has shifted noticeably from asking what it is to asking how it can
be done.'
MR COOK is the chairman of the Object Technology 93 conference in Cambridge
at the end of March and notes that prospective attendees are asking
practical questions: 'Object technology is obviously going to effect the
whole ecology of software and applications. Users want to know what is going
to happen.'
'There is a stage when the penny drops and people start to realize how
powerful object technology can be,' explains Paul Fitzgibbon, marketing
director with UK software company Protek.
Some users are already building systems using the object-oriented approach.
Kredietbank in Belgium has started a pilot project to analyse balance sheets
using the approach. It uses Hitachi's Object IQ development package running
on a network of Hewlett Packard computers.
'We chose ObjectIQ - not for its object-oriented capabilities but its
rule-processing features,' explains Dr Marc de Brabanter, head of
Kredietbank's research and development team.
'We've long-term plans to use more object-oriented techniques - but these
are driven by the business. The tools we want just happen to be
object-oriented,' Dr De Brabanter adds.
Few users have reached this stage of course. But with the growing bandwagon
and the inevitable surge in marketing hype, it will not be long before users
will have to take account of the new ecology for software.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Technology.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-2001</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWABWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (18):
Bridge between east and west - The new Nordic-Russian telecommunications
joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LINDSAY NICOLLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUMANS may have pulled down the Berlin Wall but it is telecommunications
that is now building the bridge between east and west.
'We hope to overcome the communications barriers between east and west and
make it possible for companies in eastern Europe to work in the western
way,' explains Mr Tapio Paarma, head of an international project to build
and run advanced mobile telephone and data communications services in the
key commercial centre of St Petersburg and its surrounding area.
The service will open up international communications for the 200-300
western companies which have already moved into St Petersburg, such as
Barclays Bank, Credit Lyonnais, Deutsche Bank and Western hotel and
restaurant chains.
The service has gone live for voice but it will be two to three years before
the full data telecommunications network is complete. Mr Paarma expects to
have 100,000 subscribers by 1998.
Russia needs to catch up quickly in telecommunications: its services are
currently based on antiquated telephone exchanges with inadequate capacity.
ADVANCED western mobile technology is considered the quickest and most
cost-effective way of updating Russia's communications while maintaining
some level of service. Radio communications are regarded worldwide as the
natural successor to traditional fixed-link communications in the longer
term.
'The Russians are learning English very quickly and are extremely keen to
understand western telecom technology,' says Mr Carl-Fredrik Geust, Russia
area director of Telecom Finland, which is leading the consortium running
the St Petersburg project.
'They already have the western way of thinking about market economics: St
Petersburg is one big flea market with street-buying and selling. They just
need the telecommunications infrastructure to express it.'
The advanced technology being adopted is the Global System for Mobile
Communication. GSM is a 1980s Scandinavian vision of a pan-European mobile
telecommunications network based on digital technology which already
provides stable voice services and will handle data in the near future.
Data can already be sent on analogue mobile systems but such systems are not
reliable enough. The sender must be stationary and have a good radio path to
the receiving base station - small electrical cabinets which operate
unattended. The base station relays the data to the telephone exchange.
With digital GSM, data transmission will be much easier and safer. The
laptop computer of the future will have an inbuilt GSM mobile station and a
rod aerial at the side. The sender will dial the destination using the
keyboard. A computer-controlled digital exchange will identify the sender
from its database and route the call and its bill simultaneously.
St Petersburg is a key centre in the total Russian network. It has been the
gateway to Russia since the time of Peter the Great and is one of the most
advanced ex-communist cities in terms of western business development. Its
proximity to Russia's only north-west seaboard guarantees its future
commercial success if its telecommunications infrastructure can be
overhauled.
Telecom Finland's Nordic-Russian consortium that has been awarded the
licence to operate the telecom service in this area includes Swedish Telecom
International and Norwegian Telecom, plus the St Petersburg Trunk Line
Exchange and Leningrad Regional Posts and Telecommunications Administration
(which still prefers the old Communist name for the city).
The consortium won the contract in January against stiff opposition from US
and European telecom groups.
The total cost of the network has been estimated at USDollars 160m. Funding
is expected to come from international telecom operators and banks and from
aid organisations like the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
Telecom equipment manufacturers around the world will hear shortly which of
them have been chosen to provide the bulk of the technology, while the
Russians will donate their local expertise and exchange equipment, masts and
antennae.
An optical fibre cable between Helsinki and St Petersburg will carry the GSM
and old analogue traffic when it passes tests now being carried out. It will
provide unlimited transmission capacity compared to the current 64 kilobits
which carries international telephone connections and packet switched data
services, thanks to another Finnish-Russian venture.
When the Russians elected last year to grant 12 GSM licences to companies to
develop GSM networks, Nordic operators were high on the list because they
have much experience of developing communications to remote and inaccessible
regions.
Finland is ideally situated next to its friendly Russian neighbours. The St
Petersburg GSM area is only 150 kilometres from the Finnish border. The
entire Finnish population of 5m is less than the 7.5m potential subscribers
in the St Petersburg area alone.
Some say this last factor - relative size - influenced the Russians not to
award the vital St Petersburg licence to US telecom giant US West
International, which won eight of the other licences and the responsibility
for GSM co-ordination across Russia. St Petersburg, they say, is 'too key a
commercial area to trust to the Americans.'
Such Cold War memories are mutual. Western security services are currently
scrutinising GSM networks to ensure that inbuilt encryption techniques are
not so good that they render the networks untappable. They have the
authority to ban the export of highly secure GSM equipment to 'enemy' states
if they choose.
But Mr Geust at Telecom Finland does not think the security issue will deter
business take-up of GSM: 'I'm sure that regardless of what encryption
algorithms are inherent in the system, organisations such as banks will
probably have their own encryption equipment at both ends of the network:
no-one trusts outside equipment anyway.'
ANOTHER unresolved issue shadowing the progress of GSM worldwide and
separating the US from the Europeans is the choice of digital technology.
For global mobile telephony and data transmission to work, clearly everyone
ought to agree on a standard technology. Wisely, equipment manufacturers are
developing systems to suit both camps. They already have their eye on the
GSM replacement, the futuristic Universal Mobile Telecommunications System.
Meanwhile the St Petersburg partners' first aim is to get the initial
service fully live. Even so, they are already looking to exploit the data
service to the full.
'There is now pressure from the international market and especially from the
Russians to have improved voice and high-speed data transmission,' says Mr
Geust. 'Database access, the transmission of high resolution pictures and
graphics - these are our next challenges.'
</TEXT>
