<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (16):
Reducing the paper mountains - The Electronic Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOIA SHILLINGFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST when you thought it was safe to joke about the 'paperless office,' the
convergence of a number of technologies is making it possible.
Early attempts at the paperless office failed because no matter how many
computers a company bought, paper kept arriving in the post.
But now a number of companies are starting to store both incoming mail and
computer files electronically. They include Nirex, the UK company tasked
with finding long-term storage for Britain's nuclear waste, IBM systems
house Triangle Computers and the mortgage department of Barclays Bank.
Later this month, scientists at Nirex will receive all their post
electronically. The contents of their filing cabinets are also being turned
into electronic files. So in future when they need information, they will be
able to use a database (a computer-based library) to retrieve all the
information available, whether it be letters, in house reports or external
research.
No-one wants a nuclear waste repository nearby and Nirex's ability to
respond quickly and efficiently to questions about safety could determine
the success or failure of its plan to site the repository at Sellafield.
The idea is that the system will provide a single-source of information,
both for office work and for operational tasks, such as construction and
maintenance. It will be one of the first systems to do this.
Yusef Eisa, the company's new information technology (IT) director, says:
'The data contained in the system will constitute the corporate memory and
is therefore an important asset. Information on the nuclear waste repository
will have to be kept indefinitely because future generations may need to
look at it.'
Nirex's system (called Fred - for Fast Retrieval Electronic Database)
illustrates the way different technologies are coming together. It is a
combination of established and emerging tools combined in a new way by two
UK-based suppliers: image processing company Trimco and free-text specialist
Kinesis.
The tools include:
Traditional office automation products, such as wordprocessing and
electronic mail.
Personal computers (PCs) connected by a network.
Image processing. This enables paper documents (including any
signatures/graphics) to be turned into electronic images, which can be
displayed on a computer screen.
Optical character read (OCR) technology. This is being used to 'read'
electronic images (which can't be altered) and turn them into computer
files, which can be edited.
Structured and free-text databases. Structured databases allow users to look
for specific information, such as everything received on a particular date,
or written by a particular person. Free-text databases are useful for
retrieving everything written about a specific topic, eg'reprocessing
plants.'
Workflow software. This helps to route information automatically between
workers involved in a common process and improve the information flow.
High-quality graphics and computer-aided design software. This will enable
engineering drawings, designs and maps (for both construction and planned
maintenance) to be included in the second phase of the project.
Groupware software (which supports team work). For example, Nirex plans to
use 'red-lining' - a form of shared editing - to underline and add margin
notes to online reports and drawings which have to be approved by several
people.
How it works
Paper-based information, such as a letter, will be scanned into the new
system. An electronic image of the letter will appear on a large screen in
the mailroom. Then the post clerk will key basic details about the letter
(such as date, author of letter, and addressee) into an Oracle database
index.
The image will then be sent to a queue on a Sun workstation. From there, OCR
software will produce a text file of the image. The image and its associated
text file will then be forwarded to a specific department, where further
words will be typed into a structured index.
Finally, the image of the letter will be stored on an optical disk and the
text version will be loaded into the BRS/Search database.
In the second phase of the project, it will also be possible to load
wordprocessed documents into the free-text database very easily. And to link
them with other files. For example, an outgoing letter might be linked with
an incoming letter. The idea is that when a user carries out either a
structured or a free-text search, he/she will get as full an answer as
possible. If a structured search does not retrieve the information required,
the user can try a free-text search - or vice versa. In addition to database
searches, users will be able to send each other images via electronic mail.
Groupware benefits
However, Nirex's approach is not the only way of reducing the paper
mountain. According to Roger Whitehead, editor of the Groupware News
newsletter: 'Many different combinations of old-fashioned office automation
and new-fangled groupware products can support new ways of office working.
They can help conquer the boundaries of time and space, enabling people who
are normally separated by different time zones or different locations to
work together on the same project.' Typical groupware applications include
workflow; shared editing systems; group decision support; and conferencing
and information management.
For example, last month Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch multinational decided to
use Lotus Notes (one of the best-known groupware products) to break down
communications barriers between its international offices. Notes provides
information management as well as information distribution and can be used
to exchange graphics, photographs, figures and text.
Unilever expects to have over 10,000 Notes users. Mike Johnson, worldwide
head of IT at Unilever, says it will be used to 'support team-working, and
the sharing of information from desk-to-desk, worldwide.'
This will reduce the paper flow. But Triangle Computers, a Notes reseller,
has decided to dispense with paper altogether. Every piece of information
that comes into the company, gets scanned into Notes and thrown away.
Douglas Drysdale, the company's technical director, says: 'People are
basically lazy. They make better use of information if it is at their
fingertips, rather than a short walk away in a filing cabinet. In the end,
it boils down to efficiency.'
For some, reducing the paper mountain can open up new business
opportunities. Barclays Bank's Intermortgage division has started to use
Filenet imaging technology to convert its mortgage correspondence files into
electronic documents. This has speeded up the time taken to approve mortgage
applications and cut costs. Before long, it plans to process all loans
electronically.
Gordon Charlesworth, who is responsible for image processing at the division
says: 'In the third and fourth quarter of this year, we will start scanning
all the post that arrives in the mail room in to the image processing
system. This will be phased in a department at a time.'
As the division's processing costs have fallen, it has started to attract
business processing mortgages for other lenders. It hopes to win more
business of this kind in future.
Changes in technology could mean that the paperless office becomes less of a
laughing matter and more of a serious competitive advantage.
The writer is editor of the Financial Times newsletter, The Electronic
Office.
</TEXT>
