<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (14):
Faster and cheaper data links - Wide Area Networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIE HARNETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WIDE area networks (WANs), using high-speed private or public
telecommunications lines, are common among large organisations needing an
efficient and cheap method of information exchange between head office and
branches.
There are various means of achieving the links using multiplexers, modems
and packet switched technologies. The transport mechanisms used by most
companies requiring a degree of information security are leased circuits
from Mercury or BT (eg KiloStream or MegaStream) for point-to-point
connections or X25 for multi-site connections.
Choice is largely dependent on distance between the various sites, traffic
volumes and data transfer rates needed. However, with downsizing driving the
move towards multiple LANs and distributed computing, it is unlikely that
the traditional WAN will be able to cope.
Increasingly, computer-users need to be able to work on collaborative
projects and communicate with colleagues as easily as if they were sitting
at the next desk, no matter where they are located and no matter how many
network gateways, bridges and servers they have to be routed through.
Interconnection with seamless, real-time inter-operability are key.
The Enterprise Wide Network (EWN) of tomorrow will, then, need to be based
on high-speed transport mechanisms capable of providing the aggregate
network bandwidth required for increasingly popular workgroup applications
such as CAD/CAM and real-time full-colour multimedia, as well as corporate
workflow applications such as video-conferencing, multiple messaging
services and EDI (electronic data interchange).
That data communications will increase for most organisations there appears
no doubt. This is highlighted by a report published by network specialists
3Com, entitled The Myth of the Global Village, which shows that 81 per cent
of companies expect their data communications across Europe will increase
over the next 12 months, with 20 per cent expecting an increase of over 100
per cent.
Tom Plimmer, managing director of 3Com UK notes: 'Few have the network
infrastructure capable of supporting that expansion. Very soon, companies
will find themselves facing unforeseen and therefore unmanageable and very
costly network growth.'
The answer?
'Rather than be overwhelmed and held back by over complex implementations,
they will need to form new partnerships with (networking) suppliers and
integrators,' he says.
Don Parry, manager of customer systems, Mercury Communications, agrees: 'It
is even more important now that integrated voice and data solutions are, at
last, deliverable. The WAN marketplace has been very fragmented, with some
market leaders going through some disturbing periods of instability.
'What customers need to do is follow the example of organisations like BT
and Mercury and look for partners with a solid foundation they can have
confidence in, can understand their business aspirations and can offer
flexible, standards compliant solutions.'
IF the Enterprise Wide Network is set to become the central nervous system
without which no corporate body will be able to function nor grow, what are
the standards-compliant, multiplexed broadband solutions of the future?
Most R&amp;D investment, it seems, is being directed towards Frame Relay, ATM
(Asynchronous Transfer Mode) and SDH (Synchronous Digital Hierarchy). Market
research organisation, Frost &amp; Sullivan, believes that it is these more
robust OSI (Opens Systems Interconnect) standards, when finalised, that will
take market share from currently available but functionally limited
standards like TCP/IP (Transaction Control Program/Internet Protocol) and
SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol).
According to a new Frost &amp; Sullivan report,* fast packet switching, as it is
generically known, is forecast to rise in value from USDollars 74m in 1992
to more than USDollars 2bn by the end of 1997. Within that period, shipments
of frame relay are set to treble from the current value of USDollars 166.5m.
Because of its ability to switch both voice, data, image and video, analysts
forecast that the European market for ATM/cell relay technology will grow
even more dramatically, rising from USDollars 51m in 1992 to over USDollars
1.17bn by 1997.
Frame relay is ideal for complex, geographically dispersed networks. Based
on Open Systems Interconnect (OSI) standards, frame relay enables WAN
managers to consolidate traffic from multiple protocol environments over a
single circuit. Above all, it provides bandwidth on demand at speeds over
ten times faster than X25 packet switching.
Steve Priestley, UK sales manager at Dynatech Communications, says: 'We
firmly believe that frame relay will become the network of the future
because it has so many obvious advantages. It enables different applications
and protocols to be transported transparently across the network. Coupled
with this, it reduces bandwidth costs and can offer substantial savings to
heavy networks users.'
Private network managers have been among the first to consolidate traffic
over existing lines with frame relay, according to Robert McGuire, technical
director at Ascom Timeplex.
This, he says, is 'because the capital investment pays off quickly and the
additional cost of adding more facilities that need more bandwidth is
delayed. If connecting remote locations to the backbone involves fairly high
leased line charges then public frame relay becomes an attractive
alternative.'
But as promising as frame relay is, says McGuire, it is no panacea - 'like
all technologies, it provides dramatic benefits where it is deployed in the
correct setting to achieve realistic goals.
'Frame relay is ideal for WAN traffic originating from LANs, but it is not
deemed appropriate, for example, for time-critical transfer of financial
information, where point-to-point leased lines would be a better, more
secure option.'
Similarly, 'X25 packet switching would provide ample throughput rates where
the network consists primarily of cluster controllers for host terminal or
other low-speed transmissions.'
ATM makes the ultimate goal of seamless enterprise wide networks a reality,
say its proponents, because it means there is no longer any need to run two
separate and non-interlinked networks.
The only problem with ATM is that the CCITT standards have not been yet
finalised. Nevertheless, the 150 members of the ATM Forum are pressing ahead
with systems developments that can be upgraded in the field via software.
The first implementations will be on private networks. It will then take 18
months before ATM is generally available. Only then, it is said, will the
bandwagon effect take over.
By launching a very low-cost ATM LAN solution, SynOptics aims to be at the
forefront of that. Product line manager, Robert Newman, cites the benefits
of ATM when it becomes available at WAN level:
Massive performance increases, with high-speed dedicated connections and
high aggregate network bandwidth.
Flexible breakthroughs, with scalable end-node connection speed, scaleable
aggregate network bandwidth; and global workgroups through WANS.
Data and real-time multi-media support.
Standards shared by local and public network vendors.
Enhanced management and control.
Newman adds: 'The initial drive for ATM is coming from graphics-intensive
users on LANs who, individually, may only need file transfer at 10Mbps but,
collectively, need 100Mbps or more if bottlenecks are not to bring projects
to a grinding halt.
'With an X25 WAN you drop down to 56Kbps and that does not make sense.
ATM provides 155Mbits per second.'
There are a number of initiatives underway. For example, GPT, Siemens and BT
are set to deploy Metropolitan Area Networks (MANs), heralded as the first
evolutionary step towards ATM broadband networks of tomorrow. AT&amp;T, Cisco
and Stratacom have just announced that they will be working together to
launch products for the first public full ATM service in the UK.
Northern Telecom believes that the ability to support both narrowband and
wideband applications within a consolidated network of the future is
crucial, hence the development of Magellan Passport. Its frame-switching
capabilities within an open architecture deliver cost-effective bandwidth
utilisation for data communications, while its cell capabilities allow
consolidation of bursty, high-speed data with delay-sensitive voice and
video.
* The European Market for Frame Relay and Broadband, E1737, USDollars 3,500
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P3661 Telephone and Telegraph Apparatus.
    P7373 Computer Integrated Systems Design.
    P481  Telephone Communications.
</IN>
<XX>
