<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWABPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (12): US
businesses are leading the way - Virtual Private Networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MONICA HORTEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN in the age of the global corporation, human behaviour is slow to
change: many people have a mental block about phoning their colleagues, just
because they have to use an international dialling code.
According to Robert Taylor, consulting manager in international
communications at pharmaceutical company SmithKline Beecham, such reluctance
to make international calls creates a geographic barrier. This can limit the
progress of a company - 'if a company manufactures a product in one part of
the world, and someone in another part of the world wants to use the same
techniques, why not share that knowledge?' he says.
Mr Taylor believes that a new-style phone service, known as a virtual
private network or VPN, could go a long way to solving the problem. A
virtual private network offers businesses a way to link the switchboards on
different office sites, without having the expense of installing and running
their own private network.
In its most basic form, a VPN means that staff can use short code internal
phone numbers to any of the sites which are connected. Those sites could
even be in a different country. More sophisticated VPNs also permit the
system to call back when an engaged number becomes free, or to display the
number of the person calling.
Such facilities won't be new to British or US companies which have had
private telephone networks for several years. But in countries such as
France and Germany, VPNs will be the first opportunity for many companies to
obtain an advanced telephone capability.
Barclays Bank was the first organisation to sign up for British Telecom's
VPN service. John Grimmett, chief executive of Barclays Network Services,
wants to use the VPN to expand the private network facilities to many of the
bank's smaller branches where a private line is not viable.
Mr Grimmett was also attracted by the flexibility of the VPN, which be
dynamically re-configured to handle business changes within the bank.
For example, the bank might operate a payment service out of six branches in
the London area, but wants to concentrate the processing in just one of
them. Customers, on the other hand, should not have to be told to re-dial if
they call their branch with query.
Using the VPN, calls can be transferred internally, and it appears to the
customers that everything takes place in their branch.
Another VPN convert is French chemical company, Rhone Poulenc. It took the
decision on the basis of cost: for competitive reasons, most telephone
companies are pricing their VPN services at a discount to both private and
public network facilities.
'In France, the company did a full-cost analysis, looking at private
networks compared with VPN, and was initially surprised at the savings,'
said Peter Hewitt, telecom manager for the company's UK operations.
The Rhone Poulenc vpn stretches across four countries and is one of the
first to set up international links. It currently comprises BT's Featurenet
in the UK, France Telecom's Colissee service, MCI's V-Net in the US, and
KDD's Virnet in Japan. So far, 26 sites in France, 80 in the US, three in
the UK, and four in Japan have been hooked up.
Links between the VPNs in each country have been set up by the phone
companies. This means that Rhone Poulenc obtains the same facilities on
international calls as on national calls. Thus, French employees only have
to dial a seven-digit number to reach colleagues in the UK. And if they fly
to the US office, and want to call the same people, they dial the same seven
digits.
It's too early, however, to say how popular the facility will be: the UK
sites have only been connected since December last year. However, monitoring
of calling patterns in France has shown that employees are gradually getting
into the habit of calling via the VPN, although the total number of calls
has not increased.
Mr Hewitt also believes that he will make significant savings on the annual
telephone bill in the UK. He said that BT's VPN tariffs offer a 25 per
discount on international calls, and almost half of the company's UK phone
calls are to its own locations abroad.
Although some phone companies do publish VPN tariffs, most international VPN
contracts are individually negotiated. Susan Ablett, an analyst with
specialist research company Analysys of Cambridge, believes that corporate
customers are now in a position where they can use their financial muscle to
obtain good deals on VPNs - 'we say to them to use their negotiating power.
They are in a powerful position now to bring down prices, which they weren't
two years' ago,' she says.
However, Mr Taylor believes that the European phone companies could do more
to make their VPN services attractive. SmithKline Beecham is an active user
of VPN services in the US, and he is looking at possibilities for the Cable
and Wireless-Sprint joint venture known as global virtual private network
(GVPN).
In his view, the US phone companies provide better support for customers.
For example, their staff work full-time on the customer's premises. They
also provide bigger discounts for high-volume corporate customers. He would
like to see similar customer support and incentives offered on this side of
the Atlantic.
But the US market for VPNs is much more mature than in Europe, and was worth
an estimated Dollars 2.5bn in 1992. It grew up rapidly in the late 1980s,
when the three phone companies, MCI, Sprint and AT&amp;T waged a price-cutting
war.
Today, the market research company Yankee Group estimates that US customers
can get discounts of up to 38 per cent can be obtained on five-year
contracts.
Further deals are offered to customers interested in calling card or free
phone facilities - for example, sales reps are given a calling card and PIN
number, so that they can call the office from anywhere, and the call travels
via the VPN.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
