<DOCNO>FT931-2010</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWABNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (8):
Prizes to the value of Pounds 20,000 - Competition: Business Software
Challenge '90s
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S young software writers have the chance to win prizes to the value
of Pounds 20,000, plus a range of hardware and software, in this year's
'Business Software Challenge '90s,' the results of which will be covered
later this year in the FT's quarterly review of business software, Software
at Work.
The competition is sponsored and funded by software vendor, Computer
Associates, which founded it two years ago as a way of encouraging students
to write applications to solve real business problems. Also giving their
support are the British Computer Society, Coopers &amp; Lybrand and the
Institute of Management.
The competition is aimed at students in higher education, working
individually or in teams, and recent graduates. They are invited to submit
current work which solves a specific, defined, business problem. There is no
definition of what applications are appropriate, but judges look for robust,
working solutions and a clear explanation of the business benefits.
The software should run on a commonly available computer, and integrate with
other relevant software where applicable. Entrants must be able to
demonstrate how their design addresses a particular problem.
Entries close on August 27.
Previous winners
Winners in previous years have been responsible for a number of highly
promising products, and some have gone on to full-time careers in software
design. The 1992 winner was a system by Stephen Marshall at the University
of Sheffield which helped medical staff make accurate diagnoses of patients
suffering heart attacks.
Prize-winners in the past have received help in taking their products to the
appropriate marketplace. Computer Associates retains no rights of any sort,
however, over the software submitted.
For more information, and an explanatory booklet, apply to:
The Competition Secretary
'Business Software
Challenge 90s,'
24-24 Bloomsbury Way
LONDON WC1A 2PX
Telephone: 071 831 6262.
Fax: 071 831 0639.
