<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (7):
Software becomes the key success factor - Telecommunications in transition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TECHNOLOGY has provided the building blocks for the telecommunications
systems of the 1990s, but the industry will enter the next century shaped as
much by political and economic forces which are pushing towards
privatisation, liberalisation and globalisation, writes Paul Taylor.
Highly protected national post and telecommunications organisations (PTOs)
controlled most domestic and international telecommunications traffic until
recently and had little incentive to improve efficiency, introduce new
services or cut customer charges.
But in the the wake of the court-appointed break-up of the Bell system in
the US in the early 1980s other countries, led by the UK in Europe and Japan
in the Far East, have begun to adopt policies designed to foster
competition.
The results have been impressive. In those countries which have liberalised
their telecom regimes, competition has led to a wider range of higher
quality services, lower prices and larger markets.
In Europe, however, liberalisation and privatisation have been a largely
British phenomenon so far. But this may be about to change.
The UK remains the only EC country with two PTOs, although Germany and
France have both introduced competition into mobile telephony and satellite
links. Most countries, including Germany, also have full or partial
privatisation plans for their PTOs. In Germany, for example, talks between
the coalition government and the opposition on the privatisation of Deutsche
Telekom, the German state telephone monopoly, re-opened earlier this month.
At the regional level, the European Commission is just completing nearly six
months of consultations with the industry, consumers, regulators and member
states on the future direction of EC telecommunications policy.
The Commission has long advocated liberalisation but has only been able to
proceed at the pace of its slowest member. So far, it has only required
competition in terminal equipment and data services and not in basic voice
telephony - which represents the bulk of the Ecu 110bn European telecoms
market.
Publication of a Commission report on future telecommunications policy was
twice delayed last summer, partly because of concern about its impact on the
French Maastricht referendum. When it was finally published in October it
laid out four options for the next wave of legislation, ranging from doing
nothing to full liberalisation.
Initially, commissioners favoured a cautious approach, opening cross-border
calls within the EC to competition as a first step. However, senior
Commission officials now appear to believe the next wave of EC telecoms
legislation should go further.
They have been encouraged by signs that the mood of the industry is
gradually changing towards supporting the opening all telecommunications
traffic to competition, albeit with competition phased over a period as long
as 10 years.
IN its response, BT urged the Commission to open the European telecoms
market to free competition by issuing a directive that would force
liberalisation on EC members by January 1, 1995.
Mercury Communications took a slightly less strident view, emphasising that
while it supports moves towards rapid liberalisation of public voice
services and underlying infrastructure throughout the Community, it also
believes that process should be phased in beginning with measures to allow
competition for cross-border voice services and infrastructure, followed by
full liberalisation of national and international voice services and
infrastructure.
Mr Terry Rhodes, Mercury's director of competition policy, argues that in
order to foster competition new entrants 'need time to establish their
operations.' Thus, Mercury emphasises that regulation plays a crucial role
in bridging the gap between monopoly and effective competition in order to
ensure that customers are protected from abuse of market power, and that
market conditions encourage the introduction of effective and economic
competition.
A decision on whether to press for a full liberalisation and harmonisation
of voice telephony in the EC is due around mid-May and will be taken by the
17 commissioners, advised by Mr Martin Bangemann, EC commissioner for
industry and telecommunications, and Mr Karel van Miert, responsible for
competition.
The outcome is a matter of considerable speculation at present, not least
because Mr Bangemann has only recently added responsibility for
telecommunications policy to his industry portfolio and Mr van Miert, a
Belgian socialist, has recently taken over competition policy from Sir Leon
Brittan.
In the meantime, the EC faces a more immediate challenge over public
procurement policy from the US. The new Clinton administration has
threatened to block EC companies from bidding for millions of dollars' worth
of US government contracts in retaliation for what the US says is EC
discrimination against US sales of telecommunications and power-generating
equipment.
Trade friction could also delay or derail plans by equipment manufacturers
and telecommunications operators on both sides of the Atlantic to compete
directly against each other as part of their emerging global strategies.
For example, Northern Telecom, the Canadian equipment manufacturer, has
established a strong presence in Europe following its acquisition of STC,
and Bell Canada's parent BCE has acquired a 20 per cent stake in Mercury
Communications. As part of that deal, Cable &amp; Wireless, Mercury's parent,
has become a partner in BCE's UK cable TV business. In addition, a number of
US-based companies have won mobile telephony licences in Europe.
However, particular attention is focused on BT's emerging global strategy.
The group already has already established Syncordia, an Atlanta,
Georgia-based network management company, and earlier this month applied to
the US regulatory authorities for permission to operate domestic and
international telephone services in the US.
If approval is given, it will clear the way for BT to become the first
international telecommunications operator able to provide multinational
customers with a broad range of voice, data and video services between the
US and the UK.
However the application faces stiff opposition from BT's US competitors,
AT&amp;T, MCI and Sprint, who are likely to argue that US carriers do not enjoy
a similar freedom to operate in the UK. The outcome of BT's application will
therefore depend on discussions over reciprocal market access between the US
Federal Communications Commission and Britain's Department of Trade and
Industry.
In the UK market itself, BT still has over 90 per cent of the domestic
market eight years after privatisation and 10 years after Mercury
Communications began opertions. However, the duopoly faces new competition
from domestic and foreign-owned competitors in the wake of 1991 review
conducted by Oftel, the industry regulator.
Last month, Ionica, a Cambridge-based company backed by institutional and
corporate shareholders, was licensed to set up a radio-based rival national
telephone service. Ionica aims to win five per cent of its target household
and small business markets within 10 years. As many as 30 more license
applications are being considered by the Department of Trade and Industry.
Oftel plans to ease some licence conditions for new entrants to the telecoms
marketplace, in particular newcomers are not expected to have any social or
universal service obligations.
Moves like this are designed to keep up the pressure on BT's dominant market
position. As Mr Bill Wigglesworth, deputy director of Oftel said recently:
'When you move to unlimited competition, market dominance is the issue. That
means BT should be licensed more tightly.'
However, BT has been protesting loudly about what it considers to be
excessive regulatory control. More cynical observers have suggested that
BT's grumbles have been timed to co-incide with the arrival at the start of
next month of Oftel's new director general, Mr Don Cruickshank.
Among his first tasks, Mr Cruickshank will have to tackle the contentious
issue of imposing accounting separation on BT. This is considered vital in
securing fair agreements for other telecom companies which need to connect
into BT's network.
In the UK, therefore, as elsewhere, it seems that politics and regulations
will continue to play a big role in determining the competitive landscape.
This is likely to become more - rather than less - true in the future
because the telecommunications business is undergoing a fundamental
transformation - with the emphasis shifting away from facilities-based
carriers with large networks, such as BT and AT&amp;T.
As Mercury's Mr Rhodes noted in a recent speech: 'It is software, rather
than hardware which is becoming the critical success factor.' This means
that ownership of the physical infrastructure will be relatively less
important in the future and the development - and deployment - of
software-based products will become even more critical.
'Technology per se, particularly in an era of open interfaces and standards,
is unlikely to be an enduring source of competitive advantage,' said Mr
Rhodes.
</TEXT>
