<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (2):
Opinions differ on costs - New generation server-workstations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN SONSINO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIKE ageing characters in a long-running soap opera, mainframe computers
have been written off and written out of the IT buyers' script.
Today's buyers, weaned on media stars such as PCs and local area networks,
are clamouring for the new generation server-workstation architectures,
architectures that combine the two. But the server-workstation architecture
is nothing new. It's nothing more than distributed data processing in the
Emperor's new clothes. So why all the excitement?
There are three key reasons why the rush to server-workstation architectures
has accelerated in the past year:
First, it gives users greater control over data. Instead of massive
databases, traditionally untouchable by end-users, data is instantly
accessible at the departmental level, and in real-time. Users can now have
their executive information where and when they need it, and they can get at
it through an easy-to-use front-end, often their own desktop PC.
Secondly, today's users are more computer literate, more sophisticated in
what they want from computing and more demanding of IT staff. Now, it's not
unusual for the financial director to be intimately involved with the search
for and selection of IT systems.
And finally there is cost: cost of ownership, as you might expect, but also
cost-savings in use. Opinions differ widely, though, on server-workstation
costs and some users prefer to retain and maintain existing mainframe
systems, rather than ditch them in favour of distributed systems.
THOSE companies that have ditched mainframes in favour of clusters of
workstations have mixed stories to tell. Some have been forced to revive the
mainframe link before it was severed completely because the new systems
couldn't cope.
Others, however, such as EBC Amro, have successfully replaced clusters of
minis or mainframes with networks of PCs hooked up to file servers. Up to a
point, it is fairly straightforward to mirror the physical storage and
processing characteristics of a mainframe with networked PCs and file
servers.
In this way, users can see 'downsizing,' the marketing executives' latest
jargon, as a form of systems integration. Here the traditional DP department
exchanges centralised control for centralised systems management.
Benefits for the user should include more effective support, frequent
upgrades and lower system costs. And those cost savings can be remarkable,
says the National Computing Centre.
One member-company reports a saving of around Pounds 200,000 a year in
maintenance costs alone, as a direct result of downsizing. There seems to be
no apparent loss of capacity or functionality, it claims.
Nick Evans, chairman of the British Computer Society's Client Server Group
claims that cost savings can be phenomenal - 'we surveyed one leisure
services company that could cut its costs by 75 per cent overall,' he says.
There were even larger savings to be made for companies that could stop
leasing their mainframe systems to switch into server workstation
architectures. But cost-savings should be questioned closely by users
intending to tread the client-server route.
'Anyone who buys client-server systems to save money is in for a shock,'
says Peter Stuart, marketing strategy manager for ICL's midrange systems.
Combining hardware, software and integration costs can sometimes exceed the
value of a small mainframe system, he suggests. Though he is quick to point
ou t that the switch does save money in the medium to long-term, by offering
better performance.
'What is good about client-server is that users can invest incrementally, a
step at a time,' he adds, 'so there can be a cost-saving in that sense.'
Henry Brysh, a senior communications consultant at the National Computing
Centre, believes that users should question vendors closely on costs.
'What they don't tell you is there are hidden costs, mainly to do with
integrating the whole system.'
In the past, users bought mainframes from IBM, ICL or Unisys, for example,
and operations managers were comfortable with the technology. In addition,
they had a stable relationship with their suppliers.
'Now,' says Mr Brysh, 'users are buying the systems, specifying the
commodities, and they're responsible for driving the whole thing.'
IN SHORT, the focus has shifted away from the performance of key hardware or
software, and towards the overall performance of the entire network.
'When you find the three distributed databases you've got linked together
don't work,' he asks, 'who do you turn to?'
But cost is a complex issue. It hardly seems fair to compare a Unix box at
Pounds 30,000 with a mainframe at Pounds 500,000, but Mr Brysh believes
these hidden costs must be measured if users are to make a fair comparison
between the systems.
Fortunately for users, a survey by KPMG, a management consultant, has gone
some way towards measuring these costs.
The survey - of workstation users at companies such as Ford, National
Westminster Bank and Refuge Assurance - has revealed that the annual cost of
running workstations is almost Pounds 6,000 per machine. Of this, over 90
per cent represents hidden support costs, claims the report.
'I was asked to speak on a lecture tour by one systems and software vendor,'
says Geoff Jarvis, a principal consultant at KPMG. 'The vendor was obviously
trying to migrate its 10-12,000 customers on to Unix boxes, claiming it
would be a tenth of the cost. I had to say 'Hold on a minute' and was nearly
booed off the tour.'
It is no surprise that vendors are so excited about client-server - even IBM
has pitched in to the market, and it is looking for a sizeable portion of
the business.
'Compared with the traditional mainframe business, this is a much broader
opportunity,' says Nicholas Donofrio, IBM Enterprise Systems general
manager.
'It's a Dollars 150bn market, which will grow at about 7 per cent over the
next five years.'
There are three main barriers for users wishing to adopt server-workstation
architectures, according to market research company Ovum:
A shortage of skills.
The immaturity and unreliability of the LAN environment.
And the lack of support and development tools.
Today's users are demanding application development tools to run in the
client-server environment, but they also need management tools, tools to
support the mainframe, as well as multi-vendor platforms.
In particular, users need tools for systems and network management.
Perhaps the over-riding concern for users is for better service and support
from hardware and software vendors. In a client-server environment, problems
are much tougher to identify and isolate.
Allocating them to one vendor over another could prove impossible. So users
need a one-stop shop for their IT systems, a shop that can support
multi-vendor systems from desktop PCs to backroom mainframes.
Thus, servers and workstations clearly have their place as the distributed
databases of tomorrow, although the questions of cost and effective support
cannot be ignored by the concerned user.
'I'm not firing the flare on client-server,' says Henry Brysh of the
National Computing Centre.
'It is effective when people decide it can help their business. But it
shouldn't be undertaken just because the chief executive or the finance
director has been playing golf with the wrong person.'
</TEXT>
