<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (5): The
shape of things to come?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY SALZ-TRAUTMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPUTERS are progressing to the point that they can accept a user's wish as
their command, writes Peggy Salz-Trautman.
Scientists at several research laboratories in the US, Japan and Austria
have moved beyond the keyboard, the mouse and the joystick, and progressed
to experimenting with so-called 'mind-over-cursor' technology - a by-product
of the bio-cybernetics program began by the US Defense Department in the
late 1970s - which enables specially trained individuals to use a computer
without uttering a sound or moving a muscle.
It is claimed that interaction between a brain and a computer is possible
thanks to the advance of electro-encephalography, or EEC, the technique of
attaching electrodes to the scalp. Signals collected by EEC, signals which
are emitted by the brain as it works, can now be passed on to computers
whose job it is to analyse them.
In practice, a person fitted with a slew of cables and a helmet which could
easily belong to either an officer of Star Fleet Command or a member of the
local swim team, focuses his total concentration on a series of letters or a
particular command - and the computer obeys the order.
According to a recent report in The New York Times, University of Illinois
psychologists have developed a way of allowing people to type, albeit at a
rate of only 2.3 characters a minute, by spelling out words in their minds.
Researchers at Fujitsu, Japan's largest personal computer manufacturer, take
this a step further. They are developing super-sensitive brain-wave
detectors, or Squids (which stands for 'superconducting quantum interference
device') to interface between the silent speech of the brain and the program
language of a computer.
For Prof. Kevin Warwick, expert on cybernetics at Britain's Reading
University, one-to-one interaction between a brain and a computer is 'not
science fiction and not yet science fact.'
See also: research and development, page XII
</TEXT>
<XX>
