<DOCNO>FT931-2019</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCXAWABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (22):
Users want more freedom - Open systems: OSI in the doldrums
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JUDGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE is mounting for governments to open up their definition of open
systems. The policy of requiring systems based on 'official' standards has
had mixed results and users in the public sector have begun to demand
freedom to adopt the technology they want.
Since the 1980s, users in the public sector have been required to adopt
network products based on the official OSI standards. But some of those
standards have had little impact in the market, and other technology has
been more practical.
'Back in 1989 or so, we believed everything that was said - that there would
be no alternative, and OSI would be a panacea to all our ills,' says Len
Graves, county information technology (IT) officer at Essex County Council.
'Now, we are frustrated. The deliverable has never really materialised.'
In the 1980s, the European Commission was forging ahead towards its 1992
target for a common market and, beyond that, to greater unity.
Goods and people had to move freely around Europe, and to provide public
services on a European basis, government departments and other public bodies
had to work together. To achieve this, the governments' IT systems had to
have a common language. At the time, IBM and the other suppliers were using
their own communications protocols, which limited the choice users had, and
cut them off from other users' systems.
The international standards bodies were working on standards for open
systems interconnection (OSI), which promised to solve this.
Whatever systems you had, once the suppliers installed OSI communications,
they would communicate with each other.
In 1987, the European Commission passed a Decision, stating that all public
procurements above a certain value must refer to international standards.
The Decision required the OSI standards for communications.
The move was meant to kick-start an OSI market. If the whole public sector
asked for the same thing, suppliers would change their proprietary ways.
Public bodies would be able to communicate with each other, and have free
choice of the systems they bought.
The private sector would follow. Free communications would make European
businesses stronger and more competitive.
That was the theory; in practice, the standards were almost unworkable. They
included a vast number of options, and there was no guarantee that products
would communicate.
To deal with this, the European standards community took on more work.
Tighter standards, called profiles, were defined, along with conformance
tests which would establish whether a product met a particular profile.
The UK government's IT adviser, CCTA, weighed in with the Government OSI
Profile (GOSIP), a procurement guide which helps users buy products which
work with other GOSIP products. A European handbook on open systems (EPHOS)
based on GOSIP, is under development.
Up to a point, this has worked. OSI protocols have been in development for
13 years, and there are now products available which do work together. But
they are finding, like Rip van Winkle waking from his long sleep, that
things have changed.
OSI was designed to tackle problems which are no longer so serious. Vendors,
suffering from recession and technical change, cannot impose their will on
users so easily, and are co-operating more readily. In the 1980s 'industry
standards' were imposed by single suppliers, and OSI opposed them; in the
1990s, industry standards are developed by consortia with much the same
goals as the standards bodies.
Ironically, users acknowledged this situation more quickly than the
authorities. When users in the public sector were required to adopt open
systems and standards, they responded by buying systems based on the
emerging operating system, UNIX, which communicates with the TCP/IP
protocols.
It is claimed that TCP/IP and related network protocols have inferior
features to the equivalent OSI standards. What they do have is a proven
track record, and easy availability.
Whatever the technical merits, many public sector users would rather have an
80 per cent solution now, than a 99 per cent solution in five years. But
they are saying it privately, because the EC decision requires them to have
an OSI strategy. The irony is that, although these protocols are excluded
from the policy, because they are not international standards, they actually
provide most of what the EC wanted from OSI in the first place. They offer
easy connections and are free from the control of any one supplier.
Public bodies are meeting the EC's objectives, but they are doing it by
misunderstanding the guidelines, or using loopholes to get what they want.
Fortunately, the decision allows plenty of exceptions. The EC never wanted
to force users to waste money, so other protocols are allowed if
standards-based products are uneconomic over the life of the system, if the
standards are ill-defined or untestable, or if the technology is new and
unproven. They are also allowed, for compatibility with existing systems.
Purchases below 100,000 ECUs are exempt.
Larger bodies are still positive about using the OSI protocols on 'backbone'
networks: 'Most people are persevering,' says Seth Mason, of the National
Health Service's Information Management Centre. 'With the advent of EPHOS
and maturing of GOSIP into two boxed sets, it has become easier to reference
OSI specifications.'
The biggest networks are run by the telecom operators. Like large public
bodies, they look to OSI to solve the big problems, such as global
directories and network management, areas where there is little alternative
work. But in bodies the size of local authorities, there is frustration.
'If it is in reality a waste of time, then it is also a waste of money,'
says Roger Toms, general manager for information systems services at Surrey
County Council. 'If OSI is truly becoming an irrelevance, then they have to
be honest enough to say so, and not force the public sector through an
artificial process, which increases our procurement costs and causes delay.'
Mr Toms fears the OSI requirement could put the local authority's own
departments at a disadvantage in a compulsory competitive tender against
outsiders from the private sector, who are not subject to the same
procurement restrictions.
Often the TCP/IP solution is so much cheaper that it falls beneath the
100,000 ECU threshold, but public sector bodies still have to go through the
lengthy process of claiming exemption. Consultant Ray O'Connor, who has
advised the EC on this issue, says: 'Governmental policy needs to be more
flexible, recognising that OSI has an important role to play, but that it
has little chance of becoming the universal solution which was expected.'
CCTA is opening up its policy a little. Its published guide keeps an
optimistic tone, with a suggested target date of 1994 for a complete
transition to OSI. When advising individual organisations, however, CCTA it
is reported to be more relaxed, and it supports the use of agreed
specifications from industry, such as the Portability Guide from the X/Open
group.
But there is not much hope of a new policy. The EC wants to keep up its
pressure for open systems, of whatever kind, but the Treaty of Rome's
principle of subsidiarity would only allow legislation binding in all the
member-states, in an emergency. There is now no emergency.
It seems all too likely that the present system of lip service to a 1980s
solution will continue. Meanwhile, users will adopt the solutions that
industry provides in the 1990s, which will be a mixture of the available
protocols.
The writer is editor of OSN, the Open Systems Newsletter, and author of the
Guide to IT Standards, both published by Technology Appraisals, telephone
(44) 81 893 3986. Technology Appraisals also publishes the OSI Products
Guide.
</TEXT>
