<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (3):
Sales continue to fall - Mainframes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN SONSINO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE world will only ever need five mainframe computers,' said Thomas Watson,
the founding father of International Business Machines. His prediction, made
many decades ago, may yet come true as sales of the industry's workhorse
'number crunchers' continue to fall.
IBM's 1992 results - one of the worst losses in financial history - are the
final evidence, if any were needed, that the day of the proprietary
mainframe is finally over. Now IBM is intent on capturing the open systems
market, rather than on trying to pen its customers into proprietary systems
architectures.
'Customers are very clear about what they need to solve large problems,'
says Mr Nicholas Donofrio, IBM's Enterprise Systems general manager. 'We are
responding by making our products more open, by further enhancing server
capabilities and by continuing to reduce the total cost of computing on
multiple platforms.'
And the company certainly seems to be opening up its architectures,
announcing open standards as recently as February 1993 for MVS/ESA, a key
IBM mainframe operating system.
Britain's ICL has also announced changes, mainly performance upgrades, to
the System 39SX range, its top-end mainframes. And it, too, has opened up
its mainframe operating system, VME.
ICL's VME, launched in the mid-1970s, is perhaps the youngest of the
mainframe operating systems, and it was relatively easy to fit open
interfaces on top of the operating system software, says Peter Slavid, ICL's
corporate business systems manager.
'We've learned a lot from the Unix environment about openness,' he says,
'and we can apply this to the mainframe environment. But we've also learned
some of the limitations.' Mr Slavid does not believe Unix is yet capable of
managing a very large corporate network, for instance, leaving some room for
potential growth in the mainframe arena.
BESIDE the ageing of the mainframe market, though, there is increasing
pressure on mainframe vendors from the makers of supercomputers. Many
believe, though, that the machines from companies such as Pyramid and
Sequent are probably not as resilient or as fault tolerant as mainframes, or
as effective at archiving and data management, especially if they support
more than a few hundred users.
Of the true supercomputer vendors, such as Cray and other scientific
mainframe suppliers, mainstream mainframe manufacturers seem even less
worried.
'In other European countries, supercomputers are common in commercial
environments,' says Mr Slavid. 'But these people are coming from a
scientific background and these applications are very different from the
banking and commercial applications in Br itain.'
Which means that mainframe manufacturers still have the pick of the UK
market - for the present, at least.
A problem with that UK market, though, is price. Once unassailable, the
prices of mainframe systems are tumbling now like PC prices at sale time.
'With the commoditisation of the market, mainframes are now just boxes,'
says John Perkins, a director at the National Computing Centre. 'There is
intense pressure on the margins of mainframe suppliers who are being
attacked on all sides,' he says. 'That's inescapeable.'
This explains the switch in focus of hardware vendors, away from hardware
sales and into software and services. IBM, ICL and Digital among others are
all becoming service-oriented suppliers.
The watchword is 'solutions.' One remaining demand for mainframe systems, a
demand that will keep sales trickling in for some time, is the requirement
for large transaction processing systems. Mainframe systems in banks and
building societies effectively operate as country and even continent-wide
networks. Trying to replace these with a distributed network of Unix boxes
may mean saying goodbye to processing power and security.
'It's important to remember that we have learned a lot of lessons in the
mainframe market over the last 30 years,' says John Perkins. 'For many
people, mainframes represent a significant investment of time, money and
effort. This is not something they will throw away lightly.'
But that is exactly what many users are considering. In a 1992 survey
conducted by the NCC, over 55 per cent of its members - representing 584
medium to large computer installations and over two million staff - have
already considered downsizing and a further 11 per cent plan to do so within
two years.
The main reason users are looking to move away from mainframes is their
initial cost, but ease of access and flexibility of use are also important
to today's increasingly sophisticated users.
The result for mainframe vendors will be a 31 per cent cut in the number of
mainframes in the coming year. They will be replaced chiefly by
super-minicomputers and intelligent workstations.
Perhaps the most important, often forgotten factor companies should consider
when downsizing is corporate culture.
Clearly, a decentralised, distributed IT system is not the best solution for
a hierarchical and highly centralised organisation. In companies such as
this, service to the user will deteriorate and cost-savings will evaporate
in a flood of corrective measures designed to remedy an irremediable
solution.
Further problems may arise for users with the change in skills needed among
IT service personnel. The key problem here is that software development
platforms will move away from the traditional mainframe database management
systems and ever closer to the PC-based database systems and fourth
generation languages of the Unix world.
In the medium-term, therefore, skills issues will become increasingly
central to the drive away from mainframes.
In the short-term, however, downsizing will continue, as will the fall in
price. And to combat the drainage, away from mainframes and into open,
Unix-based systems, hardware companies will continue evolving into software
and service companies.
'The hardware companies will continue to move into the service business as
fast as they can,' says Doug Eyeions, secretary of the Computing Services
Association.
IBM, ICL and Digital Equipment all make more money from software and
services today than they do from hardware sales. This may suggest a sudden
death for the mainframe, but its future for the time being is assured.
'The mainframe is still good at cost-effectively sharing large volumes of
data among large numbers of users,' says Peter Stuart, marketing strategy
manager for ICL's mid-range systems. Large scale applications such as
airline reservation systems will stay on mainframes, he suggests. Doug
Eyeions agrees: 'For the rest of this decade we will still need mainframes
as database drivers on very large applications, but that's all.'
But what about the future?
In the long-term, it seems, mainframes will becoming corporate data centres,
massive repositories of data. But to get at the data, users will be managing
a transparent network of Unix boxes. And what do users think of this
diagnosis?
'In the long-term, Northern Electric's strategy is to move away from
proprietary mainframe platforms,' says Peter Wadham, programme manager for
integrated billing services at Northern Electric. 'At the moment, though,
the size, availability and processing power of Unix boxes just isn't there.'
The users seem to agree.
</TEXT>
