<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Survey of Information and Communications Technology (1): New
era of global networks - The increasing convergence of the computer and
communication technologies is a powerful driver of globalisation, enabling
companies to capture economies of scale by eliminating barriers of time and
space
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNION of computers and communications is a marriage made in heaven. Yet
while the banns have been read many times over the past two decades,
consummation has been a slow process.
The reasons are both cultural and technical, but today there is renewed
optimism that a new era in information processing systems is about to unfold
as a result of the convergence of the two most powerful modern technologies.
Computers and digital (computer language) communications lie at the heart of
information technology; computers realise their full potential only when
connected in networks; telecommunications systems based on digital
technology are infinitely more flexible and powerful than their analogue
cousins.
Together, they are a powerful driver of globalisation, enabling companies to
capture economies of scale by eliminating barriers of time and space.
The telecom and computer industries, however, have separate origins and
history. Telecoms stretches back into the last century; the industry grew up
with traditions of regulation, monopoly power and a duty to maintain and
protect the network.
The computer industry grew out of research into scientific calculation and,
in the 1950s, it was grafted onto the mature office equipment business which
it then proceeded to cannibalise.
Telecom companies and computer companies have often been seen as competitors
rather than allies. In the 1980s, AT&amp;T, the US telecommunications giant, and
International Business Machines, the world's largest computer manufacturer,
seemed set for a battle royal as AT&amp;T established a computer division and
IBM bought Rolm, a promising telecoms manufacturer.
In the end, it proved to be a phoney war. AT&amp;T bought NCR two years ago to
rationalise its loss-making computer business; IBM sold Rolm to Siemens of
Germany in 1989.
According to Mr Alan Willsher, managing director of GPT Communications
Systems, owned jointly by GEC of the UK and Siemens of Germany, the moves
were premature: 'They came in too early before digital public-switched
networks had been properly established. Ten years on, most developed
countries have a good digital system'.
Among other developments which are creating optimism that the rate of
convergence of computers and communications is speeding up include:
Pressure on national telecommunications authorities to deregulate and
liberalise their services. The US is the world's most deregulated
telecommunications market; the UK leads in Europe. The European Commission
seems set to put pressure on the remaining European nations to speed up the
process, buoyed by a European Court of Justice decision that the commission
has the right to compel member-states to deregulate certain telecom
services.
LIBERALISATION is seen by many as the key to the new era of information
technology. According to Mr William Marx, writing in a colloquium report* to
be published later this year: 'The liberalisation of trade and of regulation
and the formulation of policies that bolster market-based economies will
hasten the expansion and modernisation of global networks and at the same
time deliver to individuals, companies and government, the full benefits of
information technology.'
Growth of distributed data processing, more commonly described now as
client-server computing. This is a direct consequence of the increasing
power of microprocessor chips and the declining cost of computing. For many
applications today it makes economic sense to distribute processing through
a network of personal computers, or clients, with more powerful systems -
servers - providing network management and control, database services and a
reservoir of computing power.
A consequence has been a decline in the use of traditional mainframe
computers with deleterious effects on the profit and loss accounts of
mainframe vendors such as IBM and Groupe Bull.
Client-server designs are not for everybody, however. A survey carried out
among delegates to City IT, a conference held in London, showed worries
about the difficulty of building and managing networks, fears of losing
control of data and data security and concern for the technical inadequacies
of personal computers - 'it is back to the dark ages,' one delegate said
'All the things mainframe people have known for the past 20 years, PCs do
not have.'
A market for mobile, radio-based telecommunications growing explosively.
Building on the success of the earlier, analogue cellular telephones,
suppliers are preparing to launch digital voice and data services. The
pan-European Groupe Speciale Mobile will provide the digital infrastructure
for a personal communications network.
The use of digital technology in these networks will make possible new and
sophisticated services while making better use of the available frequency
spectrum.
A further factor is the growth of distributed multimedia systems - the
convergence of sound, data, static image and video.
Many believe that multimedia will emerge as the dominant mass technology of
the next century. The pace of change is being driven by the evolution of
optical storage, which is making possible the capture of huge volumes of
information on a disc only a few centimetres wide. A single disc, for
example, can hold all the text and graphics from a 21 volume encyclopaedia
set.
However, as Mr David Hutchison of Lancaster University in the UK pointed out
recently,** the telecoms authorities control the spread and adoption of
multimedia applications - 'high telecommunications prices will hinder
applications rollout. This is because multimedia traffic will require high
bandwidths (transmission capacity): a single digital video stream offering
full colour and motion may require two million bits per second even when
compressed, using the most advanced techniques.'
The growth of digital networks is changing the balance of power within the
sector. Telecom companies, in particular, are showing a renewed interest in
computer firms. This time round, however, their interest is in services
companies. Nynex, for example, one of the US 'Baby Bells' bought the UK
computing services company BIS, while AT&amp;T bought Istel, the former data
processing unit of the Rover car group. France Telecom has invested in the
Anglo-French Sema Group, while there are tenacious rumours that BT of the UK
has an interest in acquiring a stake in EDS, the large General Motors
subsidiary.
This is a reflection of the fact that computer hardware has become
essentially a commodity, yielding a low gross profit margin of perhaps less
than 20 per cent. Computing services offer faster growth and a more
reasonable margin and are a better fit with the nature of the telecoms
business with its emphasis on service and customer satisfaction.
One of the more exciting developments in the past two years has been the
emergence of 'personal communicators,' hand-held devices which combine the
functions of telephone handset with computer and facsimile machine. AT&amp;T is
at the forefront of one such development working with the Californian
company EO; the Japanese organisations Matsushita and Marubeni; and
Olivetti, the Italian computer company.
According to Mr Elserino Piol, Olivetti vice-chairman, a leading IT company
these days has no choice but to enter the market for personal communicators.
Other companies developing personal communicators or 'personal digital
assistants' include IBM, Apple and, in the UK, Amstrad.
The importance of personal communicators and their desk-bound equivalents is
the emergence of the 'broadband' society where individuals have access to
virtually unlimited amounts of information.
Mr Marx* sketches the likely future: 'Universal access to information and
the relatively inexpensive cost of transmitting it, offer the potential to
create a worldwide entrepreneurial revolution to rival the one that followed
the personal computer.'
* Globalization, Technology and Competition; Bradley et al eds; Harvard
Business School Press.
** The Computer Journal, Volume 36, No. 1, Oxford University Press.
</TEXT>
