<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FADING hopes of a cut in UK base rates, worries about the political
situation in Russia and a higher than expected trade deficit combined to
depress the derivatives sector, writes Joel Kibazo.
In futures, the opening of the June contract on the FT-SE 100 at 2,905, 5
points below Friday's close, was the first indication of the selling that
was to drive June lower for the rest of the session on the domestic economic
and overseas worries.
A mid-morning attempt at a rally petered out after the 11.30am release of
figures showing a higher than anticipated UK trade deficit with non-EC
countries. This drove June lower once again, falling to 2,861 by lunchtime.
Bargain hunting saw the contract start to claw its way back from the lows
after lunch, but the upward momentum once again proved to be premature for
the poor opening on Wall Street led to another bout of selling of the
contract.
June eventually closed at 2,852, down 58 on the previous session and around
an 11-point discount to the underlying cash market, with volume a healthy
12,927 lots.
Traded options was also dull and saw volume of 26,130 contracts, down from a
previous 30,610. The FT-SE 100 option saw business of 7,385 contracts and
the Euro-FT-SE 3,058. Fisons was the busiest stock option after a 'Roll
Over' trade, at 3,020 lots.
</TEXT>
