<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets: Two-way market in Tokyo outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM COCHRANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Once again, Japan dominated the FT-Actuaries World Indices last week, taking
the World Index to a gain of 1.1 per cent in local currency terms in spite
of flat performances from the US, and Europe.
Declining corporate profits, low economic growth, and political scandals
have put the health of the recent Tokyo rally in question. It has been
suggested that the gains, owing much to the performance of NTT, the partly
state-owned telecommunications stock, have been engineered to get Japan's
financial institutions comfortably through the closing of their books on
March 31.
However, Mr Nicholas Knight, the Nomura strategist who called the turn of
the Tokyo market last year, thinks that the market is more strongly based
than that.
He says that institutions are turning their attention to next year and that,
after a drop in domestic interest rates, equities are much more attractive.
Investors are beginning to expect a massive reflation of the Japanese
economy, with a fiscal package of Y14,000bn now on the cards.
Mr Knight says that there is growing evidence that the bad corporate news
has been priced into the market, and that institutions are beginning to look
beyond that to prospective recovery. The Japanese, now, are much more
receptive to talk of corporate restructuring than they used to be; and,
finally, foreigners are losing their conviction that big short positions in
Tokyo equities will pay off from next April onwards.
Ireland put up the biggest gain of the week and, indeed, of the year so far.
Dealers at Davy Stockbrokers in Dublin say that the country's inclusion from
May 1 in Morgan Stanley's world index series has helped; talk of an outside
buyer in the Greencore privatisation has moved on to Irish Life; and the
steady reduction in domestic interest rates continued with another cut last
Friday.
