<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Money Markets: Sterling futures fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING futures contracts fell again yesterday as dealers continued to
assume that UK base rates would not fall below 6 per cent in the medium
term, writes James Blitz.
The sterling market was again swayed by indications that UK monetary policy
would remain tight for the forseeable future.
In last Tuesday's budget, the UK chancellor said the prospects for economic
growth were consistent with the current level of base rates. An unexpected
drop in the number of people out of work also consolidated the view that the
economy did not need to be stimulated by an easing of policy.
In addition, yesterday's trade figures, which showed the UK's visible
deficit with non-EC countries widening to Pounds 1.3bn in February, may also
have raised concerns about the vulnerability of the pound if base rates are
cut again.
The June short sterling contract fell 10 basis points to close at 94.12, and
the September contract fell 13 basis points to close at 94.26. Both these
prices effectively assumed that base rates will remain unchanged for the
next 6 months.
The fall in the June contract by some 44 basis points since last Tuesday
underlined the speed with which assumptions about base rates had been
revised.
One dealer said the June contract was a good buy from here, because it would
easily rise if there is any bad news on the economic front. Cash rates in
the sterling money market were more or less unchanged, with 3-month money
again closing at 6 1/16 per cent.
Euromark futures continued to reflect disappointment that the Bundesbank's
Lombard rate had not been cut at last Thursday's council meeting. However,
there were hopes that the repo rate - at which the Bundesbank provides
weekly funds to commercial banks - might be cut from 8.25 per cent today.
The June Euromark contract fell 7 basis points to close at 93.08. At this
level it is pricing 3-month money in June at 6.92 per cent, some 89 points
below yesterday's closing level.
However, according to one dealer, the chances of a cut in the repo rate
today are slim. He believed the Bundesbank would prefer to bring call money
down from the relatively high level of 8.65 per cent by adding emergency
funds. before touching the repo rate.
