<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUGAR futures slipped below Friday's closing levels as profit-taking in
London New York ate into gains. In early trading prices had continued last
week's uptrend, taking New York prices to fresh three-year peaks and
London's to the highest level since April 1991. London's May position, which
had reached Dollars 309.50 a tonne at one point, slipped back to Dollars 304
a tonne, down 80 cents. Traders had been expecting a price correction after
the recent sustained rise. 'It is healthier to have the market a little
lower, where it will attract fresh buying,' one commented. London robusta
COFFEE futures firmed in light trading with May closing at Dollars 891 a
tonne, up Dollars 11, just below the day's high. The initially steadier tone
on New York helped the London market to build on its morning advance, but
traders thought the price was unlikely in the near future to move back above
the Dollars 900 support level that was breached last week. LME COPPER prices
capitalised on the generally firmer trend engendered by the situation in
Russia but the cash price baulked at overhead resistance before closing
Pounds 4.50 up at Pounds 1,464 a tonne.
Compiled from Reuters
