<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Cash boost for Portuguese farms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PORTUGAL'S AGRICULTURE ministry has announced a Esc220bn (Pounds 975m)
investment plan to promote and improve Portuguese food products to enable
farmers to compete with their European Community partners, reports Reuter
from Lisbon. The five-year programme includes Esc126bn of direct investment
by the government.
Portuguese farmers, hit by the worst drought this century, have protested at
what they say are cheap imports.
The plan includes a risk capital fund to help existing and new companies and
the creation of credit lines at discount interest rates for producers of
fruit and vegetables, rice and meat.
Other planned measures are a Esc5bn fund for agricultural and food products
promotion and investment in processing and distribution companies. The
promotion and quality control of food products will be subsidised and new
legislation will be introduced on the management of farm co-operatives.
