<DATE>930323
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: No punches pulled as Mrs Witte
goes for gold - A bitter battle to reduce costs at Canada's Giant mine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YELLOWKNIFE, capital of Canada's Northwest Territories, is a rough place at
the best of times. But the mood there has turned downright ugly in the ten
months since 240 workers were locked out from the Giant gold mine on the
outskirts of town.
Middle ground has become hard to find in the bitter dispute between Royal
Oak Mines, which owns Giant, and the local branch of the Canadian
Association of Steel and Allied Workers (Casaw). Brawls erupt more
frequently than ever in Yellowknife's numerous bars and vandalism has become
endemic. The mood among the town's 15,000 residents was captured in a
recently-circulated anonymous letter, which expressed the wish that every
member of the union would be 'dropped from a helicopter in the middle of
Great Slave Lake with a ball and chain on each wrist and ankle'.
Emotions were rubbed especially raw by the deaths of nine strike-breakers in
an underground explosion at the mine last September. Although no arrests
have yet been made, many residents of Yellowknife take it for granted that
Casaw members were involved.
Only the intensity of the Giant dispute, however, separates it from tensions
which are evident throughout North American resource industries as employers
and workers wrestle with sagging metal prices and competition from low-cost
Third World suppliers.
Mrs Peggy Witte, Royal Oak's president, sees her company as one of the few
willing to confront organised labour in the drive to bring down costs.
Throughout the Giant dispute, Royal Oak has single-mindedly concentrated on
keeping the mine in operation, rather than taking the less painful routes of
cutting production or watering down its demands for concessions from the
union.
Third-quarter output of 22,185 ounces was 5 per cent lower than the same
quarter a year earlier, but 7 per cent up on the previous three months.
Giant's fourth-quarter production was not disclosed in Royal Oak's 1992
results, published last week.
'Many of the big companies don't want to face the situation,' Mrs Witte
says. She adds, however, that several of them have demonstrated their
support by contributing to the reward fund - now totalling CDollars 225,000
(Pounds 120,000) - for information leading to the arrest of the those
responsible for last September's murders.
Mrs Witte asserts that 'nobody is aggressive enough to say: 'It's got to
stop here'. I'm not willing to keep the mine open with a (labour) contract I
can't live with'.
Royal Oak has kept Giant operating with replacement workers flown in from
the south and, more recently, with some Casaw members who have crossed the
picket line. The company has rejected government efforts to impose a
settlement on anything other than its own terms. Mrs Witte also refuses
point-blank to take any union activists back on the payroll until last
September's murders are solved.
Royal Oak's uncompromising stand has won it admirers, but also many enemies.
A government commission was in Yellowknife last week to hear allegations
that a new union formed by replacement workers and strike-breakers is, in
the words of Casaw's lawyer, a 'front organisation' for the company.
'She doesn't want to sit down and talk to us,' complains a worker manning
the union's picket hut outside Giant's main gate. The hut is plastered with
slogans such as 'Scabs took our jobs'. Although Mrs Witte denies it, Casaw
and its sympathisers are convinced that Royal Oak's aim is to destroy the
union.
For Royal Oak, the nub of the issue is the survival of the mine. According
to Mrs Witte, Giant has a life of at least 10 years if costs can be brought
down to the USDollars 280-290 an ounce range, which is substantially below
the present gold price of Dollars 330 an ounce. If not, the mine is unlikely
to last longer than another two or three years without a big jump in the
bullion price.
Wage increases at Giant have averaged 8.3 per cent a year since the early
1980s. Prior to the lockout, workers were taking home an average of CDollars
77,000 a year in pay and benefits, with the best-paid earning CDollars
132,000, equivalent in Canada to a senior manager's salary at a large
company.
During negotiations with the union last year, Royal Oak offered to maintain
hourly wage rates. But it wants to peg future increases to the gold price
and to trim benefits, including a number of holidays, regular air fares to
Edmonton, 950 km (590 miles) to the south, and the bus which carries miners
between Yellowknife and the mine.
Since it bought the mine in 1990, Royal Oak has succeeded in bringing down
cash production costs from almost Dollars 400 an ounce to about Dollars 305
an ounce. (The latest figures exclude CDollars 3.5m in strike-related costs
last year, almost all spent on extra security for the property and the
replacement workers).
Royal Oak has added an extra shift, changed work schedules and put greater
emphasis on preventive maintenance. The replacement workers have accepted
substantially lower wages than the locked-out union members.
Giant's survival is crucial to Royal Oak's plans to press ahead with
expansion plans in the Northwest Territories. The company, which is carving
out a reputation for restoring high-cost gold mines to profitability, last
month signed a deal to acquire the mothballed Colomac property, north-east
of Yellowknife.
It aims to reopen Colomac in 1994, bringing down operating costs from about
Dollars 425 an ounce when the mine was closed to less than Dollars 300. The
key to lower costs however, is running Colomac in tandem with the Giant
property. Payroll, human resources, safety administration and various other
functions would be combined.
Mrs Witte is also interested in buying Kennecott's Con mine in Yellowknife
'if the price was right.' The labour contract at Con, which expires at the
end of April, is currently being renegotiated.
The mine's owners and its workers are expected to draw some sobering lessons
from recent events at Giant. Observers in Yellowknife anticipate that the
United Steelworkers Union, which represents the Con workers, will accept
management's demands for concessions more readily than its counterpart did
at Giant. Indeed, Mrs Witte predicts that the tough line she is taking at
Giant will find an echo in the North American mining industry far beyond
Yellowknife's two gold producers.
</TEXT>
