<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Capital Markets: Japan goes slow on commission
change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN, the only leading stock market nation where brokers' charges are still
fixed, is about to take its first step towards the deregulation of trading
commissions.
An advisory committee is expected today to endorse a gradual liberalisation,
starting with transactions of more than Y1bn (Dollars 8.4m). The measures
are due to take effect from April next year.
Transactions in excess of Y1bn make up 5 per cent of all trades among the
big four securities houses - Nomura, Daiwa, Nikko and Yamaichi - and some 2
per cent for the top 10 second-tier brokers. The immediate impact of
deregulation is thus likely to be minimal.
The decision to go-slow on deregulation is seen as a victory for the
securities industry, since the changes will have little impact on
brokerages' returns. The brokers have argued that injecting competition into
commission rates would lead to higher small-lot rates and drive individual
and small-lot investors away from the stock market.
Fixed brokerage commissions took most of the blame for the spate of stock
scandals two years ago, when brokers were found to be underwriting the share
losses of favoured clients. Supporters of deregulated commissions argue that
price competition would have made this practice obsolete.
The securities industry was outraged when the ministry of finance agreed to
review fixed commissions, since the ministry had originally agreed with the
securities industry that commissions would remain fixed but lowered to
international standards. Deregulation of commissions would result in lower
profits for the brokers.
The advisory group will also recommend that the effects be carefully
monitored, implying that full liberalisation may take longer than many
critics of the system anticipated.
Supporters of liberalisation, including institutional investors and some
foreign houses, argue that fixed commissions help maintain Japan's brokerage
oligopoly. But the securities industry contends that lower costs for
institutional trading will result in lower costs for individuals.
Liberalisation will hurt smaller houses, which rely heavily on client
commissions; and an increase in large-lot transactions could mean greater
risks for the bigger brokerages.
The ministry of finance, the reluctant advocate of commission
liberalisation, says an agenda for further deregulation is not yet set, due
to the weakness of the stock market and heavy losses among smaller brokers.
Although stock market weakness has forced the ministry of finance to scale
down its plans for financial reform, an easing of the barriers between
banking and the securities industry, together with interest rate
deregulation, appears to remain an official priority.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
