<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAR 93 / International Company News: KIO's top Briton resigns as
treasurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE KUWAIT Investment Office, Kuwait's foreign investment arm, is losing its
most senior British manager, Mr Ian Black, who has resigned as the KIO's
treasurer and is to leave in June.
Mr Black has been a key figure in retaining the trust and confidence of the
international banking community in the KIO since the Iraqis were ejected
from Kuwait in early 1991.
He played a leading role in organising a Dollars 5.5bn loan to help
reconstruct the emirate after the Gulf war. He is also said to have helped
calm nervous bankers in recent months after a public investigation was
launched by the KIO's new management into alleged losses and fraud in
investments made by their predecessors in Spain.
The uproar surrounding this investigation, in which the KIO has refused to
honour some debts incurred by former managers, has worried some large
international banks.
Mr Black's departure is likely to coincide with a reduction in the power of
the KIO, headquartered in London. The Kuwaiti government is poised to
approve plans to merge the KIO into its younger Kuwait-based parent, the
Kuwait Investment Agency (KIA).
According to proposals by the Kuwaiti finance ministry, the new merged body
would be headed by Mr Ali Rashaid al-Bader, the new president of the KIO.
The merger would mean concentrating most decision-making power over Kuwaiti
investments back in Kuwait, a move some critics fear would open Kuwait's
finances to much greater political intervention.
Defenders of the plan say the KIA and the KIO already duplicate many of each
other's functions. If the merger does take place, a number of non-Kuwaiti
staff at the KIO in London are expected to be made redundant.
</TEXT>
