<DATE>930322
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / BBC World TV faces CNN attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC World Service Television is about to face a counter-attack from Mr Ted
Turner's CNN International.
The Atlanta-based international television news service has been surprised
by the speed with which the BBC's 24-hour television news service from
London has established itself.
In Asia, for instance, BBC World Service television is available in an
estimated 11m homes with up to 45m viewers 15 months after its launch on the
Star TV system in Hong Kong, a company set up by Hutchison Whampoa.
Mr Tom Johnson, president of CNN, concedes that in the past CNN
International has been too American in its coverage but that is all about to
change. He said: 'We intend to double our international broadcasting in a
single year.'
At present 40 per cent of CNN International's coverage is international and
the rest American orientated. The proportion of international coverage is to
be increased to 70 per cent by the end of this year.
A Dollars 10m development programme has been approved and there will be an
increasing trend to hiring international reporters such as Mr Brent Sadler,
formerly of Independent Television News in the UK, rather than sending
correspondents from the US.
Mr Johnson said: 'We intend to compete aggressively in all areas with the
BBC. He added that he had great respect for the quality of journalism
produced by the corporation.
'We will let the marketplace judge the results of our efforts,' said Mr
Johnson, who believes that there is room for both the CNN and BBC
approaches.
In the past three years there has been a dramatic increase in the
international distribution of CNN. Its service is now on 11 satellites and
there are few parts of the world where it cannot be received.
The BBC aims to span the world with a self-funding television equivalent of
World Service radio by the end of this year. Mr Christopher Irwin, chief
executive of WSTV, said: 'We are on course despite the world recession.'
The BBC strategy has been to set up in business with regional partners -
with the M-Net subscription TV service in Africa and the Nissho Iwai company
in Japan. Subscriptions for the 24-hour European service are handled by
TV-Extra, a subsidiary of Philips, the electronics group.
Mr Irwin said: 'We have witnessed a similar response to the Star TV channels
elsewhere in the continent from Taiwan to the Gulf, where BBC WSTV is
rebroadcast around the clock on a dedicated terrestrial channel owned by
Bahrain TV.'
Even Taiwan, which has strong US links, has a BBC audience of 2m - an
increase of 66 per cent in six months.
Mr Johnson reflects a little wistfully on the fact that CNN was approached
first by Star TV but the two sides were unable to agree a deal. 'We gave the
BBC the opportunity to compete,' he said.
</TEXT>
