<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / The Week Ahead: Results Due
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WELLCOME, the UK pharmaceuticals group, reports half-year results on
Thursday with analysts forecasting pre-tax profits of between Pounds 295m
and Pounds 325m against Pounds 244m a year earlier on sales of about Pounds
1bn.
Retrovir, the HIV-treatment, is expected to generate between Pounds 120m and
Pounds 140m, while estimates for sales of Zovirax, the herpes and chickenpox
medicine, range from Pounds 345m to Pounds 385m.
The main reason for the large range of forecasts is the impact of the dollar
in the US where Wellcome generates nearly half of its sales. Analysts will
be watching how the cough and cold season has progressed, given Wellcome's
non-prescription over the counter business is heavily geared towards
winter-type remedies.
Prudential, the insurer, is expected to report tomorrow a big jump in
pre-tax profits for the year of around Pounds 415m from Pounds 267m,
although forecasts range widely. A much improved second-half contribution
from the US and benefits flowing from the reorganisation of its UK
distribution network are two key factors.
Reckitt &amp; Colman, the food, household products and toiletries group, should
report on Thursday flat pre-tax profits for 1992 of around Pounds 250m.
P&amp;O, the shipping group, is forecast tomorrow to produce only a modest
increase of around Pounds 10m in pre-tax profits for 1992 from Pounds 217.4m
a year earlier.
Redland, the building materials group, similarly will manage on Thursday a
moderate profit increase of around Pounds 20m from Pounds 186m, including a
nine month contribution from Steetley.
Lasmo, the independent oil company, is expected by some analysts to cut its
final dividend on Wednesday despite an increase in profits to around Pounds
45m from Pounds 17.9m in 1991.
Bowater, the packaging and industrial films group, announces its 1992
results tomorrow.
It released estimated results, showing an unaudited pre-tax profit of Pounds
147m, a 48.5 per cent increase on 1991,last
month when it announced the Dollars 434m acquisition of Specialty Coatings
international, the US coatings company.
Argos, the catalogue retailer which this week announced the closure of its
four pilot Chesterman furniture stores because of disappointing sales,
presents its full-year results today. Forecasts range between Pounds 62m and
Pounds 66m, compared with last year's Pounds 62.1m.
These, however, do not include the Pounds 12.7m charge for the Chesterman
closure, which is expected to be taken as an exceptional item, and so reduce
pre-tax profits to the Pounds 50m to Pounds 54m range.
Full year results tomorrow from Invergordon Distillers, the independent
Scotch whisky producer, are likely to reflect the increased pressure on
margins in the bulk whisky market. After five years of strong growth,
pre-tax profits are expected to be virtually flat at Pounds 32.4m against
Pounds 32.2m in 1991.
Wolseley, the heating and plumbing supplier, is expected to announce mixed
results when it reveals interim profits tomorrow.
The company is expected to reveal pre-tax profits up more than 20 per cent
to Pounds 40m-Pounds 42m in the six months to end-January. Profits from the
US east coast and the UK are likely to be strongly ahead, although results
from California and France could be disappointing because of recession.
