<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / International Company News: State to float majority stake in
Dutch telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DUTCH government has decided to sell a majority stake in the state
telecom company PTT, ending months of speculation over what proportion of
the company would be privatised, Reuter reports.
The first tranche of the flotation will be offered to the public next year.
The exact amount to be sold, who will arrange and underwrite the offer and
what level the company will be valued at remain the subject of debate,
financial sources said.
But at an estimated total value of Fl 15bn (Dollars 8bn), the fight for rich
adviser fees is under way. Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank, was named
adviser to the company at the end of January. Dutch, British and US firms
head the field of contenders for the more lucrative underwriting and
co-ordinating roles.
PTT will have to jockey for postition in an already-crowded European
privatisation calendar. In addition to the third tranche of British Telecom,
PTT is competing against several at least three other groups, including
Germany's Deutsche Bundespost Telekom and Sweden's Procordia.
</TEXT>
