<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / CrossRail bill may be reactivated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BILL authorising construction of the Pounds 2bn CrossRail link, the
biggest public transport project planned for central London, is expected to
be reactivated soon after Easter as the government seeks to counter
accusations that it is trying to shelve the scheme.
Last week the chancellor said, in his Budget speech, the project would be
re-examined as a candidate for private sector finance as part of the
government's attempt to attract more private funding for transport
infrastructure projects. This gave rise to fears of long delays for the
scheme because it had previously been agreed that it would be funded wholly
by the public sector.
But the CrossRail bill, dormant since its introduction to the House of
Commons last year, is now likely to be reactivated and given a second
reading in May.
The underground British Rail link between Paddington station on the western
side of the capital and Liverpool Street on the eastern side would enable
thousands of commuters to travel beyond the two terminuses to the West End
and the City without changing to London Underground's overcrowded trains.
At the end of last week, the Corporation of London, the City's governing
body, published a strongly worded report pouring cold water on the idea of
getting private funding into CrossRail and other projects. A co-author of
the report, Mr Stephen Glaister of the London School of Economics, said:
'There is a real danger that waiting for private sector finance to dig this
project out of a financial hole risks losing it altogether.'
Department of Transport officials yesterday emphasised that the Budget
restated the government's commitment to the project and said the Pounds 200m
allocated to preliminary work on the scheme over the next three years
remained in place.
Crosstown traffic, Page 12
