<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / US battles to hold share of Japanese chip market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KONA, HAWAII
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US-Japan battle over semiconductor trade is not over yet, in spite of
the surprise announcement on Friday that the long-sought US target of a 20
per cent foreign share of the Dollars 20bn (Pounds 14bn) Japanese
semiconductor market had finally been achieved.
The US is now pressing Japan for continued improvement in foreign access to
its semiconductor market by maintaining an average 20 per cent foreign
market share over the next 12 months.
Japanese officials said, however, that they would 'reject out of hand' any
suggestions for further quantitative measures of market access. As trade
officials and industry representatives from both countries gathered in
Hawaii for semiconductor trade talks that began yesterday, it was evident
that sharp differences remained which could have important implications for
trade relations in this and other sectors.
Officials from both countries were surprised by Friday's announcement that
the foreign share of the Japanese microchip market was 20.2 per cent in the
fourth quarter of 1992, a 4.3 percentage point jump from the previous
quarter.
Although the market share rise alleviated trade tension, it also raised new
questions about the use of market share as a quantifiable indicator of
market access.
Japan has always vigorously denied that the 1986 semiconductor agreement
guaranteed foreign chip manufacturers a fifth of the Japanese market.
The Japanese government's resistance to further use of market share data has
been hardened by US suggestions that a similar approach might be applied in
other sectors.
However, the sharp increase in the foreign share of the Japanese chip market
in the fourth quarter could be explained more by economic conditions in
Japan than by the significant increase in foreign semiconductor sales. US
officials acknowledge that the size of the Japanese semiconductor market
declined drastically.
