<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: UK insurance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Lamont also held out a little noticed but juicy carrot for the UK
insurance industry. Insurers have long argued for the right to set aside
tax-deductible general reserves against unspecified future losses. The
Budget gave them cause for celebration by promising a consultation paper on
the issue. Swings in profits caused by natural catastrophes could be ironed
out by such equalisation reserves. European insurers enjoy a competitive
advantage in the London market by being allowed to create them.
Yet there is plenty of scope for disappointment in the fine print.
Equalisation reserves would be of little value if they were restricted to
minor classes of business. The big gains would flow from reserves against
future losses on property and household accounts. Only then would
shareholders funds be protected from hurricanes or deep recessions. If the
government and the Inland Revenue are prepared to go that far, insurance
companies may be more inclined to maintain dividends through the cycle and
the sector would be a less volatile investment.
The industry will still have to argue its case. Smoothing profits goes
against the grain of recent UK accounting reforms. The continental practice
of setting up general reserves discourages transparency. Insurance companies
which are free to reserve to the hilt on the upswing may also be tempted to
write bad business in difficult markets. Far from smoothing the insurance
cycle, equalisation reserves would then only add to the problem.
</TEXT>
