<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Statistics chief seeks business links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BILL McLENNAN, head of the Government Statistical Service, is looking for
ways to improve the data it can offer government departments and businesses.
An internal inquiry into the operations of the service is trying to find and
fill gaps in the provision of data.
Mr McLennan wants the service to form stronger links with the business
world, mainly because he believes better business contacts will focus
statisticians' minds on data that other people find useful. He also wants
the service to examine ways to gain more finance via private-sector sales.
The investigation covers the statistical work of about 30 Whitehall
departments and has been ordered by Mr McLennan.
The study, due to be completed by the end of this year, is likely to focus
on specific items of data that could be sold to companies, either directly
by the government or through private-sector statistical agencies.
The statistical service, which employs about 5,000 people, of whom 700 are
statisticians, has an annual budget of about Pounds 120m, virtually all of
which is met from public funds.
The service co-ordinates the statistical work of officials in a range of
government departments including health, transport, social security,
employment, trade and industry and defence.
The inquiry is likely to focus on ways to:
Obtain from different government departments statistics that relate to
specific regions of the UK, for instance in the field or housing or
environmental issues.
Allow individual departments to pool more of their data, for example to
determine the statistical links between areas such as unemployment and
health.
Use computers and telecommunications more effectively to channel data
between government departments and users.
Bring together in an accessible form specific kinds of data of interest to
the business world.
Link sources of statistics in the UK more closely with those in other parts
of Europe to enable a better comparison of broad trends in areas such as
transport or social security.
Identify new surveys which might be needed to plug gaps in knowledge, for
instance concerning the service industry which is less well monitored than
manufacturing.
Mr McLennan, an Australian who was appointed to the GSS just over a year
ago, has recently won the approval of ministers to redirect the work of the
service to make its work more relevant to companies as well as to other
parts of the government.
He is also director of the Central Statistical Office, which is mainly
concerned with economic data and answers to the Treasury. He has introduced
more rigorous procedures in the CSO to reduce leaks of sensitive economic
information.
</TEXT>
