<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Baltic rises from wreckage: The return of trading to the
bombed exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING at London's historic Baltic Exchange resumes early next month, just
less than a year after an IRA bomb wrecked the London shipping market's
headquarters.
The Baltic has emerged from the disaster - in which three people were killed
and dozens injured - as a much smaller institution. Managers have been
forced to slash the scale of back-up operations it provides, reducing staff
by two thirds.
Complete restoration of the 91-year-old, grade 2 listed building - one of
the City's best known landmarks - could take a further three years.
Mr Jim Buckley, the Baltic's chief executive, says, 'It has not been an
entirely happy experience. In fact it has been a nightmare.'
Mr Buckley took seven months to negotiate a Pounds 27.6m insurance
settlement. Although there is enough money to cover repair work and many
other costs, Mr Buckley says the insurance was insufficient to cover the
entire cost of the disrupt-ion.
The ordeal started last April when the building's facade took the full force
of the bomb blast. Pieces of Swedish granite and carved Portland stone were
hurled through the building's lavish interior. Steel columns clad in Italian
and Greek marble, nine glass domes, including a central dome 40ft in
diameter, moulded bronze chandeliers, stained-glass windows and a 23,000 sq
ft Rhodesian walnut trading floor all sustained heavy damage.
Ironically, trading was barely affected. Brokers who buy and sell space on
ships for bulk cargoes ranging from oil to phosphate, and from grain to
sugar, improvised in the first few days after the explosion and within a
week had rented alternative premises at the nearby Lloyd's of London
insurance market.
Mr Buckley says it was merely a 'hiccup' in trading, which generates about
Dollars 1.4bn a year in commission income.
However, the impact on the exchange, its staff and the small businesses
associated with it has been far more severe. Because so many of the small
offices surrounding the trading floor were destroyed, the exchange's annual
income of Pounds 5m a year was immediately halved by the loss of Pounds 2.5m
a year in rent.
'We have been out of the building a lot longer than we had expected,' Mr
Buckley says. 'The insurance wasn't going to cover all our costs.' He has
set aside Pounds 7 1/2 m of the Pounds 27.6m settlement to meet that loss
over the next three years. A further Pounds 1m covered the cost of a year's
rental income at Lloyd's, while the immediate clean-up and refurbishment
have cost about Pounds 3m. That leaves just Pounds 15m to carry out
essential rebuilding work, and although the sum will be enough to restore
the building to grade 2 status, there will be insufficient cash to rebuild
the 110,000 sq ft of office space.
'We have had to husband our resources carefully on behalf of our members,'
says Mr Buckley, who was forced to dismiss 100 of the exchange's 150 staff
last May. Many of the small businesses which surrounded the exchange - the
Italian sandwich shop next door, the wine bar and the restaurants, and the
gym in the basement - have little hope of being re-established.
'There is a bitter and human side of the story,' Mr Buckley concludes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
