FT  22 MAR 93 / Straw seeks fresh line on clause IV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW approach by the Labour party to public ownership is urged today in a
pamphlet by Mr Jack Straw, a senior shadow cabinet member.
Mr Straw's call to revise clause IV of the Labour party's constitution,
which deals with 'common ownership', has already re-ignited the controversy
between the traditionalists and modernisers in the party, outraging some
leftwing MPs.
Mr Straw said on London Weekend Television's Walden programme yesterday: 'We
may perhaps conclude that the reluctance to bite this particular bullet
speaks volumes for our timidity, our lack of confidence in our beliefs.'
Party officials said that although Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, had
made it clear that he regarded a debate about clause IV as an unnecessary
diversion from Labour's main task, he was relaxed about Mr Straw's wish to
stimulate discussion on the issue.
Mr Straw argued that when clause IV was written about 75 years ago Labour
was seeking an alternative to laissez-faire capitalism, and that its
economic analysis had to change in the light of the failure of Marxist-based
economies.
'At the heart of what Labour stands for is the conviction that the market
must be made to work for the people,' Mr Straw said. No Labour manifesto had
ever said that the way of increasing prosperity was to nationalise
everything.
