<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Auditing role urged for non-executive directors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORPORATE boards should establish audit committees composed exclusively of
non-executive directors, say guidelines published today by Pro Ned, the
organisation which promotes the role of non-executive directors and which is
backed by the Bank of England.
The recommendations are similar to those adopted last year by the Cadbury
committee on the financial aspects of corporate governance. The guidelines
were adopted in consultation with Pro Ned's sponsors, who include the Stock
Exchange, the Institutional Shareholders Committee and the Confederation of
British Industry.
Pro Ned says board-level audit committees should be responsible for ensuring
that a company's financial and accounting systems provide accurate and
up-to-date information, that the financial statements give a true and fair
picture of its position, and that the external audit is conducted in a
thorough manner.
External auditors should be able to meet privately with the audit committee
at least once a year to enable the auditors to raise unresolved issues of
concern, the guidelines say. Also, the full board should circulate a
resolution authorising the committee to ensure that senior and middle
managers understand and accept the nature and purposes of the committee.
The audit committee's functions should include reviewing half-year and
annual financial statements before they go to the board, and reviewing
statements issued at the time of a rights issue, an acquisition or a bid
defence.
Guidelines on Audit Committees. Pro Ned, 1 Kingsway, London WC2B 6XF. Pounds
10.
</TEXT>
