<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Power chiefs hold out on coal deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEADS of several regional electricity companies said last night that
they were still unwilling to sign deals to buy coal until the government
published its white paper on the future of the coal industry. The government
has said it wants the deals signed before the white paper.
After a weekend of talks in the coal and electricity industries there was
continuing uncertainty about whether the government could publish its coal
white paper before the Easter parliamentary recess.
British Coal executives and the electricity companies said considerable
progress had been made in the talks on contracts which will replace those
ending this month. Most outstanding differences were resolved.
Senior executives at the corporation are resigned to the uncertainty over
the industry's future continuing for several months after it emerged on
Friday that the white paper would not include details of deals for coal
additional to those for 'base contracts' which were the subject of the
weekend negotiations.
One corporation executive said: 'The white paper will not be the end of the
story, just a further stage in the process. We still hope to keep some pits
open but how many is uncertain.' The best guess is that fewer than 10 of the
31 pits will be kept in the corporation's ownership, although several more
may be leased to the private sector.
At the weekend outstanding issues between the two generating companies and
some of the regional distribution companies were resolved without the need
to resort to binding arbitration. British Coal and the generators also
settled most remaining differences.
Even if the government and the electricity companies resolve their dispute
over whether signing the deals or publishing the white paper should come
first, ministers have a tight timetable if they want to publish this week.
Some electricity companies said yesterday they were prepared to sign
contracts before the white paper if the government provided written
guarantees on several issues.
Regional companies want to be sure the government does not alter its
timetable for liberalising the electricity supply market. The generators are
seeking assurances that they will not be forced to sell generating plant
they no longer want to operate.
Several companies said the detail of the contracts, most of which are more
than 200 pages long, meant that signing before the end of the week would be
impossible even if the assurances were provided.
One chief executive said last night he was strongly against signing before
the white paper was published. He would be consulting with other companies,
and this would affect how firm a stance he would take, but 'in any case we
cannot sign by Thursday'.
That is the day the cabinet meets and the first opportunity the government
is likely to have to publish the white paper.
</TEXT>
