<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / Miners struggle to find paydirt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL Enterprise, founded to create jobs in coalfield areas, has
launched a research project to discover how more ex-miners can be turned
into successful businessmen.
'Our view is miners don't make very good entrepreneurs. They make good
employees,' said northern regional BCE manager Mr Roland Stevenson.
With hundreds of miners leaving the industry each week and more pit closures
looming, BCE is working with Durham University Business School to study how
suitable ex-miners would be for a career in business. Mr Stevenson said the
aim of the Durham study was to see 'if there is something hidden we can
bring out'.
Since its formation in 1984, BCE claims to have been highly successful in
placing former miners in new employment and helping coalfield companies,
through financial support, to create more jobs.
But its experience helping them become entrepreneurs has been more mixed. Of
the relatively small number who have opted for self-employment, few have
created substantial businesses and some have failed, losing their redundancy
money.
As part of the research, co-funded by the Department of Trade and Industry,
BCE has started running pilot one-day workshops in north-east England and
the Midlands, in which ex-miners planning self-employment undergo
psychometric analysis and behaviour studies. The sessions are intended to
gauge personality traits such as goal orientation, leadership, communication
skills, the ability to thrive under pressure and willingness to take risks.
The research is also assessing a selection of companies in Durham and
Bristol to identify which qualities in the person at the helm have
contributed to their survival.
Since 1985 the number of miners employed by British Coal has dropped from
191,000 to 33,000. BCE estimates that of 27,207 ex-employees, including
miners and white-collar staff, whom it has resettled since 1987, 2,070 have
become self-employed. It does not know how many are still in business.
Ex-British Coal employees no longer in business include Mr Michael Peary of
Pegswood, Northumberland. His British Gnome Stores at the Gateshead Metro
Centre, which opened in the late 1980s and did a brisk trade in Thatcher
gnomes, closed a year ago. Mr Peary was reluctant to discuss his experience
but said: 'There were quite a few of us at the time went into
self-employment. As far as I know there's none of us self-employed now.'
</TEXT>
