<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / French Elections: Election arouses little excitement among
voters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Francois Albert, a retired building worker, has voted Socialist all his
life and sees no reason to stop now. 'I'm not saying this government has
been perfect, but at least they've done their best,' he said yesterday after
casting his vote in the first round of the French parliamentary elections at
the town hall of the 4th arrondissement in Paris.
'The polls say the right will win this time. Maybe they will. What will
happen to pensioners like me then?'
Mr Albert, like the rest of the French electorate, will probably find out
next Sunday after the second and final round of voting in the elections.
The atmosphere in Paris yesterday was as downbeat as the rest of the
campaign. French law imposes rigorous restrictions on electoral publicity.
Candidates may not spend more than FFr500,000 (Pounds 63,000) on their
campaigns and there are other tight curbs in force for the six months before
the vote.
The tourists milling around Paris yesterday in the spring sunshine could
have been forgiven for not realising an election was in progress. There were
none of the blockbuster advertising campaigns that mark US elections, nor
the eager canvassers who badger voters outside many other European polling
stations.
The only signs of the French vote were a few fly posters, odd splashes of
graffiti and the billboards of smiling candidates pasted up outside town
halls.
Moreover, the tone of the campaign, the 10th parliamentary polls in the
Fifth Republic, has been subdued even by French standards. The apparently
inevitable conservative landslide, coupled with President Francois
Mitterrand's determination to stay on at the Elysee Palace until the 1995
presidential poll, has sapped the electorate's enthusiasm.
'All the parties are as bad as each other,' said Mr Alexandre Mercier, a
young shop assistant, voting in the 4th arrondissement. 'The left is
useless. The right is useless too. I've voted for the ecologists, not
because I believe in them but because I can't stand the rest.'
Even conservative voters were unenthusiastic. 'I've voted conservative
because the sooner the left goes the better,' said an elderly woman. 'But
nothing will really change in France until that man Mitterrand goes too.'
Some are so disillusioned they are not bothering to vote at all. Mr Francis
Bertaux and Mr Patrick Miller, two designers in the Marais area of Paris,
abstained yesterday and plan to skip the second round of voting next Sunday
in favour of spending the evening at the Matisse exhibition in the Georges
Pompidou Centre.
'We don't believe in any of the parties,' said Mr Miller. 'Everyone will be
at glued to their televisions at home next Sunday, watching the final
results. It'll be our only chance to see the Matisse show without the usual
crowds.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
