<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 93 / French Elections: Shocked ecologists see hopes collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE unexpected victims of yesterday's right-wing landslide were the two
ecology parties, which received a possibly terminal blow to their hopes of
becoming a force in national politics.
According to early exit polls, Les Verts and Generation Ecologie pulled in a
mere 8.5 per cent of the votes. That is around half of their score at the
peak of their popularity at the turn of the year and well below the nearly
14 per cent they recorded in regional elections a year ago. As the count
continued, it looked as if their first-round score could fall below 8 per
cent, at which level they would win no seats. Their fate questions the
commonly held belief that the Green movement was the main beneficiary of the
Socialists' decline.
'A crushing majority (for the right) would bury France in concrete,' mourned
Mr Antoine Waechter, leader of Les Verts, the more hardline of the ecology
pair. He called on his election candidates to fight on to the second round
'however few in number'. He claimed the Greens had been victims of
'political manoeuvres and false candidatures'. The one positive element in
yesterday's setback was that 'ecology was a confirmed part of the French
political landscape', he claimed.
His partner, Mr Brice Lalonde, a former Socialist environment minister, was
less cheerful. The result was a 'disappointment' due partly to France's
majority voting system and partly to the fact that other political groups
had sought to steal the Green vote.
Pre-election polls had shown that support for ecologists lay in what had
been traditional Socialist territory - the young, graduates, middle managers
and religious agnostics. Many observers believed the two parties' decision
to make an electoral pact, as Entente des Ecologistes, after months of
wrangling, would help them build on last year's regional election success.
However, the pact failed to reconcile splits on a whole series of issues,
from nuclear power to the strategy to adopt with a new government - a
failure which appears to have sapped their credibility.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
